headline: Review: In ‘The Last Family,’ a Polish Artist’s Tragic Home Life
summary_short: The difficult family life of the Polish painter Zdzislaw Beksinski makes for an often funny but also harrowing and heartbreaking film.

headline: Review: ‘Legion of Brothers’ on Secret Missions in Afghanistan
summary_short: This documentary tells the stories of Green Berets who were sent to topple the Taliban immediately after the Sept. 11 terrorist attacks.

headline: Review: ‘Speed Sisters,’ Revving to Go in the West Bank
summary_short: This documentary centers on the challenges faced by five young women who make up the first female streetcar racing team in the Middle East.

headline: Review: In ‘The Salesman,’ Scenes From a Marriage in Tehran
summary_short: The ghost of Willy Loman hovers over this film from Asghar Farhadi, but it seems occupied with its own dramatic issues, our critic writes.

headline: Review: Shah Rukh Khan as ‘Raees,’ a Villain but Still a Do-Gooder
summary_short: The “king of Bollywood” rarely plays the bad guy, but in this film he’s a criminal who’s also fighting corruption in 1980s and ’90s India.

headline: Review: A Long-Buried Family Secret Explodes in ‘The Daughter’
summary_short: This drama, set in a declining Australian logging town, centers on an estranged son who comes home, smoldering with resentment.

headline: Review: Alice Returns in ‘Resident Evil: The Final Chapter’
summary_short: In the sixth entry in Paul W. S. Anderson’s dystopian franchise, Milla Jovovich’s character is back in zombie land, aided by her former nemesis the Red Queen.

headline: Review: Climate Change and Conflicts in ‘The Age of Consequences’
summary_short: Jared P. Scott’s film explores the issue from the perspective of military experts rather than that of scientists. The information is compelling, but the movie is ham-handed.

headline: Review: ‘Kung Fu Yoga’ Features Jackie Chan Saving the Day
summary_short: Mr. Chan mugs and thwarts assailants in this harmless international romp.

headline: Review: ‘Lost in Florence’ Blends Romantic Fantasy and a Rough Sport
summary_short: Evan Oppenheimer’s film is a mild romantic drama with a guy perspective, featuring beautiful women and a brutal athletic spectacle.

headline: Review: ‘Midsummer in Newtown’ Revisits the Pain of Sandy Hook
summary_short: This documentary explores the value of a Shakespeare production intended to help residents heal after the horrific school shooting.

headline: Review: Matthew McConaughey Mines Profane Capitalism in ‘Gold’
summary_short: He plays a rogue who strikes it rich, a thrill complicated by the corruptions of wealth, treachery and the schemer’s own fecklessness.

headline: Review: ‘A Dog’s Purpose,’ With Many Lives and Many Clichés
summary_short: This film, opening amid a call for a PETA boycott, is a string of hero-dog fantasies and observations from the canine point of view.

headline: Review: ‘Saving Banksy’ Affirms Graffiti’s Populist Values
summary_short: This documentary honors the street-based work of the British artist known as Banksy, and implicitly criticizes those who would try to turn profits from it.

headline: Review: M. Night Shyamalan’s ‘Split’ Has Personality. O.K., Personalities. Lots.
summary_short: “Split” represents something of a return to form — or formula — for its writer and director, M. Night Shyamalan. It’s all plot, spun into a ribbon of suspense.

headline: Review: ‘The Red Turtle,’ Life Marooned With an Ornery Reptile
summary_short: This largely nonverbal animated French-Belgian-Japanese coproduction, from Studio Ghibli, the home of Hayao Miyazaki, flirts with eco-mysticism.

headline: Review: The French Countryside Holds Surprises in ‘Staying Vertical’
summary_short: In Alain Guiraudie’s quirky hybrid of thriller, sex comedy and folk tale, a screenwriter meets a shepherdess and, voilà, a baby is born.

headline: Review: Turning the World On, the LSD Way, in ‘The Sunshine Makers’
summary_short: Cosmo Feilding Mellen’s documentary suggests that two young men saw themselves as spreading transcendence one hit at a time.

headline: Review: ‘XXX: Return of Xander Cage’ Deploys Vin Diesel on a New Mission
summary_short: In the third installment of this franchise, the hero and new oddball allies set out to retrieve a stolen superweapon.

headline: Review: Cannibalism, Torture and Apocalypse in ‘We Are the Flesh’
summary_short: This debut feature by the Mexican writer and director Emiliano Rocha Minter seems to build on the character of Coffin Joe in the 1960s films by José Mojica Marins.

headline: Review: ‘The Founder,’ the Story of a Supersize Businessman
summary_short: Mr. Keaton’s kinetic performance as the man who made McDonald’s what it is today doesn’t enhance the movie; it is the movie.

headline: Review: ‘Sleepless,’ but No Need to Reach for the Sominex
summary_short: This entry in the dad-to-the-rescue action-movie genre doesn’t have enough twists to even tie a shoelace.

headline: Review: Horses Under the Hood? In ‘Monster Trucks,’ Try a Cephalopod
summary_short: A small-town teenager and a creature released by a geyser are unlikely friends in this live-action eco-fable from the “Ice Age” director Chris Wedge.

headline: Review: ‘Reset’ Follows Benjamin Millepied’s Efforts to Rejuvenate Paris Opera Ballet
summary_short: The job didn’t work out in the end, but this riveting film documents a choreographer’s cheerfully tenacious effort as well as his work on one ballet.

headline: Review: ‘The Son of Joseph’ Fancifully Repackages the Nativity
summary_short: Eugène Green’s new movie is divided into five sections, each titled after a biblical episode.

headline: Review: A Husband Vanishes in ‘Claire in Motion.’ Mysteries Multiply.
summary_short: In this film, the latest written and directed by Lisa Robinson and Annie J. Howell, a wife searches for clues and finds larger unanswered questions.

headline: Review: ‘Bad Kids of Crestview Academy’ Brings Blood to Detention
summary_short: Prep-school students in Saturday detention are trapped on campus to die one by one in this film directed by Ben Browder, a sequel to “Bad Kids Go to Hell.”

headline: Review: ‘The Bye Bye Man,’ Oddly Overstaying His Welcome
summary_short: This movie melds the summon-the-evil-by-its-name convention with the old try-not-to-think-of-an-elephant mind game, with scary results.

headline: Review: ‘100 Streets,’ Where an Ex-Jock, a Cabby and a Thug Struggle
summary_short: Idris Elba is among the stars of this Jim O’Hanlon film, a converging-narratives movie set in London.

headline: Review: ‘One Piece Film: Gold,’ a Frantic Hunt for Pirate Loot
summary_short: This entry in the “One Piece” anime franchise involves the liberation of gamblers on a floating casino complex.

headline: Review: ‘Underworld: Blood Wars,’ Bathed in Blue and Partied Out
summary_short: This action-horror franchise about warring vampires and werewolves returns for a fifth outing. But is it a sequel or a dissertation?

headline: Review: In ‘The Ardennes,’ a Freed Convict Returns Home to a New Reality
summary_short: Robin Pront’s film depicts a man who took the fall for a crime and who catches up with his brother and his girlfriend, now reformed and in a relationship, four years later.

headline: Review: ‘Arsenal’ Finds Nicolas Cage as a Criminal, Not Playing Nice
summary_short: This movie, directed by Steven C. Miller, follows two brothers under pressure by a crime boss in Mississippi.

headline: Review: It’s Slick, but ‘Master’ Is No James Bond Movie
summary_short: The bloat of this routine South Korean crime thriller, directed by Cho Ui-seok, magnifies its generic qualities.

headline: Review: ‘Railroad Tigers’ Features a Resourceful Jackie Chan
summary_short: Mr. Chan, 62, dazzles in this action movie set during the Second Sino-Japanese War, but the most challenging moves are left to younger stuntmen.

headline: Review: 1 Teenage Boy and 3 Mothers in ‘20th Century Women’
summary_short: Annette Bening stars as a complicated and divorced Santa Barbara mother in Mike Mills’s funny, emotionally piercing new film.

headline: Review: He Pledges Allegiance Only to His Tommy Gun, in ‘Live by Night’
summary_short: Ben Affleck directed and stars in this gangster movie set in the 1920s, in which he tries to pour new wine into a bullet-riddled vessel.

headline: Review: Questions and Prayers Go Unanswered in Scorsese’s ‘Silence’
summary_short: In Martin Scorsese’s film, Jesuit priests in 17th-century Japan operate underground to keep their religion alive when they and their adherents are persecuted.

headline: Review: ‘Hidden Figures’ Honors 3 Black Women Who Helped NASA Soar
summary_short: The women, part of the giant step for mankind, have their stories told in this movie directed by Theodore Melfi.

headline: Review: ‘A Monster Calls,’ Offering a Boy a Lifeline
summary_short: Liam Neeson is the voice of a giant tree that helps a child with a vivid imagination through difficult times.

headline: Review: ‘Patriots Day,’ a Mosaic of Portraits From Marathon Bombing
summary_short: This film declines to consider the jihadist ideology that apparently motivated the Boston Marathon bombers.

display_title: Breaking Point: The War for Democracy in Ukraine
headline: Review: ‘Breaking Point’ Finds Fake News and Real Violence in Ukraine
summary_short: The documentary, directed by Mark Jonathan Harris and Oles Sanin, looks at Russian aggression toward the country, which is struggling to rebuild.

headline: Review: ‘Liza, Liza, Skies Are Grey’ Seems Out of Step With Its Period
summary_short: Teenagers on the run, with a motorcycle, and hints of the 1960s.

headline: Review: In ‘Get Out,’ Guess Who’s Coming to Dinner? (Bad Idea!)
summary_short: This movie by Jordan Peele, his first as a director of feature films, is a skillful hybrid, blending genres into something terrifying.

headline: Review: ‘Dying Laughing,’ About Bombing Onstage, or, Conversely, Killing
summary_short: Paul Toogood and Lloyd Stanton’s documentary talks to comedians about the rigors of the road and other stresses of their profession.

headline: Review: In ‘As You Are,’ a Nod to Nirvana, and a Loaded Gun
summary_short: Two teenage boys in the 1990s bond over alt-rock only to have their friendship strained in this first feature directed by Miles Joris-Peyrafitte.

headline: Review: ‘Bitter Harvest’ Offers a Clunky Lesson in Ukrainian History
summary_short: Prettily filmed yet parochial, this film follows two lovers through a mass starvation in the early 1930s.

headline: Review: In ‘Paraguay Remembered,’ Does Time Heal All Wounds?
summary_short: This documentary reflects on a legacy of political turmoil as the director, Dominique Dubosc, returns to Paraguay after 40 years.

headline: Review: ‘My Life as a Zucchini,’ an Oscar Nominee With Depth and Soul
summary_short: This animated tale of an orphan, freighted with the name Icare, or Icarus, is more charming than grim.

headline: Review: Guard the Sheep? He’d Rather Be a ‘Rock Dog’
summary_short: An animated movie for children is elevated by a fine vocal performance from Eddie Izzard.

headline: Review: Immigrants ‘From Nowhere,’ Anxiously Living Under the Radar
summary_short: Julianne Nicholson plays a Bronx high school teacher who tries to help three undocumented students cope with the threat of being discovered by the authorities.

headline: Review: Two Friends Dance a Wary Tango in ‘Lovesong’
summary_short: The movie, directed by So Yong Kim, explores the mystery of unspoken love.

headline: Review: Ice Cube and Charlie Day Face Off in ‘Fist Fight’
summary_short: It’s the last day of school, and two teachers are getting ready to rumble in this comedy directed by Richie Keen.

headline: Review: ‘American Fable,’ Pastoral With a Wolf Howling
summary_short: Anne Hamilton’s film seems full of suspenseful promise as it opens on an isolated swath of the country’s heartland, but the story finds no traction.

headline: Review: In ‘How Heavy This Hammer,’ Life Takes a Toll on Dad
summary_short: Written and directed by Kazik Radwanski, this film was shot in practically all hand-held almost close-ups.

headline: Review: An Anti-Semite Learns of His Jewish Roots in ‘Keep Quiet’
summary_short: This documents how the career of the far-right Hungarian politician Csanad Szegedi was upended when he found out about his lineage.

headline: Review: Saving Dad, and Finding Herself, in ‘My Name Is Emily’
summary_short: Evanna Lynch, of “Harry Potter,” plays a teenager who leaves her foster home to search for her institutionalized father.

headline: Review: ‘Everybody Loves Somebody,’ a Rom-Com With Bite
summary_short: A messed-up heroine is asked to choose between naughty and nice in Catalina Aguilar Mastretta’s sophomore feature, which is predictable but satisfying.

headline: Review: Matt Damon Battles Clusters of Monsters in ‘The Great Wall’
summary_short: Zhang Yimou’s costume spectacle offers drooling creatures, glowering warriors, a swaggering mercenary and a message about China’s might.

headline: Review: ‘A Cure for Wellness’ Is a Riot of Film References. With Eels.
summary_short: This thriller from Gore Verbinski makes for a nice game of Name That Movie Influence as it treads the boundary between homage and outright plagiarism.

headline: Review: Cute Cats of ‘Kedi,’ Rekindling a ‘Love of Life’
summary_short: This documentary profiles distinctive street cats in Istanbul and the human communities that interact with them.

headline: Review: ‘A United Kingdom’ With Love That Tested Racial Tolerance
summary_short: This romance illustrates the struggle for African independence from colonialism, under the shadow of apartheid.

headline: Review: ‘I Am Jane Doe’ Takes Aim at Escort Ads
summary_short: This documentary is a chronicle of the fight to hold an online classifieds site liable for children being sold into sex slavery.

headline: Review: ‘Don’t Hang Up’ Has a Menace on the Line
summary_short: This formulaic horror movie features teenagers behaving badly and suffering the consequences.

headline: Review: ‘Eagles of Death Metal’ Revisits the Paris Terror Attack
summary_short: Colin Hanks’s documentary follows the band that was playing at the Bataclan in Paris when terrorists struck in 2015.

headline: Review: ‘Fifty Shades Darker,’ and Only Half as Watchable
summary_short: Will moviegoers want to surrender control to this sequel to “Fifty Shades of Grey”?

headline: Review: ‘The Island Funeral’ Goes on a Restless Road Trip
summary_short: This second feature by the Thai director Pimpaka Towira finds three young adults on an enigmatic journey.

headline: Review: ‘John Wick: Chapter 2,’ a Roman Holiday With Shots Not Sparks
summary_short: This sequel is an altogether more solemn affair than the original, weighed down by the philosophy that more is always more.

headline: Review: ‘Left on Purpose’ Follows a Man Who Plans to Kill Himself
summary_short: This documentary focuses on Mayer Vishner, a man who has decided to end his life, and finds the filmmaker in an uncomfortable position.

headline: Review: In ‘1 Night,’ a Hotel, 2 Couples, a Bad Prom and a Reckoning
summary_short: This debut feature by Minhal Baig has two high school students, a couple in their 30s and a dash of charm.

headline: Review: In ‘The Lego Batman Movie,’ Toys and Heroes, What’s Not to Like?
summary_short: Warner Bros. offers amusement at its own expense and Will Arnett gives great voice to Gotham’s brooder, but this new movie is still a commercial.

headline: Review: In ‘Rings,’ Best Not Go to the Videotape
summary_short: The latest in a horror franchise that began in Japan, this film fills in the back story of Samara, the girl who kills via VCR.

headline: Review: ‘I Am Not Your Negro’ Will Make You Rethink Race
summary_short: Raoul Peck’s documentary is an important introduction to James Baldwin’s work and an advanced seminar in racial politics.

headline: Review: ‘This Is Everything: Gigi Gorgeous,’ a Self-Made Cover Girl
summary_short: Barbara Kopple’s film documents how Gigi Gorgeous, formerly Gregory Allan Lazzarato, took control of her transgender destiny with the support of her family.

headline: Review: ‘Eloise’ Has the Usual Haunted-Hospital Clichés
summary_short: Robert Legato’s horror movie is “a strange mix of the recycled and the surreal,” Jeannette Catsoulis writes.

headline: Review: In ‘A Good American,’ Examining Sept. 11 and Data Collection
summary_short: Friedrich Moser’s documentary employs re-enactments, moving graphics and a Philip Glass-like score.

headline: Review: ‘Growing Up Smith’ Plants a Boy From India in 1979 America
summary_short: This gentle coming-of-age film centers on a youngster caught between two cultures and struggling to adapt in suburbia.

headline: Review: ‘The Space Between Us,’ the Story of a Boy Who Fell to Earth
summary_short: Peter Chelsom’s movie concerns a young human (Asa Butterfield), raised in isolation on Mars, who visits Earth and a video-chat pal (Britt Robertson).

headline: Review: Robert De Niro as ‘The Comedian,’ a Has-Been Seeking a Comeback
summary_short: Joined by a cast that includes Edie Falco and Harvey Keitel, Mr. De Niro plays an insult comic in a film that, like its jokes, lacks zing.

headline: Review: ‘Mr. Gaga’ Doesn’t Sing but Has His Own (Dance) Language
summary_short: Tomer Heymann’s documentary on the Israeli choreographer Ohad Naharin is a scattered and somewhat confused film about an intriguing and complicated man.

headline: Review: ‘After Auschwitz’ Looks at Six Survivors and Their Lives
summary_short: The documentary traces the experiences of six women who settled in the United States after the end of World War II.

headline: Review: ‘Five Came Back,’ and Inspired the Likes of Spielberg
summary_short: A screen adaptation of Mark Harris’s 2014 book adds visuals to the story of five Hollywood directors who served in World War II with cameras in tow.

headline: Review: In ‘Ghost in the Shell,’ a Cyborg With Soul
summary_short: Scarlett Johansson, playing a cyborg called Major, rises above it all in the thrill-free science fiction thriller.

headline: Review: ‘All This Panic,’ a Cinematic Confidant of Teenage Girls
summary_short: This limber, light-footed documentary becomes a sort of dreamy film diary for the girls it profiles.

headline: Review: ‘The Boss Baby’ Puts Alec Baldwin in Diapers, Sort Of
summary_short: An animated feature starring a newborn with an oh-so-familiar voice may confuse the kiddies, but grown-ups should get a kick out of it.

headline: Review: ‘Live Cargo,’ Human Trafficking, and Other Woes, in Paradise
summary_short: This first feature by the director Logan Sandler has great acting, stunning imagery and a vivid Caribbean setting. But its words prove elusive.

headline: Review: In ‘Cézanne et Moi,’ Zola and the Artist Are Pals. However ...
summary_short: A new film offers an intimate, searching portrait of the turbulent friendship between the writer and the painter.

headline: Review: In ‘The Zookeeper’s Wife,’ the Holocaust Seems Tame
summary_short: This true story of a couple who sheltered Jews beneath the Warsaw Zoo has tender moments but its portrayal of the Nazi invasion is too timid and sanitized.

headline: Review: ‘Karl Marx City’ Revisits the Everyday Terror of Dictatorship
summary_short: In this documentary, a filmmaker returns to her hometown in the former East Germany seeking personal and political insight.

headline: Review: ‘Phillauri,’ an Indian Rom-Com With an Epic Sweep
summary_short: Anshai Lal’s Bollywood movie uses a friendly ghost to turn a contemporary comedy into a historical drama that includes a massacre under British rule.

headline: Review: In ‘Life,’ Extraterrestrial Fun, Until Someone Gets Hurt
summary_short: This movie offers proof of life on another planet, sure, but it is also the occasion for another “Alien”-type deadly game of hide-and-seek.

headline: Review: ‘I Called Him Morgan,’ a Jazz Tale of Talent and Tragedy
summary_short: The director Kasper Collin has created a suave and sensitive documentary about the life and death of the great trumpeter Lee Morgan.

headline: Review: In ‘CHIPS,’ Blown-Up Cars Overshadow Buddy Cops
summary_short: This unrepentantly lewd comedy, based on the 1977-83 television series of the same name, stars Dax Shepard, who also wrote and directed.

headline: Review: ‘Dig Two Graves,’ but the Goodbye Is Only Temporary
summary_short: Hunter Adams shows his skill as a filmmaker, delivering a chiller that conjures eeriness and dread without defaulting to abundant gore.

headline: Review: ‘Saban’s Power Rangers,’ With a Color-Coded Makeover
summary_short: The popular 1990s series receives a big-screen reboot, and five new teenage superheroes face off against the latest alien threat.

headline: Review: ‘Prevenge,’ Orchestrated by a Fiendish Fetus
summary_short: Alice Lowe wrote, directed and stars in this British film about a pregnant serial killer on a darkly comedic odyssey dictated by her malicious fetus.

headline: Review: ‘Wilson,’ With Woody Harrelson as a Misanthrope
summary_short: A movie, based on Daniel Clowes’s graphic novel, about a man’s well-requited contempt for humanity.

headline: Review: ‘I, Olga Hepnarova,’ Carrying Out a Vow of Vengeance
summary_short: This Czech film gives a haunting account of the life of the mentally ill young woman who killed eight people in Prague in 1973.

headline: Review: ‘A Woman, a Part’ and a Quest to Reconnect
summary_short: In Elisabeth Subrin’s feature, a nuanced take on friendship and professional frustration, an actress finds that early relationships can fade.

headline: Review: ‘Song to Song,’ Terrence Malick’s Latest Beautiful Puzzle
summary_short: This drama about intersecting love lives features themes like betrayal, identity and art. Religion appears, too, in the film, set in Austin, Tex.

headline: Review: ‘T2 Trainspotting’: Time to Pay the Piper
summary_short: The sequel to the gloriously scabrous film that kick-started the careers of Danny Boyle and Ewan McGregor illustrates the consequences of a misspent youth.

headline: Review: Fiction and Nonfiction Blur in ‘Actor Martinez’
summary_short: Acting may be his first love, but the title character in “Actor Martinez” soon learns it’s no picnic — especially when dealing with his directors.

headline: Review: In ‘Atomica,’ Hunting for Clues in a Nuclear Waste Zone
summary_short: This sci-fi thriller may not have “Arrival”-level effects or sophistication, but it delivers a solid B-movie kick.

headline: Review: ‘Betting on Zero’ Tracks a Crusade Against Herbalife
summary_short: A documentary looks at a hedge fund manager’s $1 billion bet against that nutritional company and his efforts to expose what he characterized as consumer fraud.

headline: Review: ‘Mean Dreams’ Presents Lovers on the Lam With Quiet Skill
summary_short: Nathan Morlando’s film may focus on two young lovers, but Bill Paxton shines as a corrupt sheriff in one of his final film roles.

headline: Review: A Provocateur’s Recounting in ‘The Show About the Show’
summary_short: Caveh Zahedi, the film’s director and star, recounts the misadventures experienced while producing an initially sexually explicit semidocumentary series.

headline: Review: Intimate Struggles Come to Life in ‘After the Storm’
summary_short: The Japanese director Hirokazu Kore-eda’s latest family drama, focusing on a writer who’s fallen on hard times, works in a quiet cinematic register.

headline: Review: ‘The Belko Experiment’: Kill or Be Killed
summary_short: This film, set in Colombia, wallows in the cheap and hackneyed irony of choreographed slaughter.

headline: Review: In ‘Badrinath Ki Dulhania,’ Boy Meets Girl (and Learns to Respect Her)
summary_short: This Bollywood rom-com, directed by Shashank Khaitan, describes the growing pains of a gentleman whose fiancée teaches him to acknowledge her equality.

headline: Review: Give a Student Some Offal, and You’ll Regret It in ‘Raw’
summary_short: Julia Ducournau’s film unfolds during rush week in a nightmarish veterinary school.

headline: Review: Kristen Stewart Is Entrancing as a Haunted ‘Personal Shopper’
summary_short: Olivier Assayas’s new film is both a supernatural thriller and an unnerving inquiry into the drift and mystery of modern life.

headline: Review: In ‘Canners,’ One Man’s Trash Is Another’s Nickel Treasure
summary_short: A documentary follows bottle and can collectors in New York as they toil to fill their carts for $30 or $40 a day.

headline: Review: Love as the World Wars, in ‘The Ottoman Lieutenant’
summary_short: A nurse travels to the Ottoman Empire on the eve of World War I. Can romance blossom amid earthshaking events?

headline: Review: The Soundtrack Is the Star of ‘Who’s Crazy?’
summary_short: Featuring Ornette Coleman and Marianne Faithfull, the music provides counterpoint to a tale of patients from a psychiatric institution on a kind of holiday.

headline: Review: ‘The Sense of an Ending,’ and the Elusiveness of Truth
summary_short: Adapted from Julian Barnes’s 2011 novel, Ritesh Batra’s film portrays an emotionally detached man gingerly revisiting his past.

headline: Review: ‘Kong: Skull Island’ Crosses a 1933 Classic With ‘Apocalypse Now’
summary_short: In this remake, the beast King Kong has a new look and a new beauty (Brie Larson), who’s feistier than her predecessors.

headline: Review: ‘My Scientology Movie,’ an Offbeat Inquiry
summary_short: The British journalist Louis Theroux relies on a meandering charm in this documentary examining the Church of Scientology’s hold on its members.

headline: Review: ‘Beauty and the Beast’ Revels in Joy and Enchantment
summary_short: A compassionate Belle and a splendid monster are the hallmarks of this live-action remake of the 1991 animated film.

headline: Review: In ‘Apprentice,’ Teaching the Fine Art of Execution
summary_short: In this film from Singapore, the chief executioner at a high-security prison takes on a new assistant.

headline: Review: Shirley MacLaine Wants ‘The Last Word’? She Should Have It
summary_short: The 82-year-old actress holds your attention, but this film about a woman padding out her future obituary has an artificial ring.

headline: Review: Israel Is the Focus of ‘The Settlers’ and ‘Ben-Gurion: Epilogue’
summary_short: Issues of sovereignty in the Middle East are revisited in a pair of documentaries.

headline: Review: A Father Dies, and Duty Weighs on a Son in ‘Nakom’
summary_short: Kelly Daniela Norris and T. W. Pittman’s movie tells the story of a young medical student in Ghana, who returns home to a village to pay off a debt.

headline: Review: At ‘Table 19,’ Random Wedding Guests Straining to Laugh
summary_short: Slapstick and sap vie for prominence in a comedy so lazy that it actually features someone falling off a log.

headline: Review: A Crisis of Faith and a Trip to God’s B&B in ‘The Shack’
summary_short: Sam Worthington and Octavia Spencer star in “The Shack,” a Christian-themed film based on a best seller.

headline: Review: In ‘Logan,’ a Comic-Book Stalwart Turns Noirish Western
summary_short: This is old-school meets new-school pulp filled with intimations of mortality, and raw, ugly violence. And once again, Hugh Jackman plays the Wolverine.

headline: Review: ‘Before I Fall,’ a Melodramatic ‘Groundhog Day’
summary_short: Zoey Deutch relives a day repeatedly until she gets it right in this film based on a young-adult novel.

headline: Review: In ‘Wolves,’ a High School Athlete Can’t Outrun Clichés
summary_short: Taylor John Smith and Michael Shannon star in a sports film that transcends its stock characters for a while but eventually disappoints.

headline: Review: ‘Kiki’: The Vogueing Scene, Still a Refuge for Gay and Transgender Youth
summary_short: There are echoes of “Paris Is Burning” in this documentary, which chronicles a tight-knit community in New York. Yet there is a striking absence of elder mentors.

headline: Review: Al Pacino’s Journey With Wilde’s ‘Salomé’
summary_short: A story of obsession plays out in “Wilde Salomé” and “Salomé,” as Mr. Pacino veers into Camp.

headline: Review: In ‘Wait for Your Laugh’ and ‘Gilbert,’ Comedians Work Hard
summary_short: These documentaries go behind the scenes with their well-known subjects, Rose Marie and Gilbert Gottfried.

display_title: How to Be a Latin Lover
headline: Review: Eugenio Derbez as Just a Gigolo in ‘How to Be a Latin Lover’
summary_short: In this good-natured comedy, the Mexican actor and comedian has been dumped and has to settle for real life.

headline: Review: ‘A Dark Song’ Soaked in Sorcery and a Woman’s Grief
summary_short: This intense debut feature from the Irish director Liam Gavin, with its spare style, is a marriage of acting and atmosphere.

display_title: Harold and Lillian: A Hollywood Love Story
headline: Review: ‘Harold and Lillian’ Introduces a Hollywood Power Couple
summary_short: Meet the husband-and-wife team that inspired some of the most memorable moments onscreen, from “The Graduate” to “The Birds.”

headline: Review: ‘Nise,’ the Therapist Who Resisted Lobotomies
summary_short: A drama from Brazil about a psychiatrist who defied medical orthodoxy and treated patients with paint brushes instead of spikes and electroshock therapy.

headline: Review: ‘Casting JonBenet’ Revisits a 1996 Murder
summary_short: In a conceptual exercise, actors audition for roles in the celebrated case as a way of showing how people are still preoccupied by it.

headline: Review: In ‘The Circle,’ Click Here if You Think You’re Being Watched
summary_short: Emma Watson and Tom Hanks star in this adaptation of a Dave Eggers novel that explores surveillance-state threats.

headline: Review: Rami Malek as a Drifter With a Past in ‘Buster’s Mal Heart’
summary_short: Mr. Malek, of “Mr. Robot,” heads for the hills of Montana as a man fleeing a soul-deadening job and the burdens of modern life.

headline: Review: In ‘LA 92,’ the Los Angeles Riots Feel Like Today’s News
summary_short: This documentary, one of several commemorating the riots’ 25th anniversary, assembles broadcast and helicopter footage into a taut chronological account.

headline: Review: ‘Rupture’ Justifies a Fear of Spiders
summary_short: Noomi Rapace plays a woman subjected to jumbo syringes and repulsive nuzzling after being kidnapped by a mysterious cult.

headline: Review: In the Disturbing ‘Natasha,’ Sex and Manipulation
summary_short: When a morose Russian teenager comes to town, a 16-year-old in the Toronto suburbs meets his match.

headline: Review: ‘Let It Fall: Los Angeles 1982-1992,’ a Wrenching John Ridley Film
summary_short: Politicians, the police, victims and survivors deliver an oral history of the rising racial tensions that led to the early-1990s Los Angeles riots.

headline: Review: Brie Larson as a Gangster Wrangler in ‘Free Fire’
summary_short: Ben Wheatley’s formula for action-movie success: a best actress Oscar winner, dozens of firearms and a warehouse full of testosterone.

headline: Review: ‘Unforgettable’ Serves Up Yet Another Crazy Ex
summary_short: Rosario Dawson and Katherine Heigl star in a thriller that works a wearyingly familiar formula.

headline: Review: ‘The Penguin Counters,’ Cheery in Treacherous Conditions
summary_short: This documentary follows biologists to Antarctica, where they estimate the animals’ numbers and gauge the damage of climate change.

headline: Review: ‘The Promise’ Finds a Love Triangle in Constantinople
summary_short: Oscar Isaac, Christian Bale and Charlotte Le Bon star in this wartime romance with a heavy subject (genocide) but a corny plot.

headline: Review: Worried About a Sustainable Tomorrow? There’s Hope
summary_short: The fast-faced documentary “Tomorrow” profiles men and women with concrete solutions for moving away from fossil fuels and protecting the environment.

headline: Review: ‘Jeremiah Tower: The Last Magnificent,’ a Chef’s Tribulations
summary_short: Lydia Tenaglia’s documentary is a portrait of Mr. Tower, a force behind the California Cuisine movement in the 1970s, among other culinary feats.

display_title: Citizen Jane: Battle for the City
headline: Review: Jacobs and Moses Star in ‘Citizen Jane: Battle for the City’
summary_short: Jane Jacobs fought against Robert Moses’ plans to develop Lower Manhattan. This documentary revisits their legendary feud.

headline: Review: In ‘Born in China,’ an Antelope Outshines a Panda
summary_short: Disneynature’s latest documentary visits remote parts of China to provide rare glimpses of young animals in the wild.

headline: Review: Hearts of Darkness and Light in ‘The Lost City of Z’
summary_short: Charlie Hunnam stars in this period adventure story about love, loss and mystery in the Amazon from the director James Gray.

headline: Review: Richard Gere as ‘Norman,’ an Aspirational Fixer
summary_short: ‘Norman: The Moderate Rise and Tragic Fall of a New York Fixer,’ Joseph Cedar’s latest film, pits Jew against Jew on the fringes of power and influence.

headline: Review: In ‘Tommy’s Honour,’ a Family Feud on and Off the Green
summary_short: The director Jason Connery’s staid biopic is about the 19th-century golf pioneer Tom Morris and his son, with class conflict as a backdrop.

headline: Review: In ‘Little Boxes,’ a Biracial Family Meets a White Town
summary_short: A family ventures beyond the bubble of gentrified Brooklyn to a small town and is thrown out of its comfort zone.

headline: Review: ‘Finding Oscar,’ and Hope, in Massacre’s Aftermath
summary_short: This documentary looks at a Guatemalan village that was wiped out during a civil war, and searches for one of the few survivors.

display_title: Chasing Trane: The John Coltrane Documentary
headline: Review: In ‘Chasing Trane,’ Where’s the Joy of Sax?
summary_short: John Scheinfeld’s documentary about John Coltrane draws on interviews, including those with Bill Clinton, Carlos Santana and Cornel West.

headline: Review: ‘All These Sleepless Nights’ Roams the Streets of Warsaw
summary_short: A Polish film follows its young protagonist as he flirts, attends parties until dawn and gyrates to a perpetual backbeat.

headline: Review: Family Values and Hot Rides in ‘Fate of the Furious’
summary_short: Each installment of “Fast and Furious” is more enjoyably ludicrous than the last, even as the death of the star Paul Walker continues to hang over the franchise.

headline: Review: ‘Your Name’ Takes Adolescent Identity Crises to Extremes
summary_short: Manohla Dargis reviews Makoto Shinkai’s latest film, a lovely and touching Japanese animation in which teenagers find themselves trading bodies and lives.

headline: Review: 3 Teenagers Seek a Voice in ‘Speech & Debate’
summary_short: Stephen Karam’s film adaptation of his own play is a comedy about students who don’t quite fit in but insist, in their clumsy way, on being heard.

headline: Review: ‘Going in Style’ Proves Crime Has No Age Limit
summary_short: Michael Caine, Alan Arkin and Morgan Freeman star in a comedy about old dudes who rob a bank, a remake of a 1979 movie.

headline: Review: Carrying On and Making Movies in ‘Their Finest’
summary_short: Gemma Arterton stars in this World War II drama about a screenwriter who’s hired to create uplift and propaganda. From the director of “An Education.”

headline: Review: A ‘Gifted’ Girl at the Center of a Custody Battle
summary_short: A young math prodigy and her strong bond with her uncle are tested when a debate arises over whether to cultivate her abilities or let her be a child.

headline: Review: Out of the Dark, Temptation Abounds in ‘The Ticket’
summary_short: In this drama, Dan Stevens is exceptional as a blind man who is less than happy with what he sees after his sight is restored.

headline: Review: Seeking Revenge for ‘The Assignment’ She Didn’t Want
summary_short: In Walter Hill’s film, a revenge plot is set in motion after a hit man, played by Michelle Rodriguez, undergoes a forced gender reassignment surgery.

display_title: Turn It Around: The Story of East Bay Punk
headline: Review: ‘Turn It Around’ Plays to Fans of West Coast Punk Music
summary_short: A sprawling documentary retraces the birth of the punk scene in the Bay Area, where bands like Green Day and Rancid came together and thrived.

headline: Review: ‘Radio Dreams’ Builds a Spiritual Home for Stateless Souls
summary_short: A fictional San Francisco radio station provides a place for immigrants adrift to bond in the ether.

headline: Review: Religion Tests Gender Politics in ‘The Women’s Balcony’
summary_short: The power and resourcefulness of women are on display in this small-scale comedy, which manages to speak to a broader political movement.

headline: Review: Living It Up With the Grateful Dead in ‘Long Strange Trip’
summary_short: Amir Bar-Lev’s four-hour documentary chronicles the band’s deeply musical journey while placing it at the joyous center of the counterculture.

headline: Review: In ‘Berlin Syndrome,’ Passion Leads to Horrific Regret
summary_short: Teresa Palmer has a breakthrough role as a young woman on holiday in Berlin whose instant romance with a stranger results in her abduction.

display_title: Pirates of the Caribbean: Dead Men Tell No Tales
headline: Review: ‘Dead Men Tell No Tales.’ Not Very Well, Anyway.
summary_short: The latest in the “Pirates of the Caribbean” franchise brings back Johnny Depp’s Captain Sparrow but leaves the joy an ocean away.

headline: Review: ‘War Machine’: Brad Pitt Has Met the Enemy. He Just Doesn’t Know It Yet.
summary_short: Gen. Stanley A. McChrystal is the commander alluded to in David Michôd’s satirical portrait of a man in over his head and enthralled by his own hype.

headline: Review: ‘Buena Vista Social Club: Adios,’ Analytical but Still Loving
summary_short: This vital, informative companion piece to Wim Wenders’s 1999 documentary chronicles the late-life careers, and deaths, of the “Buena Vista” stars.

headline: Review: In ‘Drone,’ Confronting Sins and a Vengeful Visitor
summary_short: Jason Bourque’s thriller examines the moral compromises of meting out death from afar, and the unraveling of a home when a victim comes to supper.

headline: Review: ‘Baywatch,’ a Romp Full of Surf, Sand and Lots of Skin
summary_short: Dwayne Johnson and his lifeguard squad try to save the Bay while providing the sort of sleazy, wholesome entertainment this ’90s series was known for.

headline: Review: In ‘Restless Creature,’ Wendy Whelan Dances Against the Clock
summary_short: A documentary captures this ballerina at a critical moment in 2013, when she was both trying for a comeback and coming to terms with aging.

headline: Review: ‘The Woman Who Left’ Is an Epic, Intimate Tale of Injustice
summary_short: From the modern Philippines, Lav Diaz’s haunting and pessimistic take on a Tolstoy story.

headline: Review: ‘Everything, Everything’ Pits Love Against Disease
summary_short: Amandla Stenberg plays a teenager with an immune system disorder who falls for the boy next door, and risks everything.

headline: Review: A 20th-Century Woman Rethinking ‘The Commune’
summary_short: Trine Dyrholm is “magnificent” as a woman buckling under the strain of her career and her marriage in Thomas Vinterberg’s latest film.

headline: Review: ‘Paint It Black,’ Amber Tamblyn’s Portrait of Grief
summary_short: In this adaptation of Janet Fitch’s novel, two women react very differently to a suicide.

headline: Review: Andrzej Wajda’s Vividly Rendered Last Film, ‘Afterimage’
summary_short: This passionate political movie tells the story of Wladyslaw Strzeminski, a real-life artist who suffered under Soviet rule.

display_title: Diary of a Wimpy Kid: The Long Haul
headline: Review: 4th ‘Wimpy Kid’ Has New Faces in a Familiar Story
summary_short: Greg and his brothers are dragged on a dreary road trip by their parents. You can probably guess the rest.

headline: Review: Bryan Cranston Is a Dad in Suburban Exile in ‘Wakefield’
summary_short: A man indulges a fantasy to escape his routine by camping out in a storage room above his garage and observing his own absence.

headline: Review: ‘Alien: Covenant’ Stays on Brand With Its Terror
summary_short: The new entry in Ridley Scott’s long-lived franchise is committed to the canny management of expectations, but that doesn’t diminish its creepiness.

headline: Review: She’s Got ‘The Wedding Plan,’ With a Groom TBD
summary_short: Rama Burshtein received acclaim for her debut feature, “Fill the Void.” Now she’s back with another biting, multilayered romantic comedy.

display_title: King Arthur: Legend of the Sword
headline: Review: Before He Was ‘King Arthur,’ He Was a Guy Ritchie Lad
summary_short: The Arthurian legend gets a makeover with quips, winks, body blows, digital elephants and an easy, breezy Charlie Hunnam.

headline: Review: In ‘The Wall,’ Two Trapped Soldiers and a Chatty Sniper
summary_short: Working with a minimalist script and a tight budget, the director Doug Liman brings vein-popping intensity to a claustrophobic standoff in Iraq.

headline: Review: ‘Folk Hero & Funny Guy’ on a Fractious Road Trip
summary_short: Alex Karpovsky of “Girls” stars as a bad comic opening for a good folk-rocker. As their trip rolls along, tensions bubble up.

headline: Review: Even Laughs Are Rationed in a ‘Whisky Galore!’ Reboot
summary_short: The islanders are still driven to lawlessness after their whisky runs out, but this remake lacks the luster of the original.

headline: Review: Olympic Hopeful in ‘Tracktown’ Finds Life Beyond the Race
summary_short: Alexi Pappas, a runner who, in real life, competed at the 2016 Olympics, helped write, direct and produce — and stars in — a film about a runner.

headline: Review: ‘Get Me Roger Stone’ Profiles a President Whisperer in Peacock Mode
summary_short: The operative Roger J. Stone Jr. has a scandalous history, a Nixon tattoo and boldfaced acquaintances, including President Trump, all explored in this documentary.

headline: Review: In ‘Urban Hymn,’ Hardened Youth and an Angelic Voice
summary_short: A social worker tries to connect with a troubled 17-year-old through music, but the girl’s street-tough best friend stands in the way.

headline: Review: ‘Paris Can Wait,’ at Least Until After the Crème Brûlée
summary_short: In this film, Diane Lane stars as a Hollywood producer’s wife whose road trip to Paris becomes a journey of self-discovery — and a gastronomic affair.

headline: Review: Cars and Culture Clashes in ‘Lowriders’
summary_short: A father is immersed in the lowrider world, while a son wants only to pursue his art. And then another son is released from prison.

headline: Review: She’s Still a Mess, but ‘Snatched’ Is No ‘Trainwreck’
summary_short: Amy Schumer teams up with Goldie Hawn in “Snatched.” Only one of them gets to be funny.

headline: Review: Cate Blanchett in ‘Manifesto,’ a Cerebral Exercise
summary_short: Julian Rosefeldt’s art installation is now a film, with this chameleonic actress morphing into multiple characters.

headline: Review: In ‘Ta’ang,’ Burmese Refugees, Displaced and in Limbo
summary_short: Wang Bing’s documentary observes refugees from the Kokang region in Myanmar who have fled across the border into China.

headline: Review: ‘Guardians of the Galaxy Vol. 2’ Wants That Loving Feeling
summary_short: Chris Pratt, Zoe Saldana and the crew are back for this sequel to the 2014 hit about a ragtag group of futuristic fighters.

headline: Review: ‘Julian Schnabel: A Private Portrait’ Puts Praise Above Art
summary_short: Though this documentary looks at the artist and his work, it is more concerned with layering on the admiration.

headline: Review: ‘The Dinner,’ Haute Cuisine and a Table of Deplorables
summary_short: Richard Gere and Steve Coogan face off as estranged brothers with serious family matters to attend to in this film adaptation of Herman Koch’s book.

headline: Review: In ‘Burden,’ an Artist Who Is Tortured. Literally.
summary_short: A documentary looks at Chris Burden, who had himself shot, crucified and more, all for the sake of his performance art.

headline: Review: Hiring an Exorcist? Get References First in ‘Another Evil’
summary_short: In this ultra-low-budget ghost story, the living may exhibit more unsettling behavior than the dead.

headline: Review: Revisiting the Mystery of Julian Assange, in ‘Risk’
summary_short: This Laura Poitras documentary follows the elusive and evasive WikiLeaks founder over several years, but real-time events have overtaken the film’s tale.

headline: Review: ‘Sacred,’ a Global Group Portrait of Faith in Action
summary_short: This documentary, using footage shot by 40 filmmakers in 25 countries, depicts the uses and rituals of religion in a range of environments.

headline: Review: Can Cheating Save a Marriage? Ask ‘The Lovers’
summary_short: Debra Winger and Tracy Letts play a couple whose passions for each other have reignited, to the chagrin of their lovers.

display_title: Angkor Awakens: A Portrait of Cambodia
headline: Review: ‘Angkor Awakens,’ a Blistering Account of Cambodia’s Painful Past
summary_short: Robert H. Lieberman’s documentary scrutinizes the harrowing abuses and tormented legacy of the Khmer Rouge regime.

headline: Review: In ‘Take Me,’ a Kidnapping Turns Cat-and-Mouse
summary_short: This deadpan comedy starring Taylor Schilling and Pat Healy features a fake abduction that gets all too real.

headline: Review: Inside the Ring With ‘Chuck,’ the Real-Life Rocky
summary_short: Liev Schreiber may not resemble Chuck Wepner, but he convincingly portrays this boxer, whose 1975 bout with Muhammad Ali inspired Sylvester Stallone.

headline: Review: In ‘Mr. Chibbs,’ Kenny Anderson Tries Another Shot
summary_short: In this documentary by Jill Campbell, the former N.B.A. point guard hopes to develop a life after the clock runs out on his athletic career.

headline: Review: ‘The House’ Is a Comedy Built on Despair
summary_short: Will Ferrell and Amy Poehler play a couple who embark on a nefarious scheme in which the odds are always in their favor.

headline: Review: In ‘The Reagan Show,’ No Grenada but Lots of the Arms Race
summary_short: A documentary assembled from archival video offers a glimpse of the 40th president’s character, but focuses mostly on relations with the Soviets.

headline: Review: In ‘Reset,’ a Mother Enters a Wormhole to Save Her Son
summary_short: This film, produced by Jackie Chan, is a tense sci-fi action thriller with a strong female lead.

headline: Review: ‘Marie Curie’ Recalls a Beautiful Mind and Tough Life
summary_short: This biopic, starring Karolina Gruszka, highlights about six years in the life of the Nobel Prize-winning scientist.

headline: Review: ‘The Skyjacker’s Tale’ Tracks Down a Fugitive in Cuba
summary_short: A documentary by Jamie Kastner is about a fugitive convicted in the deaths of eight people at a golf course in the Virgin Islands.

headline: Review: ‘The B-Side,’ Errol Morris’s Deft Portrait of a Photographer
summary_short: Elsa Dorfman, a subject of seemingly modest import for a documentary, emerges here as an artist of deep compassion, empathy, humor and wisdom.

headline: Review: From Wooing Women to Plotting Hitler’s Murder in ‘13 Minutes’
summary_short: A German biopic tells the story of Georg Elser, a carpenter who tried to blow up the Führer in 1939.

headline: Review: In ‘The Little Hours,’ These Sisters Are Neither Chaste Nor Obedient
summary_short: The film borrows from Boccaccio, with a sprinkling of Monty Python, for this irreverent comedy set in an Italian convent.

headline: Review: ‘Darkness Rising,’ a Bland Haunted-House Salad
summary_short: A woman returns to the site of a family murder only to find the evil spirit that caused it is still hanging around.

headline: Review: ‘Despicable Me 3’ Suggests a Franchise Running on Fumes
summary_short: Steve Carell and Kristen Wiig revisit their familiar characters, but the goings-on show signs of wear even as the energy level escalates.

headline: Review: In ‘Okja,’ a Girl and Her Pig Take on the Food Industrial Complex
summary_short: Bong Joon-ho’s latest film on Netflix is a high-speed satire with a conscience and a heart. And Tilda Swinton in braces.

headline: Review: In ‘Baby Driver,’ It’s Kiss Kiss, Zoom Zoom
summary_short: Burning rubber and hot licks help propel this action movie about a getaway driver named Baby, played by Ansel Elgort. Edgar Wright directed.

headline: Review: ‘In Transit,’ and Oh, the Tales These Travelers Tell
summary_short: Albert Maysles’s last documentary observes passengers traveling Amtrak’s route between Chicago and the Pacific Northwest.

headline: Review: ‘Nowhere to Hide’ for an Iraqi Nurse Still Clinging to Hope
summary_short: A documentary observes the rising tide of danger and displacement for families living in central Iraq amid the arrival of the Islamic State.

headline: Review: Cannibalism, Hallucinogens and Keanu: ‘The Bad Batch’ Has It All
summary_short: An updated tale of ostracism for the golden age of dystopia, written and directed by Ana Lily Amirpour.

display_title: Nobody Speak: Trials of the Free Press
headline: Review: ‘Nobody Speak,’ a Bombastic Look at Hulk Hogan’s Gawker Lawsuit
summary_short: Brian Knappenberger’s timely documentary serves as an impassioned defense of the news media, though it lacks depth.

headline: Review: ‘All the Rage’ Explores the Mind-Body Connection
summary_short: This documentary looks at Dr. John Sarno, who posits that many types of chronic pain, particularly back pain, are caused by stress and repressed emotions.

headline: Review: In ‘Food Evolution,’ Scientists Strike Back
summary_short: Scott Hamilton Kennedy’s documentary gives G.M.O. opponents their say, but leaves the last word to food technologists, who insist on reviewing the data.

headline: Review: ‘Paulina’ Looks at the Dark Side of Idealism
summary_short: The film, with a powerhouse performance by Dolores Fonzi, follows a young Argentine woman who confronts a horrible event in a rural town.

headline: Review: ‘In Pursuit of Silence,’ a Guide to Tuning Out the Racket
summary_short: Patrick Shen’s documentary explores the harmful effects of excessive sound, linking quietude to tranquillity and better health.

display_title: Can't Stop, Won't Stop: A Bad Boy Story
headline: Review: ‘Can’t Stop Won’t Stop’ Tells Sean Combs’s Bad Boy Story
summary_short: Daniel Kaufman’s documentary covers a lot of Mr. Combs’s history as it records preparations for Bad Boy reunion concerts in Brooklyn.

headline: Review: ‘The Beguiled,’ Sofia Coppola’s Civil War Cocoon
summary_short: Ms. Coppola won best director at the Cannes Film Festival for her film starring Nicole Kidman and Colin Farrell, an update on the 1971 movie with Clint Eastwood.

headline: Review: Transformers Get Arthurian in ‘The Last Knight’
summary_short: Mark Wahlberg is back in the latest “Transformers” movie, but it’s stolen by Anthony Hopkins and a grouchy C-3PO knockoff.

headline: Review: In ‘Harmonium,’ a Family Lets the Wrong One In
summary_short: A mysterious man becomes a disruptive presence for a married couple and their daughter in Koji Fukada’s well-acted family drama.

headline: Review: ‘All Eyez on Me’ Is Uninspired. Tupac Shakur Was Anything But.
summary_short: Benny Boom’s film fails the considerable talent of the complex rapper it chronicles and the actor portraying him, Demetrius Shipp Jr.

headline: Review: In ‘The Book of Henry,’ a Little Child Shall, Well, You Know
summary_short: Naomi Watts stars in a cliché-stuffed dumb movie about a smart kid, directed by Colin Trevorrow (“Jurassic World”).

headline: Review: ‘47 Meters Down,’ With Great Whites Circling Above
summary_short: Mandy Moore and Claire Holt play sisters looking for adventures in Mexico, but being stuck in a cage on the ocean floor wasn’t what they had in mind.

headline: Review: Car-Pooling to End Ireland’s Troubles in ‘The Journey’
summary_short: Nick Hamm’s drama imagines a fictional drive shared by the Irish republican leader Martin McGuinness and the Unionist Ian Paisley.

headline: Review: Alternative Energy Strikes Back in ‘Kill Switch’
summary_short: Dan Stevens contends with drones, militants and a video-game-style parallel universe in his quest to save humanity in this sci-fi feature.

headline: Review: In ‘Rough Night,’ It’s Women Behaving Badly (Yawn)
summary_short: Scarlett Johansson and Kate McKinnon play old friends whose boozy bachelorette weekend goes very, very wrong in a comedy from Lucia Aniello.

display_title: Once Upon a Time in Venice
headline: Review: ‘Once Upon a Time in Venice’ Unleashes a Bland Bruce Willis
summary_short: A private detective is desperate to recover his stolen dog in this action-comedy from Mark and Robb Cullen.

headline: Review: In ‘Cars 3,’ Lightning McQueen Faces an Existential Crisis
summary_short: Lightning is back and feeling a bit old in this latest breezy feature in the Pixar franchise. It offers life lessons that will resonate with adults as well as with children.

headline: Review: In ‘Megan Leavey,’ a Marine, Her Dog and a Bond Forged in War
summary_short: Based on a true story, this film, starring Kate Mara, is both harrowing and heartstring-tugging.

headline: Review: For an Aging Actor, Another Chance to Be ‘The Hero’
summary_short: Brett Haley’s low-key feature, about an older actor seeking redemption after being reduced to a cliché, belongs to its star, Sam Elliott.

headline: Review: In ‘It Comes at Night,’ a House Full of Guns and Family Desperation
summary_short: The sophomore feature by Trey Edward Shults is as spookily self-assured and ambitious as “Krisha.”

headline: Review: Familiar Woes and Unexpected Bonds in ‘Moscow Never Sleeps’
summary_short: The interlocking stories in this feature show off a bright metropolis filled with familial dysfunction and frustrated love affairs.

headline: Review: Is the Girls’ Volleyball Team Ready for ‘Miles’?
summary_short: A boy in pursuit of a college sports scholarship crosses a boundary in a real-life story starring Tim Boardman and Molly Shannon.

headline: Review: In ‘11:55,’ a Marine Returns Home to Another War
summary_short: Ari Issler and Ben Snyder’s intimate feature focuses on a young soldier who comes back from Afghanistan to face the fallout from a long-ago crime.

headline: Review: In ‘Camera Obscura,’ Murder in His Viewfinder
summary_short: This horror movie, the feature debut of the writer-director Aaron B. Koontz, has good actors but too many motifs derived from other fright films.

headline: Review: Salma Hayek Skewers a Boor in ‘Beatriz at Dinner’
summary_short: Class polarization makes for an uncomfortable dinner party in this film written by Mike White and directed by Miguel Arteta.

headline: Review: ‘The Mummy,’ With Tom Cruise, Deserves a Quick Burial
summary_short: This reboot of a monster franchise could have been creepy or campy, but it settles for the dreary action-blockbuster template.

headline: Review: ‘Ascent’ of Mount Fuji, Guided by Over 4,000 Images
summary_short: Fiona Tan’s ode to this volcanic mountain draws on a scripted voice-over to impart observations and histories.

headline: Review: In ‘Past Life,’ Family Mysteries and Cosmic Questions
summary_short: This film by the Israeli director Avi Nesher, based on Baruch Milch’s memoir, uses a potboiler setup to delve into themes of history and reconciliation.

headline: Review: High School Is Still Terrible for a ‘Handsome Devil’
summary_short: Two unlikely friends at an all-boys school in Ireland must survive their classmates’ bullying with the help of a sympathetic teacher.

headline: Review: Power Ballads as Couples Therapy in ‘Band Aid’
summary_short: Zoe Lister-Jones wrote, directed and stars in this comedy about an out-of-sync couple turning their squabbles into songs.

headline: Review: ‘The Exception’ Is a Diverting Tale Set Before Nazi Horrors Fully Emerged
summary_short: Christopher Plummer plays the exiled German Kaiser Wilhelm II in this melodrama, which unfolds in the Netherlands in the early years of the Second World War.

headline: Review: In ‘Vincent N Roxxy,’ Love Is in the Air, N So Is Fear
summary_short: This combination crime drama and romance finds Emile Hirsch and Zoë Kravitz circling each other, and trying to stay away from bad guys.

headline: Review: ‘Tatara Samurai’ Forges a Man of Honor
summary_short: This historical action movie from Yoshinari Nishikori has a laudably realistic grit and takes an unexpected turn for a film of its genre.

display_title: Captain Underpants: The First Epic Movie
headline: Review: ‘Captain Underpants,’ Pretty Much What You’d Expect
summary_short: DreamWorks brings the book series to the screen, riding the voices of Kevin Hart and Thomas Middleditch and a story featuring huge bathroom fixtures.

headline: Review: ‘Wonder Woman’ Is a Blockbuster That Lets Itself Have Fun
summary_short: The movie, directed by Patty Jenkins and starring Gal Gadot, shakes off branding imperatives with touches of screwball comedy and romantic adventure.

headline: Review: In ‘Letters From Baghdad,’ a Woman Who Trod the Sands of History
summary_short: A documentary about the British explorer Gertrude Bell focuses on her role in drawing the modern borders of Iraq.

headline: Review: In ‘Dean,’ Demetri Martin Doodles Through Grief
summary_short: The comic tries his hand at writing and directing a feature film, producing a sweet, humorous drama about loss.

headline: Review: ‘The Incomparable Rose Hartman’ Snaps Glimpses of the Glitterati
summary_short: Otis Mass’s documentary portrait of a Manhattan celebrity photographer reflects a talented but exasperating pro.

headline: Review: Churchill Battling a War, and Himself
summary_short: This film re-examines Winston Churchill’s image as a gruff British bulldog of a leader by shining a light on his struggle with depression.

headline: ‘The Incredible Jessica James’ Is a Bold Woman in Progress
summary_short: Jessica Williams shines as a young playwright struggling with rejection — professionally and romantically — in this film streaming on Netflix.

headline: Review: ‘Menashe’ Finds Faith and Fatherhood Sometimes at Odds
summary_short: In this sweet, often understated film set in a Hasidic neighborhood, the title character is a widower who must remarry to regain custody of his son.

display_title: Water and Sugar: Carlo Di Palma, the Colours of Life
headline: Review: ‘Water and Sugar’: How Carlo Di Palma Burnished Reality on Film
summary_short: This documentary celebrates the Italian cinematographer who brought a golden touch to his collaborations with Michelangelo Antonioni and Woody Allen.

headline: Review: ‘Sled Dogs’ Exposes Abuse of Working Animals
summary_short: The documentary filmmaker Fern Levitt wants to shut down the dog-sledding industry. She makes a moving argument.

headline: Review: In ‘Person to Person,’ the Real-ish Humans of New York
summary_short: Dustin Guy Defa wrote and directed this low-budget feature that tells the stories of several New Yorkers over the course of a day.

headline: Review: Aid Workers in Love and War in Sean Penn’s ‘The Last Face’
summary_short: In war-torn Liberia, Charlize Theron and Javier Bardem face a big problem: how to keep their knotty relationship from fizzling.

headline: Review: ‘The Last Dalai Lama?’ Asks What Comes Next
summary_short: This documentary examines why the Dalai Lama is being careful to protect his lineage from Chinese interference.

headline: Review: Diamonds Are a Mighty Tease in ‘Imperfections,’ a Noir Set in Chicago
summary_short: David Singer’s film is a modest con movie about the lengths an aspiring actress is willing to go to for some extra cash.

headline: Review: Holly Hunter and Carrie Coon Try to Redeem ‘Strange Weather’
summary_short: In this road movie, a woman whose son has committed suicide travels to confront the hot-dog tycoon who stole her son’s idea.

headline: Review: In Search of a Dying Tongue in ‘I Dream in Another Language’
summary_short: In the film, a linguist seeks to keep a language alive, but the only two men who speak it aren’t interested.

display_title: From the Land of the Moon
headline: Review: ‘From the Land of the Moon,’ and on Uneven Ground
summary_short: Nicole Garcia’s turgid adaptation of an Italian novella makes for a silly movie, despite a strong performance from Marion Cotillard.

headline: Review: ‘The Emoji Movie’ Can’t Escape Its Own Idiocy
summary_short: In Hollywood, anything goes — even this big-screen tale about those little digital expressions of emotions.

headline: Review: Dressed to Kill, ‘Atomic Blonde’ Also Shoots to Kill
summary_short: Charlize Theron plays a spy in “Atomic Blonde,” which comes off like a highlight reel of car crashes and inventively choreographed fights.

headline: Review: She Hosts ‘Women Who Kill,’ and May Be in Love With One
summary_short: In Ingrid Jungermann’s droll comedy, ex-lovers who produce a podcast about serial killers find themselves at odds when a new romantic interest emerges.

display_title: Rumble: The Indians Who Rocked The World
headline: Review: ‘Rumble’ Gives Due to Unheralded Native American Pop Musicians
summary_short: Catherine Bainbridge’s “Rumble: The Indians Who Rocked the World” celebrates performers who never fully got their due for their musical contributions.

headline: Review: Out of Luck, and Seeking a Strongman in ‘Mister Universo’
summary_short: The Italian directors Tizza Covi and Rainer Frimmel’s hybrid of a film follows a young man on a sort of odyssey across Italy.

headline: Review: ‘Dunkirk’ Is a Tour de Force War Movie, Both Sweeping and Intimate
summary_short: In his brilliant new film, Christopher Nolan revisits a harrowing, true World War II mission in a story of struggle, survival and resistance.

headline: Review: A Bullied Boy Gets a Hunting Lesson in ‘First Kill’
summary_short: A deep-woods thriller stars Bruce Willis as the local police chief and features a bank robbery gone wrong.

headline: Review: ‘The Fencer’ Is an Inspiring Figure in a Formulaic Tale
summary_short: In 1950s Estonia, a principal’s envy of a popular teacher leads him to start investigating his background.

headline: Review: ‘The Pulitzer at 100’ Celebrates Awards More Than Winners
summary_short: A film about a prize for excellence in journalism and the arts shares some winners’ insights, but not enough.

headline: Review: ‘The Midwife’ Is Unflappable, Until the Past Blows In
summary_short: Two great French actresses, Catherine Deneuve and Catherine Frot, share the screen in this film about forgiveness and redemption.

headline: Review: ‘Romeo Is Bleeding,’ and Shakespeare Is Relevant
summary_short: A documentary finds a group of young people in violence-plagued Richmond, Calif., staging their own version of Romeo and Juliet’s romantic tragedy.

headline: Review: In ‘Landline,’ the Family That Strays Together
summary_short: Jenny Slate, John Turturro and Edie Falco star in Gillian Robespierre’s new comedy, set in 1995.

headline: Review: ‘Killing Ground’ Will Make You Rethink That Camping Trip
summary_short: The movie, set in an Australian national park, features two families and one set of brutal killers.

headline: Review: In ‘The Untamed,’ Close Encounters. No, Even Closer.
summary_short: A slimy, many-tentacled alien has sex with several unhappy residents of the Mexican city of Guanajuato in Amat Escalante’s movie.

headline: Review: ‘Kekszakallu’ Plunges Into the Unknown
summary_short: This Argentine film, very loosely inspired by the Bartok opera “Bluebeard’s Castle,” observes the lives of teenage girls on the verge of adulthood.

headline: Review: A Poor, Little Rich Maharajah in ‘Black Prince’
summary_short: Kavi Raz’s film, based on the true story of Duleep Singh, never finds a rhythm or dramatic arc.

headline: Review: ‘Valerian’ Is a Rave in Space (but Not Much Fun)
summary_short: If you can summarize the plot of Luc Besson’s film adaptation of the graphic-novel science fiction series, you weren’t paying attention.

headline: Review: In ‘Girls Trip,’ Women Giddily Under the Influence
summary_short: In the affably amusing, sometimes spittingly funny “Girls Trip,” a weekend getaway brings trouble, laughs and sisterhood.

headline: Review: Modern-Day Conflicts Creep Into Idyllic ‘Santoalla’
summary_short: A Dutch couple goes off the grid to live a quiet life in Spain, but their idyll ends in a true crime mystery that is the subject of this documentary.

headline: Review: ‘Chasing Coral’ Bears Witness to the Death Aquatic
summary_short: Jeff Orlowski’s documentary emphasizes that climate change isn’t just an aboveground phenomenon — warmer oceans mean that coral reefs are in peril, too.

headline: Review: In ‘Footnotes,’ It’s Out of Work We Go
summary_short: A Marxist musical comedy follows its heroine into a luxury shoe factory and then into a labor dispute.

headline: Review: A Music Box to ‘Wish Upon,’ With a (Deadly) Catch
summary_short: A teenager unhappy with her circumstances falls prey to a strange box, and it doesn’t bode well for the resident high school meanie.

headline: Review: ‘Blind’ Aims for Steamy Romance but Hits Silliness
summary_short: Alec Baldwin and Demi Moore star in a clumsy tale about a cranky blind writer and a married woman who finds him affair-worthy.

headline: Review: Victims or Not? ‘The Wrong Light’ Looks at a Rescue Group
summary_short: A documentary initially focused on Thailand’s sex industry takes a sharp turn when the filmmakers begin to doubt the activist who is their guide.

headline: Review: ‘Endless Poetry,’ Alejandro Jodorowsky’s Surreal Self-Portrait
summary_short: An 88-year-old polymath’s nostalgic look back on the Chilean literary scene in the late 1940s.

headline: Review: ‘Lady Macbeth’ in Hoop Skirts
summary_short: Victim or villain, flower or serpent? In this British movie, a young 19th-century woman finds passion, makes mischief and commits murder.

headline: Review: In ‘Birthright: A War Story,’ a 40-Year Offensive Against Reproductive Choices
summary_short: The documentary argues that not just pregnancy-related treatment, but also all manner of health care for women, is under constant attack.

display_title: War for the Planet of the Apes
headline: Review: New ‘Planet of the Apes’ Makes You Root Against Your Species
summary_short: With Andy Serkis reprising his role as Caesar, “War for the Planet of the Apes” is a humane western wrapped around a prison movie, as primates battle for primacy.

headline: Review: Okwui Okpokwasili’s ‘Bronx Gothic,’ From Stage to Screen
summary_short: A documentary revisits a harrowing solo performance piece that explores the sexual awakening of two girls in the Bronx.

headline: Review: In ‘City of Ghosts,’ Fighting ISIS With Journalism
summary_short: In this documentary, Matthew Heineman (“Cartel Land”) focuses on the gutsy Syrian citizen-journalist group called Raqqa Is Being Slaughtered Silently.

headline: Review: In ‘Swim Team,’ Autism Is No Barrier to Competition
summary_short: Lara Stolman’s documentary follows a Special Olympics team for autistic kids, the Jersey Hammerheads, and the challenges they face.

headline: Review: ‘A Ghost Story’ Has a Sensitive Specter With Time on His Hands
summary_short: Casey Affleck and Rooney Mara play a young couple, one of whom is dead, in David Lowery’s haunting new film.

headline: Review: In ‘Austin Found,’ Child Abduction Is Played for Laughs
summary_short: Dumb-comedy season is here: Linda Cardellini stars as a manipulative mother who turns to kidnapping when her pageant dreams for her daughter fizzle.

headline: Review: Spider-Man (Again) and All That Sticky Kid Stuff
summary_short: This superhero is back in a reboot that features new faces and familiar fights. Tom Holland wears the suit, but Michael Keaton owns the movie.

headline: Review: In ‘The Big Sick,’ Comedy Is Hard, Love Harder
summary_short: Kumail Nanjiani stars opposite Zoe Kazan in this very funny, moving true story about how he found and almost lost love. Holly Hunter and Ray Romano also star.

headline: Review: ‘The King’s Choice’ Depicts Norway’s Entry Into World War II
summary_short: The movie sluggishly charts how the ceremonial king acquired real negotiating power during a crisis.

headline: Review: The Hard Road of Decency in ‘The Unknown Girl’
summary_short: A young doctor struggles with her conscience in this latest film from the Dardenne brothers.

headline: Review: In ‘Rememory,’ the Machine Knows What You Did
summary_short: A traumatized car-crash survivor turns into an amateur sleuth, using a machine that records and recovers memories.

headline: Review: Fighting Dirty, Over a Man, in ‘The Layover’
summary_short: Two longtime friends, played by Alexandra Daddario and Kate Upton, take a trip to Florida and end up vying for their seatmate’s attention.

headline: Review: ‘The Teacher,’ a Classroom Satire on Political Corruption
summary_short: The Czech director Jan Hrebejk’s new film shows that a culture of collaboration requires active participation, even if subconscious.

headline: Review: In ‘Birth of the Dragon,’ Young Bruce Lee Meets a Master
summary_short: The film focuses on an early chapter in the martial-arts superstar’s life, when he battled a Shaolin monk in the Bay Area.

headline: Review: In ‘Beach Rats,’ Life and Sexuality in Limbo
summary_short: Eliza Hittman’s refreshing sophomore feature centers on its main character’s existential crisis.

headline: Review: ‘The Villainess’ Reveals a Sadist’s Eye for Action
summary_short: A South Korean action drama deftly gives viewers a first-person view of violence, but falters when trying to convey its emotional costs.

headline: Review: ‘England Is Mine,’ a Portrait of Morrissey’s Early Years
summary_short: In case you were uncertain, Mark Gill’s unrelentingly dour biopic confirms that the Smiths’ singer was a miserable lad.

headline: Review: A Civil War Erupts in ‘Bushwick’
summary_short: Forget high rents and artisanal pizza. This dystopian glimpse of a Brooklyn neighborhood features an army of snipers and storm troopers.

headline: Review: In ‘Death Note,’ When Danger Calls, Reach for a Notebook
summary_short: Adam Wingard has adapted this sprawling Japanese manga series about a high schooler whose world is upended by an ancient notebook.

headline: Review: True to Its Title, This ‘Lemon’ Is Far From Peachy
summary_short: Janicza Bravo’s feature debut centers on a would-be actor who is a failure in every respect.

headline: Review: Two Animated Orphans Make Their Way to Paris in ‘Leap!’
summary_short: This risk-averse animated movie features the voices of Elle Fanning, Carly Rae Jepsen and Mel Brooks.

headline: Review: In ‘Crown Heights,’ Justice Delayed and Denied
summary_short: Based on a true story, Matt Ruskin’s film stars Lakeith Stanfield as a man who spent decades in prison for a crime he did not commit.

headline: Review: A Hostage Standoff Unfolds in ‘6 Days’
summary_short: Toa Fraser’s film about a hostage crisis at the Iranian Embassy in London in 1980 can feel closer to a re-enactment than a thriller.

headline: Review: Once Simply ‘Sidemen,’ Now They’re the Stars
summary_short: “Sidemen: Long Road to Glory” is a loving tribute to the bluesmen Willie Smith, Hubert Sumlin and Joe Willie Perkins.

headline: Review: ‘Patti Cake$,’ a Classic Striver’s Tale With a Hip-Hop Beat
summary_short: This showbiz tale finds new talent in Danielle Macdonald, its star, and Geremy Jasper, its writer and director.

headline: Review: ‘California Typewriter’: Preserving the Past, Key by Key
summary_short: This documentary directed by Doug Nichol plumbs the depths of devotion to a machine whose day might appear to be over.

headline: Review: ‘Logan Lucky’: Steven Soderbergh and His Motley Band of Thieves
summary_short: This class-conscious caper, with Channing Tatum and Adam Driver as down-on-their-luck brothers, is ridiculously entertaining.

headline: Review: Penélope Cruz Is Luminous in ‘The Queen of Spain’
summary_short: Fernando Trueba’s light ensemble comedy is a romp that pillories Hollywood’s deal-making with the Franco regime in the 1950s.

headline: Review: ‘The Hitman’s Bodyguard,’ With Samuel L. Jackson
summary_short: Mr. Jackson is an ill-tempered contract killer. Ryan Reynolds is his uptight protector. You can figure out the rest.

headline: Review: ‘The Nut Job 2’ Squirrels Away the Laughs for Itself
summary_short: A profiteering mayor threatens to displace a city park’s animal residents unless a grumpy squirrel named Surly can wreck his plans.

headline: Review: A True-Life Journey Into Interstellar Space in ‘The Farthest’
summary_short: Emer Reynolds’s dazzling film traces the history of Voyager 1 and Voyager 2. Like the NASA team that produced these spacecraft, it inspires awe.

headline: Review: In ‘Nocturama,’ Bored, Beautiful Terrorists With a Taste for Luxury Brands
summary_short: Bertrand Bonello’s “Nocturama” chronicles a dramatic attack in Paris, with remarkably little resonance with current events.

display_title: The Only Living Boy in New York
headline: Review: ‘The Only Living Boy in New York’ Rejects Dad’s Money but Not His Mistress
summary_short: Marc Webb’s movie has an all-star cast (Jeff Bridges, Cynthia Nixon, Pierce Brosnan). Yet it lacks a proper story for them.

headline: Review: In ‘Annabelle: Creation,’ Orphans Are Child’s Play for a Doll
summary_short: The director David F. Sandberg proves to be a master of the flash-scare as he strings together jolts in this prequel to the 2014 film “Annabelle.”

headline: Review: In ‘The Trip to Spain,’ Everything Tastes Stale
summary_short: Steve Coogan and Rob Brydon return for the latest installment in their banter-filled franchise, this time amid the glorious Iberian scenery.

headline: Review: In ‘Planetarium,’ Natalie Portman as a Medium in 1930s Paris
summary_short: A spiritualist sister act from the United States enchants a film producer in Paris in Rebecca Zlotowski’s ambitious feature.

headline: Review: Anatomy of Ferguson, From a Shooting to Activism
summary_short: The documentary “Whose Streets?” examines the protests that came after the traumatic police shooting of Michael Brown in 2014.

headline: Review: A ‘Good Time,’ if in Name Only
summary_short: Robert Pattinson plays a not-too-bright bank robber on the run in Josh and Benny Safdie’s latest film, “Good Time.”

headline: Review: ‘Ingrid Goes West,’ and Social Media Is Her Road Map
summary_short: Matt Spicer’s debut feature is a showcase for Aubrey Plaza’s comedic timing and some unbecoming online behavior.

headline: Review: ‘A Taxi Driver’ Honors a Humble Hero in South Korea
summary_short: Jang Hun’s drama recalls the efforts of the German TV journalist Jürgen Hinzpeter and a cabby he hired to record the Gwangju uprising in 1980.

headline: Review: In the Ireland of ‘Pilgrimage,’ Grays, Not Greens, and Death
summary_short: The story, set in 1209, finds a group of monks safeguarding a holy relic as they transport it across a violent countryside.

headline: Review: Woody Harrelson as a Wild and Crazy Dad in ‘The Glass Castle’
summary_short: Adapted from Jeannette Walls’s best-selling memoir of her chaotic childhood, a movie decides to play it safe.

headline: Review: Staying Together ‘After Love’ and Regretting Every Moment
summary_short: A couple break up, but remain together, frustratingly, because of the husband’s financial woes.

headline: Review: Murder Mystery on the Reservation in ‘Wind River’
summary_short: A rookie investigator meets her match while investigating a murder on an Indian reservation.

headline: Review: Modernism’s Promise and an Auspicious Feature Debut in ‘Columbus’
summary_short: The video essayist Kogonada uses architecture to pose larger questions in a small Indiana town.

headline: Review: In ‘This Time Tomorrow,’ a Family Will Be Upended
summary_short: Lina Rodriguez’s film, about a family of three in Colombia, is more consequential than it first appears.

headline: Review: ‘Fun Mom Dinner’ Means a Night Out Without the Kids
summary_short: In this comedy, Toni Collette, Molly Shannon, Bridget Everett and Katie Aselton are out to prove that mothers can have fun, too.

headline: Review: ‘4 Days in France,’ With a Little Help From Grindr
summary_short: In a director’s feature debut, an impulsive wanderer flees Paris for adventures in rural France.

headline: Review: ‘Chronically Metropolitan,’ and Hopelessly Self-Indulgent
summary_short: The movie, featuring high-income characters in low-stakes situations, finds a writer returning home to Manhattan to win back a lost love.

headline: Review: In ‘Brave New Jersey,’ a Martian Invasion That Wasn’t
summary_short: Jody Lambert’s lighthearted comedy about the panic in a fictitious town after “The War of the Worlds” radio drama in 1938.

headline: Review: In ‘Armed Response,’ a Prison Has a Mind of Its Own
summary_short: This action-horror hybrid by John Stockwell flirts with intriguing ideas but betrays them with flat characters and undercooked pyrotechnics.

headline: Review: In ‘Step,’ Baltimore Teenagers on the Cusp of Womanhood
summary_short: Three high school seniors balance applying to college and devoting time to rehearsing for a major dance competition.

headline: Review: The Good, the Bad and the Stupid in ‘The Dark Tower’
summary_short: Idris Elba and Matthew McConaughey star in “The Dark Tower,” a mess of a movie based on Stephen King’s sprawling, multivolume series of the same title.

headline: Review: A Heist Goes Bad, and the Bloodletting Begins in ‘68 Kill’
summary_short: This absurdly morbid comedy doesn’t take itself too seriously, and hopes viewers won’t, either, as bodies pile up and the violence never tones down.

headline: Review: Halle Berry’s ‘Kidnap’ Takes Maternal Revenge to the Road
summary_short: This thriller follows a mother in pursuit of the kidnappers who have taken her son. “Wherever you go, I will be right behind you,” she seethes.

headline: Review: ‘It’s Not Yet Dark,’ an Inspirational Journey by a Man With A.L.S.
summary_short: This documentary takes you into the mind and body of a young filmmaker, Simon Fitzmaurice, who wakes each morning closer to total paralysis.

headline: Review: In ‘Icarus,’ Unexpectedly Exploring the Russian Doping Scandal
summary_short: “Icarus” was going to be a sort of “Super Size Me” film about steroids but switched gears when Russia was accused of helping Olympic athletes cheat.

display_title: An Inconvenient Sequel: Truth to Power
headline: Review: ‘An Inconvenient Sequel,’ With Al Gore Keeping the Pressure On
summary_short: A follow-up to “An Inconvenient Truth,” with new information on climate change and even some positive developments.

headline: Review: In ‘Detroit,’ Black Lives Caught in a Prehistory of the Alt-Right
summary_short: Kathryn Bigelow’s new movie, set amid the Detroit riots of 1967, grapples with the legacy of American racism.

headline: Review: ‘Rebels on Pointe,’ and in Tutus
summary_short: The Ballets Russes de Monte Carlo meld technique with comedy, and tour more than two-thirds of the years

headline: Review: Two Unlikely Roommates Share Heartbreak in ‘Crash Pad’
summary_short: A slacker, his lover and his lover’s husband make a sticky love triangle in this awkward comedy.

display_title: Take Every Wave: The Life of Laird Hamilton
headline: Review: A Daredevil Optimist in ‘Take Every Wave’
summary_short: This documentary about Laird Hamilton, conqueror of big waves, stirs up most of its sporadic excitement with its surfing footage.

headline: Review: Why the New ‘Flatliners’ Is Just ‘Meh’
