summary_short: The original starred Julia Roberts, Kiefer Sutherland and Kevin Bacon, among others. The new one has Ellen Page and some horror movie tricks.

headline: Review: A Cranky Loner Faces Mortality in ‘Lucky’
summary_short: In one of his last roles, Harry Dean Stanton shines as a cantankerous old man.

headline: Review: ‘Let’s Play Two’ Takes Pearl Jam Out to the Ball Game
summary_short: Blending concert film and sports diary, Danny Clinch chronicles Pearl Jam’s pair of shows at Wrigley Field during the Cubs’ championship season.

headline: Review: ‘American Made’ Has Tom Cruise. And Lies, Spies and Coke.
summary_short: Mr. Cruise plays a real-life pilot turned smuggler who worked for the C.I.A., in Doug Liman’s new movie.

display_title: Mark Felt: The Man Who Brought Down the White House
headline: Review: In ‘Mark Felt,’ Liam Neeson Is the Man Known as Deep Throat
summary_short: Peter Landesman’s accidentally timely Watergate procedural has men in suits fighting for the independence of the F.B.I.

headline: Review: A Violent Accident Rocks a Friendship in ‘Super Dark Times’
summary_short: Kevin Phillips’s direction and fine acting from the cast elevate this tale centered on two high schoolers coping with tragedy.

headline: Review: In ‘Realive,’ a Man Is Reanimated in 2084
summary_short: This above-average science-fiction film, written and directed by Mateo Gil, plays like a “Black Mirror” episode combined with a solemn love story.

headline: Review: ‘Blood Stripe’ Finds a Woman Back From War, and Still Fighting
summary_short: A former Marine returns home and battles with post-traumatic stress in this film.

headline: Review: Robert Redford and Jane Fonda Are Neighbors With Benefits in ‘Our Souls at Night’
summary_short: This small-town romance was adapted from the novel by Kent Haruf.

headline: Review: ‘Bugs’ Is a Culinary Adventure. Insects Never Looked so Yummy.
summary_short: Ben Reade and Josh Evans travel the world to visit cultures where insects are prepared as food.

headline: Review: Advantage, Bobby, but Game, Set, Match, Billie Jean in ‘Battle of the Sexes’
summary_short: Emma Stone plays Billie Jean King and Steve Carell plays Bobby Riggs in a movie about the 1973 tennis match that became a referendum on equality.

headline: Review: Jake Gyllenhaal in ‘Stronger’ Loses His Legs in the Boston Bombing
summary_short: With raw emotion, David Gordon Green’s “Stronger” tells the true tale of Jeff Bauman, catastrophically injured as he watched the 2013 marathon.

headline: Review: ‘Loving Vincent’ Paints van Gogh in His Own Images
summary_short: An innovative biopic explores the Dutch painter’s last days, with the people he rendered on canvas being brought to uncanny life.

headline: Review: ‘Victoria and Abdul,’ a Royal Friendship in a Nest of Vipers
summary_short: “Victoria and Abdul” sees a queen in a life-changing relationship with a Muslim Indian man.

headline: Review: ‘Unrest,’ a Personal Account of Chronic Fatigue Syndrome
summary_short: In this film, Jennifer Brea describes her life that Chronic Fatigue Syndrome hijacked.

headline: Review: Lady Gaga Unplugged, Sort Of, in ‘Gaga: Five Foot Two’
summary_short: This documentary depicts Lady Gaga as a disciplined, accomplished performer, but one who inhabits a peculiar isolation despite her fame.

headline: Review: A Sweet Immigrant Story in ‘The Tiger Hunter’
summary_short: It’s 1979 and one aspiring engineer is ready for America and to win over his childhood sweetheart.

headline: Review: ‘The Lego Ninjago Movie’ Sticks to the Instruction Manual
summary_short: A father, a son and the battle to save a snapped-together city.

headline: Review: In ‘Kingsman: The Golden Circle,’ the Natty Spies Are Back
summary_short: This espionage sequel is an emotionally sterile lark, its wounds inflicted with a smirk and a shrug, even if it’s Sir Elton John in the cross hairs.

headline: Review: Grieving Among the Redwoods in a Pretty but Dull ‘Woodshock’
summary_short: Kirsten Dunst stars in the hallucinatory first feature from the founders of Rodarte, Kate and Laura Mulleavy.

headline: Review: Ben Stiller Is a Dad With a Bruised Ego in ‘Brad’s Status’
summary_short: Mike White’s empty-nest comedy starring Ben Stiller is both cringy and kindhearted.

headline: Review: Hey, Jack Reacher and Jason Bourne. Room for One More?
summary_short: “American Assassin,” the first adaptation of a series of thrillers, stars Dylan O’Brien as a rogue C.I.A. killer and Michael Keaton as grizzled mentor.

headline: Review: Love of Il Maestro Drives ‘In Search of Fellini’
summary_short: A sheltered young woman enamored of the films of the famous director sets off to Italy to meet him.

display_title: Manolo: The Boy Who Made Shoes for Lizards
headline: Review: Watch Manolo Blahnik Make Famous Friends — and Shoes
summary_short: A new documentary about the famed designer could use more of the shoes for which he’s renowned.

headline: Review: ‘Strong Island’ Explores a Killing and Its Aftermath
summary_short: The documentary looks at William Ford Jr., an unarmed black man who was killed by a white man who was never charged.

headline: Review: ‘Alina’ Is the Work of an Indie Film Veteran, New at Directing
summary_short: Ben Barenholtz kick-started the career of David Lynch. But his first fiction feature shows he has not mastered directing.

display_title: First They Killed My Father: A Daughter of Cambodia Remembers
headline: Review: In Angelina Jolie’s New Movie, a Child’s-Eye View of War
summary_short: “First They Killed My Father” depicts life under the Khmer Rouge in a film taken from Loung Ung’s memoir.

headline: Review: ‘Mother!’ Is a Divine Comedy, Dressed as a Psychological Thriller
summary_short: Jennifer Lawrence and Javier Bardem portray a couple in Darren Aronofsky’s film, a religious allegory with visual wit and dexterous camera work.

headline: Review: For the Wild Things in ‘Trophy,’ Life Has a Price
summary_short: This thoughtful documentary raises tough questions about big-game hunting and wildlife conservation.

headline: Review: ‘Nobody’s Watching,’ an Actor’s Immigration and Alienation
summary_short: An Argentine actor, played by Guillermo Pfening, pins his hopes on a movie career in America.

headline: Review: All Is Not Well in ‘Company Town’
summary_short: Sick residents, environmental pollution and questions of corporate accountability in a small town in Arkansas.

headline: Review: In ‘School Life,’ Teachers Who Make All the Difference
summary_short: A documentary captures the routines of an Irish boarding school and two of its cherished teachers.

headline: Review: In ‘The Limehouse Golem,’ Bawdy Limericks and Bloody Corpses
summary_short: Bill Nighy pursues a serial killer in 19th-century London in Juan Carlos Medina’s film.

headline: Review: ‘Year by the Sea’ in Search of Answers to Life’s Riddles
summary_short: A crisis in her marriage sends a woman, played by Karen Allen, to Cape Cod to reflect.

headline: Review: ‘Rebel in the Rye’ Looks at the Creation of Salinger’s Classic
summary_short: Years after “The Catcher in the Rye” came out, Hollywood was still salivating over it. This film takes a step back to examine the author.

headline: Review: No Right Way to Keep the Faith in ‘The Good Catholic’
summary_short: A promising young priest finds life outside of service, to the detriment of his profession.

headline: Review: In ‘Home Again,’ an Imitation of Life (and Mom)
summary_short: Reese Witherspoon plays cute and single in a mirthless romantic comedy in a movie by Hallie Meyers-Shyer, the daughter of Nancy Meyers and Charles Shyer.

headline: Review: ‘It’ Brings Back Stephen King’s Killer Clown
summary_short: This new, updated adaptation follows a bunch of kids on the trail of an evil force.

headline: Review: In ‘Spettacolo,’ a Tuscan Town Where All the World’s a Stage
summary_short: A documentary about Monticchiello in Italy, where each year the residents put on a play about their most urgent concerns.

headline: Review: ‘Tulip Fever’ Delivers a Wilted Period Piece
summary_short: Alicia Vikander, Dane DeHaan and Christoph Waltz star in this much-delayed film about an overripe love triangle in 17th-century Amsterdam.

headline: Review: ‘Kill Me Please,’ a Summer of Murder and Teenage Kicks
summary_short: Murdered women arouse adolescent hormones in this gorgeous Brazilian thriller.

headline: Review: ‘Hazlo Como Hombre’ Mistakes Manhood for Intolerance
summary_short: In this romantic comedy, a man can’t handle his best friend’s revelation that he’s gay, throwing their circle of friends and family into disarray.

headline: Review: In ‘Viceroy’s House,’ the Birthing Pains of Two Nations
summary_short: This film is a handsome, fleet look at the months leading up to the end of British colonial rule in India.

headline: Review: In ‘I Do ... Until I Don’t,’ Love and Loathing in Florida
summary_short: Three married couples outwit a documentary filmmaker in Lake Bell’s sex comedy.

headline: Review: ‘Unlocked,’ a New Spy Thriller, Same as the Old Spy Thrillers
summary_short: Noomi Rapace plays an undercover C.I.A. agent in a film that serves up clichés with its suspense.

headline: Review: In ‘Jesús,’ a Delinquent Teenager in Trouble Too Deep to Handle
summary_short: The actions of troubled teenage boys have dire consequences in this Chilean drama.

headline: Review: Glib Laughs and Race Hate in ‘Suburbicon’
summary_short: George Clooney stays off camera to direct Matt Damon and Julianne Moore in a caustic comedy about the good old American days of fear, hate and rage.

headline: Review: Lena Olin Is Fierce as a Suicidal Poet in ‘Maya Dardel’
summary_short: A character who wants to play with power in a movie that reeks of scholarly pretension.

headline: Review: ‘Mully’ Is a Man Dedicated to Saving Kenya’s Orphans
summary_short: A documentary looks at Charles Mully, who gave up great wealth to aid the poor and homeless in his country.

headline: Review: In ‘All I See Is You,’ Sight Is Restored and a Marriage Rocked
summary_short: This psychodrama from Marc Forster stars Blake Lively and Jason Clarke as a seemingly happy married couple.

headline: Review: In ‘Thank You for Your Service,’ the War at Home
summary_short: The film, from the screenwriter of “American Sniper,” is an earnest and powerful drama about Iraq veterans returning to Kansas.

headline: Review: ‘The Divine Order’ Recalls the Fight for Women’s Suffrage in Switzerland
summary_short: Set in 1971, Petra Volpe’s film takes a middlebrow, mildly rollicking approach toward a serious subject.

display_title: Joan Didion: The Center Will Not Hold
headline: Review: A ‘Joan Didion’ Portrait, From an Intimate Source
summary_short: This documentary is directed by Griffin Dunne, Ms. Didion’s nephew, a relationship that limits the movie in certain ways, but opens it up in others.

headline: Review: Love Is Wild, if Not Pretty, in ‘God’s Own Country’
summary_short: This feature debut of the writer and director Francis Lee is a bracing, sometimes brutal movie.

headline: Review: In ‘Geostorm,’ Gerard Butler (and His Stubble) Save the Planet
summary_short: In this action film, the world is threatened by a space-based weather-control system armed with ice, fire, hail and heavy rain.

display_title: Tyler Perry's Boo 2! A Madea Halloween
headline: Review: A Case of Déjà Vu in ‘Tyler Perry’s Boo 2! A Madea Halloween’
summary_short: In this sequel that feels like a remake, all prospects for amusement are never even vaguely realized.

headline: Review: ‘Wonderstruck,’ Todd Haynes’s Imitations of Life
summary_short: Mr. Haynes’s lovely adaptation of Brian Selznick’s book centers on a girl in the 1920s and a boy in the ’70s whose lives are mysteriously connected.

headline: Review: ‘Only the Brave’ Is an Inspiring Tale of Firefighter Sacrifice
summary_short: This action drama from Joseph Kosinski — about the Granite Mountain Hotshots of Prescott, Ariz. — offers some real feeling under a schematic surface.

headline: Review: Uncovering a Displaced Family’s Past in ‘Aida’s Secrets’
summary_short: This documentary follows Izak Szewelewicz, who was sent to Israel as a toddler after World War II, on a search for the brother he didn’t know he had.

headline: Review: ‘The Snowman’ Is a Thrill-Free Thriller Tied in Knots
summary_short: Michael Fassbender and other talented people wander through this leaden mess.

headline: Review: In ‘Tragedy Girls,’ Teenagers Terrorize (and Tweet)
summary_short: In this slasher comedy, two high school social media stars find that murder is the best way to drum up followers for their online horror brand.

headline: Review: ‘One of Us,’ a Portrait of Starting a New Life
summary_short: This documentary, directed by Heidi Ewing and Rachel Grady, follows three ultra-Orthodox Jews who have left the Hasidic community.

headline: Review: In ‘Dealt,’ a Magician Never Shows His Hand (Until He Does)
summary_short: This documentary focuses on the hyperkinetic card magician Richard Turner.

headline: Review: Secrets and Lies in ‘Never Here’
summary_short: This film, which features Sam Shepard in his final, all-too-brief screen role, plays more like an experimental art project.

headline: Review: Braving Foot Rot and Fire Ants in the Amazon ‘Jungle’
summary_short: Daniel Radcliffe suffers for his art in this true-life survival tale about the Israeli adventurer Yossi Ghinsberg.

headline: Review: The Crushed Romanticism of Philippe Garrel’s ‘L’Enfant Secret’
summary_short: A film that opened in Paris in 1979 finally surfaces in the United States.

display_title: Professor Marston and the Wonder Women
headline: Review: ‘Professor Marston,’ With Kinks! Pleasures! Female Power!
summary_short: In “Professor Marston and the Wonder Women,” the writer-director Angela Robinson tells a knotty story with wit, sympathy and economy.

headline: Review: Reliving Delicious Terror in ‘78/52: Hitchcock’s Shower Scene’
summary_short: A documentary by Alexandre O. Philippe finds plenty to examine in one of the most memorable scenes in American film.

headline: Review: Two Hoarders Clean House in ‘Thy Father’s Chair’
summary_short: The mess that two Brooklyn brothers make of their house in this documentary is unholy in several senses of the term.

headline: Review: In ‘Marshall,’ a Legal Pioneer Gives History a Shove
summary_short: Reginald Hudlin’s movie about the crusading lawyer and Supreme Court Justice Thurgood Marshall smartly keeps the focus tight.

headline: Review: ‘Te Ata’ Shares a Heroic Story of a Chickasaw Ambassador
summary_short: A biopic about the rise of a Native American performer who overcame discriminatory laws to perform on Broadway and in the White House.

headline: Review: Jackie Chan Seeks Vengeance in ‘The Foreigner’
summary_short: He plays an aggrieved father facing off against Pierce Brosnan, who plays a character with possible links to the I.R.A.

headline: Review: In ‘For Ahkeem,’ a Last Option for a Troubled Teenager
summary_short: A documentary observes a St. Louis student facing a bleak future if she can’t graduate from an alternative school.

headline: Review: A Cheery Portrait of Severe Disability in ‘Breathe’
summary_short: The disability-rights pioneer Robin Cavendish is given an upbeat biopic in “Breathe,” starring Andrew Garfield and Claire Foy.

headline: Review: In ‘The Departure,’ Watching Over Those Who Flirt With Death
summary_short: This documentary follows a Buddhist priest who counsels those who are in danger of committing suicide.

headline: Review: Dead Again … and Again in ‘Happy Death Day’
summary_short: A mean coed relives her own murder multiple times in this snappy horror-comedy.

headline: Review: Adam Sandler Is a Revelation in ‘The Meyerowitz Stories’
summary_short: A career high, and not just for this film’s writer and director, Noah Baumbach.

headline: Review: ‘Brawl in Cell Block 99’ Features a Revelatory Vince Vaughn
summary_short: Mr. Vaughn plays a reluctant avenger in this vicious thriller from the director of “Bone Tomahawk.”

headline: Review: Paul Farmer Works to Heal Haiti in ‘Bending the Arc’
summary_short: This feel-good documentary dives into global health care with the same optimism as its subjects, two founders of Partners in Health.

display_title: The Death and Life of Marsha P. Johnson
headline: Review: ‘The Death and Life of Marsha P. Johnson’ Explores a Mystery
summary_short: The documentary, by David France, looks at the death of the transgender activist. Police say it was suicide; friends suspect it was murder.

headline: Review: Love in a Cold Climate in ‘The Mountain Between Us’
summary_short: Idris Elba and Kate Winslet crash into a mountain — and each other — in this drama.

headline: Review: In ‘Walking Out,’ Two Men Go Hunting; Who Knows Who’ll Come Back
summary_short: The film follows a father and son who trek into the Montana wilderness, only to encounter danger.

headline: ‘Overdrive,’ a Car Thief Movie That Could Use a Script Tuneup
summary_short: Scott Eastwood and Freddie Thorp star as brothers and car thieves in this action film.

headline: Review: In the Documentary ‘Dina,’ a Differently Abled Love Story
summary_short: An intimate, affecting film about a couple with autism, as they plan their wedding.

headline: Review: ‘Chavela’ Recalls the Life of the Ranchera Singer Chavela Vargas
summary_short: The documentary about the singer Chavela Vargas provides a biography, but doesn’t give a strong sense of the musician’s power.

headline: Review: In ‘Blade Runner 2049,’ Hunting Replicants Amid Strangeness
summary_short: The director Denis Villeneuve tries to both honor Ridley Scott’s 1982 dystopian classic and to slip free of its considerable shadow.

headline: Review: A ‘Crooked House’ of Murder and Resentment
summary_short: Glenn Close, Julian Sands, Gillian Anderson and Christina Hendricks make up an all-star roster of suspects in this Agatha Christie adaptation.

headline: Review: In ‘Hangman,’ Al Pacino Trails a Killer With a Unique Vocabulary
summary_short: The detectives in this serial-killer thriller can’t even be bothered to solve the word puzzle.

headline: Review: In ‘32 Pills,’ a Filmmaker Investigates Her Sister’s Death
summary_short: Hope Litoff’s documentary becomes more voyeuristically gripping as it progresses.

headline: Review: ‘Naples ’44’ Chronicles Life During Wartime
summary_short: Taken from a British intelligence officer’s memoir, and narrated by Benedict Cumberbatch, this film paints a portrait of the occupied city.

headline: Review: ‘Eric Clapton: A Life in 12 Bars,’ of Triumphs and Tragedies
summary_short: A documentary on the life of Eric Clapton is candid on the rock legend’s struggles with addiction.

headline: Review: ‘Cuba and the Cameraman’ Lavishes Love on a Country … and Castro
summary_short: The filmmaker Jon Alpert has been visiting and documenting Cuba for 45 years. His new movie looks back fondly at its people and its leader.

headline: Review: ‘Al Di Qua,’ Homelessness Through an Artsy Filter
summary_short: In this film, Turin’s poorest tell their stories to the camera.

headline: Review: A Boy’s Own Desire in ‘Call Me by Your Name’
summary_short: In the latest movie from the Italian director Luca Guadagnino (“I Am Love”), Armie Hammer plays a visiting student who falls for his host’s teenage son.

headline: Review: ‘Darkest Hour,’ or the Great Man Theory of History (and Acting)
summary_short: Gary Oldman plays Winston Churchill in Joe Wright’s drama about the early days of World War II.

headline: Review: ‘Coco’ Brings the Pixar Touch to Death
summary_short: The movie delivers moments of cinematic rigor and playful pop-culture erudition. And though it deals with the afterlife, don’t let that scare you.

headline: Review: In ‘The Man Who Invented Christmas,’ Dickens as a Secret Documentarian
summary_short: This drama purports that Charles Dickens took inspiration for his fictional characters from real-life encounters.

headline: Review: In ‘Mr. Roosevelt,’ an Ailing Cat and a Comedian in Crisis
summary_short: Noël Wells wrote, directed and stars in this film about a young woman who returns to her former home and discovers much has changed.

headline: Review: ‘Mudbound’ Is a Racial Epic Tuned to Black Lives, and White Guilt
summary_short: Dee Rees’s new film illuminates the daily cruelties in post-World War II Mississippi.

display_title: Jim & Andy: The Great Beyond - Featuring a Very Special, Contractually Obligated Mention of Tony Clifton
headline: Review: ‘Jim & Andy,’ When Carrey Became Kaufman
summary_short: In his documentary about Jim Carrey, Andy Kaufman and the making of “Man on the Moon,” the director Chris Smith finds multiple realities and laughs.

headline: Review: In ‘The Breadwinner,’ a Girl Bravely Provides for Her Family
summary_short: The children in this animated film based on a novel by Deborah Ellis navigate life under the Taliban.

headline: Review: In ‘Wonder,’ a Not-So-Ordinary Boy Makes His Way
summary_short: Auggie, the little boy in this smart and warmhearted family film, is inspirational in his differences.

headline: Review: ‘Wet Woman in the Wind’ Is a Queasy Sex Romp
summary_short: Let’s make no bones about it: This film, part of a project to reboot a Japanese soft-core genre, is designed to appeal to male prurient interest.

headline: Review: In ‘Roman J. Israel, Esq.,’ Denzel Washington as a Lawyer Out of His Element
summary_short: Dan Gilroy’s new film about a socially awkward jurist misfires when it appoints him as a sort of angelic figure.

headline: Review: ‘Cook Off!’ Gives Chefs the ‘Best in Show’ Treatment
summary_short: This mockumentary about a cooking competition features Melissa McCarthy but is being released 10 years after it was first shown at a comedy festival.

headline: Review: ‘Justice League,’ Better Than the Last One!
summary_short: In this superhero jamboree, the Flash, Aquaman and Cyborg sign on with the DC Comics team leaders Batman and Wonder Woman. (Psst … where’s Superman?)

headline: Review: In ‘Song of Granite,’ Fragments of an Irish Folk Singer’s Life
summary_short: This biography of the singer Joe Heaney seems uncertain of what made him tick.

headline: Review: ‘I Remember You’ Is a Piercing Horror Film From Iceland
summary_short: The director Oskar Thor Axelsson prefers mood and compelling human conflict over copious gore to deliver chills. The result is effective.

headline: Review: In ‘Bitch,’ a Desperate Housewife Finds Her Bark
summary_short: Jason Ritter plays a husband whose wife goes to the dogs in this feminist horror-comedy.

display_title: Window Horses: The Poetic Persian Epiphany of Rosie Ming
headline: Review: ‘Window Horses’ Animates a Young Poet’s Self-Discovery
summary_short: Ann Marie Fleming’s film explores the passions of a sheltered poet who travels to Shiraz, Iran, for a poetry festival.

headline: Review: In ‘Daddy’s Home 2,’ Father Doesn’t Know Best
summary_short: Mel Gibson gets off lightly as a crass paterfamilias in this comedy sequel to the hit starring Will Ferrell and Mark Wahlberg.

headline: Review: ‘Intent to Destroy’ Shows That the Armenian Past Is Not Over
summary_short: This documentary, directed by Joe Berlinger, explores the Armenian genocide through old footage of survivors and insights from historians.

headline: Review: A Virus Creates ‘Mayhem’ Among Backstabbing Lawyers
summary_short: “Mayhem,” featuring the “Walking Dead” actor Steven Yeun, embraces its pulpy title with fighting-and-fornicating glee.

headline: Review: On Violence and the Pain of Others in ‘Three Billboards’
summary_short: A ferocious Frances McDormand plays a grieving mother seeking justice in Martin McDonagh’s movie, which mixes tears and tragedy with corrosive laughs.

headline: Review: An All-Star ‘Murder on the Orient Express’ With Few Surprises
summary_short: Kenneth Branagh assembles Judi Dench, Johnny Depp, Michelle Pfeiffer and others for his film remake of Agatha Christie’s mystery novel.

headline: Review: ‘Hello Again,’ a Movie Musical Ode to Love and Lust Over Decades
summary_short: This film from Tom Gustafson, based on a 1993 Off Broadway show, has a formidable cast of Broadway names but wants for dramatic traction.

headline: Review: ‘Most Beautiful Island,’ an Immigrant’s New York Nightmare
summary_short: This suspense film, about a woman entering a rabbit hole of urban peril, is an effective writing-directing debut for Ana Asensio, who also stars.

headline: Review: ‘LBJ’ Hides Its Light Under a Bushel of Makeup
summary_short: Woody Harrelson swaggers through this movie, which tries to track the coming into consciousness of Lyndon B. Johnson.

headline: Review: ‘Along for the Ride,’ an Artist Through the Eyes of an Assistant
summary_short: Dennis Hopper’s life could be seen as a wild ride, on and off the screen. Someone who was by Hopper’s side interprets his story.

headline: Review: ‘My Friend Dahmer,’ the Boy Who Became a Cannibal
summary_short: The story of the making of a monster.

headline: Review: ‘A Gray State,’ Behind a Filmmaker’s Madness
summary_short: Erik Nelson’s documentary centers on the aspiring filmmaker David Crowley, whose violent death became a cause for conspiracy theorists.

headline: Review: In ‘Wait for Your Laugh’ and ‘Gilbert,’ Comedians Work Hard
summary_short: These documentaries go behind the scenes with their well-known subjects, Rose Marie and Gilbert Gottfried.

headline: Review: Bad Grandmoms Show Up for ‘A Bad Moms Christmas’
summary_short: Christine Baranski, Cheryl Hines and Susan Sarandon join the cast for a sequel to “Bad Moms.”

headline: Review: Sorcery and Revenge Fuel ‘Blade of the Immortal’
summary_short: A brokenhearted girl and an undying samurai team up in Takashi Miike’s film.

headline: Review: In ‘11/8/16,’ Looking at Election Day, After the Race Is Run
summary_short: The documentary followed more than 16 people to the polls on Election Day to learn about their thoughts and feelings on the candidates.

headline: Review: ‘It Happened in L.A.,’ All That Questing After Love
summary_short: This ensemble comedy from Michelle Morgan concerns one woman who exits a relationship, and another who seeks one. Their city only complicates matters.

headline: Review: In ‘No Dress Code Required,’ a Gay Couple’s Mexicali Blues
summary_short: Cristina Herrera Borquez’s documentary follows Victor Aguirre and Fernando Urias in their bureaucratic battle to be legally married.

headline: Review: ‘Last Flag Flying’ Is a Starry, Somber and Comic War Movie
summary_short: Three Vietnam vets — played by Steve Carell, Bryan Cranston and Laurence Fishburne — reunite during the Iraq war to accomplish a grim mission.

headline: Review: ‘Thor: Ragnarok,’ of Gods, Monsters and Silly Jokes
summary_short: In the newest, loosest, goofiest and funniest Thor blowout, Chris Hemsworth’s superhero chillaxes with the Hulk and takes a punch from a Valkyrie.

headline: Review: Greta Gerwig’s ‘Lady Bird’ Is Big-Screen Perfection
summary_short: Saoirse Ronan plays a high school senior who insists on asserting her individuality, and it makes for a thrilling film.

headline: Review: ‘The Light of the Moon’ and the Trauma of Rape
summary_short: Stephanie Beatriz plays a young woman who learns to survive after a night out ends in a brutal attack in this drama from Jessica M. Thompson.

headline: Review: In ‘1945,’ Hungarian Villagers Are Forced to Revisit Wartime Sins
summary_short: Ferenc Torok’s lean feature is a Holocaust film built, consciously or not, on a reversal of the tropes of the western.

headline: Review: ‘Frank Serpico’ Updates the Story of the Man Behind a Classic Movie
summary_short: The real Frank Serpico proves to be a compelling figure in a documentary that picks up where the classic Hollywood film left off.

headline: Review: ‘In the Fade’ Is a Tale of Grief and Violence in Modern Germany
summary_short: In Fatih Akin’s new film, Diane Kruger plays a Hamburg woman who fights for justice and sanity after the murder of her husband and son.

display_title: All the Money in the World
headline: Review: Christopher Plummer Dominates ‘All the Money in the World’
summary_short: Mr. Plummer, who replaced Kevin Spacey in the role of J. Paul Getty, is magnetic in the film, which recounts the 1973 kidnapping of his grandson.

headline: Review: Daniel Day-Lewis Sews Up Another Great Performance in ‘Phantom Thread’
summary_short: Paul Thomas Anderson’s latest film is a luxuriant love story set in 1950s London.

headline: Review: In ‘Happy End,’ Another Unhappy Family From Michael Haneke
summary_short: Isabelle Huppert, Toby Jones and Mathieu Kassovitz make up a remarkable ensemble cast. But “Happy End” belongs to Jean-Louis Trintignant.

headline: Review: In ‘Father Figures,’ Ed Helms and Owen Wilson on a Hunt for Dad
summary_short: This film about two brothers searching for their real father can’t decide whether it’s a gross-out comedy or an uplifting tale of brotherly love.

headline: Review: ‘Bright’ Has Fairies, Orcs, Elves and L.A. Cops, but Little Magic
summary_short: David Ayer’s urban action film is a loud, ungainly hybrid that does not serve police procedurals or fantasy spectaculars very well.

headline: Review: In ‘Downsizing,’ Matt Damon Sweats the Small Stuff
summary_short: Alexander Payne looks at the big picture in his new movie.

headline: Review: In ‘A German Life,’ Goebbels’s Secretary Explains Her Actions
summary_short: Did Goebbels’s secretary do anything more than type? This documentary lets viewers judge.

display_title: Along With the Gods: The Two Worlds
headline: Review: ‘Along With the Gods’ Is a Fantasy Journey With C.G.I. at Every Turn
summary_short: This delirious fantasy from Kim Yong-hwa, adapted from a web comic, buries story clarity and emotional depth under a mountain of visual pyrotechnics.

headline: Review: ‘Pitch Perfect 3’ Keeps the Songs but Loses the Plot
summary_short: The latest entry in this movie series fares best when its director treats it as a fantastical buddy comedy.

headline: Review: In ‘The Greatest Showman,’ a P.T. Barnum Smaller Than Life
summary_short: The film has the ingredients of a splashy good time — the charismatic Hugh Jackman, for one — but it fast becomes a standard-issue holiday biopic.

headline: Review: ‘Jumanji: Welcome to the Jungle’ Has Dwayne Johnson as a Nerd
summary_short: The magical game is back, and this time it’s turning geeks into action heroes and jocks into zoologists.

headline: Review: ‘Permanent,’ About the Hairstyle, Falls Flat
summary_short: Rainn Wilson and Patricia Arquette play the parents of a girl who gets the titular treatment in this unsuccessful comedy.

headline: Review: ‘The Rape of Recy Taylor’ Takes a Deep Dive Into Systemic Injustice
summary_short: Nancy Buirski’s film is one of multiple layers and marvelous gumption.

headline: Review: In ‘Soufra,’ a Women-Run Food Truck Grows in Lebanon
summary_short: This documentary from Thomas Morgan, about a female entrepreneur establishing a business just south of Beirut, is a stirring tale of empowerment.

headline: Review: ‘Birdboy,’ a Disturbing Animated Feature from Spain
summary_short: The movie has talking animals, but it’s not necessarily for kids.

headline: Review: ‘Ferdinand’ Delivers a Timeless Be-Yourself Message
summary_short: Ferdinand, the picture-book bull that is actually quite tame, gets new life in a computer-animated adaptation from Carlos Saldanha.

headline: Review: A Sci-Fi Thriller, ‘Beyond Skyline’ Is Beyond Ridiculous
summary_short: Liam O’Donnell’s genre-hopping film takes its characters from Los Angeles to Laos, but risks losing its audience along the way.

headline: Review: ‘Killing for Love’ Revisits a Virginia Murder Case
summary_short: The true-crime documentary lays out a persuasive case for reasonable doubt in the case against Jens Soering, who was convicted, along with his girlfriend.

headline: Review: Layabouts Behind a Wedding Lens in ‘Sundowners’
summary_short: In this droll comedy from Pavan Moondi, a pair of feckless layabouts are assigned to video-record a wedding at a Mexican resort. Mishaps ensue.

headline: Review: Emotional ‘Desolation’ and Woodland Horror
summary_short: This psycho-in-the-woods tale benefits from sensitive writing and organic performances.

headline: Review: The Sidekick as Hero in ‘The Ballad of Lefty Brown’
summary_short: Bill Pullman stars in this Montana-set western, which tips its cowboy hat to classics of the genre.

headline: Review: ‘Star Wars: The Last Jedi’ Embraces the Magic and Mystery
summary_short: With charm and wit, the latest “Star Wars” movie unites the past and present as it looks toward the future.

headline: Review: In ‘Miss Kiet’s Children,’ Refugees Adjust to Dutch Life
summary_short: The documentary by Petra Lataster-Czisch and Peter Lataster follows young students in the classroom but doesn’t examine their lives outside school.

headline: Review: ‘Just Getting Started’ Has Big Names, Not Big Laughs
summary_short: The writer-director Ron Shelton returns to his favorite themes in this comedy starring Morgan Freeman, Tommy Lee Jones and Rene Russo.

headline: Review: ‘Quest’ Is a Moving Portrait of an American Family
summary_short: This documentary from Jonathan Olshefski follows a North Philadelphia family through the Obama years.

headline: Review: In ‘Hollow in the Land,’ a Headstrong Woman’s Search for Answers
summary_short: When the brother of Dianna Agron’s character is accused of murder, it’s up to her to save him and their family reputation.

headline: Review: If It’s Not One Thing, It’s Your Mother in ‘Kaleidoscope’
summary_short: A toxic mother-son bond drives Rupert Jones’s glum British psychodrama.

headline: Review: ‘I, Tonya.’ I, Punching Bag. I, Punch Line.
summary_short: In this winking biopic, Margot Robbie plays the disgraced ice skater Tonya Harding.

headline: Review: ‘Bill Frisell,’ a Winning Portrait of a Very Nice Guitarist
summary_short: The director Emma Franz focuses on a musician who seems to never stop playing, featuring great collaborators of this “no drama” artist.

headline: Review: ‘Shadowman’ Traces the Rise and Fall of an ’80s Artist
summary_short: Richard Hambleton, a peer of Jean-Michel Basquiat and Keith Haring who went underground, was painting right up until his death this fall.

headline: Review: In ‘The Disaster Artist,’ How to Fail at Moviemaking
summary_short: James Franco directs and stars in this fictionalized look at the making of “The Room,” which fans call the worst movie ever made.

headline: Review: The Strange Tale of the ‘Voyeur’ and the Journalist
summary_short: This squirmy documentary follows the celebrated journalist Gay Talese’s infamous investigation of a motel owner who spied on guests.

headline: Review: ‘Wonder Wheel,’ Woody Allen’s Coney Island Memory Palace
summary_short: Kate Winslet plays an unhappily married woman whose affair with a local Romeo is derailed when he falls for her stepdaughter.

headline: Review: In ‘Sins of the Flesh,’ One Prison Replaces Another
summary_short: A drama about a prison escapee in hiding plays out against the backdrop of the 2011 demonstrations in Cairo’s Tahrir Square.

headline: Review: Strong Performances Anchor ‘The Tribes of Palos Verdes’
summary_short: Not even a move to a picture-perfect California paradise can buoy a troubled family.

headline: Review: ‘Rosa Chumbe’ Offers Little Hope for Redemption
summary_short: An alcoholic cop and her pregnant daughter are forced to reckon with their mistakes in this Peruvian drama.

headline: Review: In ‘Love Beats Rhymes,’ a Hip-Hop Artist Transformed by Poetry
summary_short: The rap luminary RZA and the hip-hop musician Azealia Banks team up for a story of rap and poetry, “Love Beats Rhymes.”

headline: Review: ‘The Dancer,’ a Glum Biopic for a Dynamic Innovator
summary_short: The film, directed by Stéphanie Di Giusto, seems genuinely hostile to its subject, the dancer Loïe Fuller, whose real-life accomplishments deserve better.

headline: Review: ‘The New Radical’ Asks, Is It O.K. to Build Your Own Gun?
summary_short: The documentary follows Cody Wilson, who published plans to create a gun using a 3-D printer.

headline: Review: ‘In Search of Israeli Cuisine’ Isn’t Just About Food
summary_short: A documentary raises provocative questions as it follows Michael Solomonov on a tour of Israel’s foodie scene.

headline: Review: In ‘Saala Khadoos,’ a Female Boxer Rises From the Streets in India
summary_short: With a rawness that dovetails with the role, the newcomer Ritika Singh stars in this Bollywood film, with her coach played by the seasoned R. Madhavan.

headline: Review: ‘Fifty Shades of Black’ Sells Sex With (Intentional) Laughs
summary_short: This satire starring and co-written by Marlon Wayans has fun with the screen adaptation of a certain best-selling book.

headline: Review: In ‘Jane Got a Gun,’ Clear Skies, Followed by a Hail of Bullets
summary_short: Natalie Portman plays a frontier wife who enlists the aid of a former lover, portrayed by Joel Edgerton, to defend her home.

headline: Review: In ‘Mountain Men,’ Two Brothers Are Forced to Work Things Out
summary_short: This Cameron Labine film features mismatched siblings and a road trip gone wrong.

headline: Review: In ‘Lazer Team,’ Bickering Losers Try to Save the World
summary_short: Four small-town idiots accidentally end up in possession of a suit of high-tech armor that is Earth’s best defense against an invasion from outer space.

headline: Review: Amos Gitai’s ‘Rabin, the Last Day’ Looks Back in Anguish
summary_short: Mr. Gitai’s new film delves into the incendiary political culture that led to the assassination of Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin of Israel in 1995.

headline: Review: ‘The Finest Hours’ Stars Chris Pine, Leading a Mission Against All Odds
summary_short: Based on a real-life 1952 rescue of men aboard a tanker in a brutal storm, this nostalgic film also features Casey Affleck as a heroic shipboard engineer.

headline: In ‘Kung Fu Panda 3,’ a New Dad Who Talks Like Bryan Cranston
summary_short: The film’s central character, voiced by Jack Black, reunites with his long-lost father just as all of China is menaced by a fearsome beast.

headline: Review: ‘The Boy,’ in Which a Doll May be Alive, or the Heroine May Be Mad
summary_short: Lauren Cohan stars in this small-cast thriller, directed by William Brent Bell, which has enough scary moments to satisfy horror fans.

headline: Review: Keanu Reeves Undertakes an Investigation in ‘Exposed’
summary_short: The appearance of angels, an unexpected birth and a violent death coincide in this drama, written by Gee Malik Linton.

headline: Review: ‘Dirty Grandpa’ Features Robert De Niro on the Prowl
summary_short: In this comedy directed by Dan Mazer, Mr. De Niro’s character cajoles his grandson to take a road trip to Florida with him in time for spring break.

headline: Review: ‘Aferim!’ Traverses an Unforgiving Romania in the 1800s
summary_short: Romania’s entry for consideration at the Academy Awards for best foreign-language film, Radu Jude’s historical drama has resonance in our present age.

headline: Review: In ‘All Mistakes Buried,’ an Addict Battles to Retrieve a Precious Necklace
summary_short: Directed by Tim McCann, the film stars Sam Trammell as a reprobate who takes on dangerous criminals in an effort to save his marriage.

headline: Review: To Be Young, Gay and Muslim in Bed-Stuy
summary_short: The Islamic taboo against homosexuality weighs on two 18-year-old Muslim best friends who are closeted in Brooklyn.

headline: Review: The Aliens Are Coming! The Aliens Are Coming!
summary_short: The extraterrestrial Others are conquering Earth. Feisty, if under-informed, teenagers decide to fight back.

headline: Review: ‘Mojave’ Looks at the Corrosive Effects of Hollywood
summary_short: The film, written and directed by William Monahan, finds a celebrity in the desert, then under siege.

headline: Review: ‘Prescription Thugs,’ a Confessional Documentary on Substance Abuse
summary_short: Chris Bell, using his own family as a window onto the subject, examines why Americans take far too many prescription drugs.

headline: Review: ‘Monster Hunt’ Features a Baby Beast on the Run With Its Surrogate Parents
summary_short: Raman Hui’s live-action and computerized hybrid, a runaway hit in China, conjures a cute newborn creature pursued by other beasts and by human bounty hunters.

headline: Review: ‘Martyrs,’ a Slashing Remake, Centers on Two Friends
summary_short: This film features women caught up in revenge, torture and the supernatural.

headline: Review: In ‘Intruders,’ a Surprise Awaits Home Invaders
summary_short: Three would-be burglars who break into a home find themselves in an unexpected game of cat and mouse with its agoraphobic owner.

headline: Review: In ‘Norm of the North,’ a Polar Bear Takes a Stand
summary_short: In this animated film, the voluble title character heads to New York to fight a proposal for condo construction in his habitat.

headline: Review: ‘Ride Along 2’ Reloads Twin Barrels of Ice Cube and Kevin Hart
summary_short: The stars reunite as mismatched police partners, now on a Miami drug lord’s trail. Ken Jeong, Olivia Munn and Sherri Shepherd lend a hand.

headline: Review: Richard Gere, ‘The Benefactor’ Who Pulls the Strings
summary_short: In ‘The Benefactor,’ Mr. Gere, who is dependent on morphine, makes others dependent on him.

headline: Review: ‘Moonwalkers,’ a Conspiracy-Theory Comedy
summary_short: This film, starring Ron Perlman and Rupert Grint, invests too much in the comedy potential of things that haven’t been funny for a long while.

display_title: 13 Hours: The Secret Soldiers of Benghazi
headline: Review: In Michael Bay’s ‘13 Hours: The Secret Soldiers of Benghazi,’ Clarity Isn’t the Objective
summary_short: Mr. Bay has moderately scaled back his extreme-cinema approach for the story about the attack on the American diplomatic mission in 2012.

headline: Review: ‘A Perfect Day’ About Aid Workers in the Balkans
summary_short: Benicio Del Toro and Tim Robbins star in this Fernando León de Aranoa’s film set in the Balkan countryside in 1995.

display_title: Troublemakers: The Story of Land Art
headline: Review: ‘Troublemakers: The Story of Land Art,’ a Documentary
summary_short: James Crump’s film looks at artists who, in the early 1960s, headed into the open spaces of North America to mold the land.

headline: Review: In ‘The Treasure,’ Digging for Something of Value in Romania
summary_short: Corneliu Porumboiu, this film’s director, waits for dramatic events to arise instead of forcing the action.

headline: Review: ‘Anesthesia’ Ponders the Meaningfulness of Life
summary_short: This film considers the cruel paradox of living amid life-enhancing technological miracles that don’t fulfill a yearning for a more purposeful existence.

headline: Review: In ‘Unlucky Plaza,’ a Comic Hostage Crisis via Tabloid Storytelling
summary_short: Ken Kwek’s debut feature, set in Singapore, centers on a hapless diner owner, loan shark, motivational speaker and other motley characters.

headline: Review: ‘The Forest’ Centers on the Search for a Twin at a Suicide Site in Japan
summary_short: Natalie Dormer plays twins, one of whom has gone missing, in this horror film by Jason Zada, set in an area near Mount Fuji where many have taken their own lives.

headline: Review: In ‘Sweaty Betty,’ Two Single Dads and Their Pals Getting Through the Day
summary_short: Joseph Frank and Zachary Reed’s first feature follows two young men, a 1,000-pound pig and a lively pit bull as they weave in and out of their neighborhood outside Washington.

headline: Review: In ‘The Himalayas,’ Two Climbers Form an Indelible Bond
summary_short: In this adventure film, an experienced climber and his protégé form a lifelong bond when they reach the world’s third highest peak together.

headline: Review: In ‘Yosemite,’ a Coming-of-Age Tale of 3 Boys in 1980s California
summary_short: Gabrielle Demeestere’s debut feature is adapted in part from stories by James Franco, who is a co-star in the movie.

headline: Review: ‘The Revenant’ Welcomes You to Paradise. Now Prepare to Fall.
summary_short: The film, directed by Alejandro G. Iñárritu and starring Leonardo DiCaprio, is based on true, terrible events in the early American West.

headline: Review: ‘The Danish Girl,’ About a Transgender Pioneer
summary_short: In Tom Hooper’s new film, Eddie Redmayne and Alicia Vikander portray the 1920s artists Einar and Gerda Wegener as Einar became Lili Elbe.

headline: Review: ‘Carol’ Explores the Sweet Science of Magnetism
summary_short: Two women fall in love in this new film from Todd Haynes, based on the Patricia Highsmith novel “The Price of Salt.”

headline: Review: ‘Room,’ Mother and Child in 100 Square Feet
summary_short: Emma Donoghue adapts her acclaimed novel of captivity for the screen, with Brie Larson and Jacob Tremblay starring.

headline: Review: In ‘The Boy and the Beast,’ Learning From Anime Animals
summary_short: Mamoru Hosoda’s fantasy tells of a runaway transported to a world whose mammals include a bear that trains him for a warrior’s life.

display_title: The Last Man on the Moon
headline: Review: ‘The Last Man on the Moon’ Is the Story of Just That
summary_short: This documentary is about Capt. Eugene Cernan, who for almost 44 years has held the distinction of being the last human being to step on the moon.

headline: Review: ‘Virus of Fear,’ a Kiss Touches Off Child Abuse Accusations
summary_short: A swimming instructor is accused of inappropriately touching a child, and battle lines are drawn among his colleagues and parents.

headline: Review: ‘A Strange Course of Events’
summary_short: A clerical worker at a hospital in Israel decides, on impulse, to visit his estranged father in Haifa.They haven’t see each other in five years.

headline: Review: ‘Marguerite & Julien,’ a Tale of Siblings in Love
summary_short: Valérie Donzelli’s film transposes the factually based, centuries-old story of incestuous French lovers to a not-quite-modern setting.

headline: Review: ‘King Georges’ Chronicles a Famed Restaurant’s Downfall
summary_short: This documentary focuses on the chef Georges Perrier and Le Bec-Fin, his Philadelphia fixture that closed in 2013 after four decades in business.

headline: Review: ‘Eddie the Eagle’ Revels in Its Underdog Status
summary_short: The film is a heavily fictionalized version of Eddie Edwards’s competition as a ski jumper at the 1988 Winter Olympics.

headline: Review: In ‘Triple 9,’ an Appealing Cast Can’t Rise Above the Violence
summary_short: The film is one of those productions in which much of the creative energy has been funneled into gaudily inventive displays of brutality.

headline: Review: In ‘Gods of Egypt,’ That Doughnut Beast Is Stepping on My Sandal
summary_short: Alex Proyas’s special-effects extravaganza, set in antiquity, is an embarrassment of kitsch riches with intermittent moments of wit.

headline: Review: In ‘The Witch,’ a Family’s Contract With God Is Tested
summary_short: Around 1630 in New England, a family leaves a plantation to settle down alone at the edge of a forest.

headline: Review: ‘Rolling Papers’ Follows The Denver Post on the Marijuana Beat
summary_short: This documentary follows Ricardo Baca and several of his writers throughout 2014 as they define their new beat.

headline: Review: In ‘Forsaken,’ the Sutherlands Bond in the Old West
summary_short: A gunslinger returns to his hometown and encounters challenges as he reconnects with his father in this film set in 1872.

headline: Review: ‘Risen,’ a Tale of Conversion Starring Joseph Fiennes
summary_short: The producers, in trying to appeal to believers and nonbelievers alike, aim for drama in the story of Clavius, a Roman army tribune.

headline: Review: ‘Snowtime!’ Tells of an Escalating Snowball War
summary_short: This animated movie, intended for a young audience, is a remake of a 1984 film called “The Dog Who Stopped the War.”

headline: Review: ‘Race’ Chronicles Jesse Owens’s Rise to Olympic Glory
summary_short: Stephen Hopkins’s film takes one of the least challenging paths in telling Owens’s story, confining its time span to three years, from 1934 to 1936.

headline: Review: ‘Fitoor’ Enlists Dickens to Tell a Hindi Love Story
summary_short: Based on “Great Expectations,” the film, directed by Abhishek Kapoor, is more Bollywood than Charles Dickens.

headline: Review: In ‘Bad Hurt,’ a Staten Island Family Struggles
summary_short: This drama, set in 1999, features post-traumatic stress disorder and other problems that are not easily solved.

headline: Review: ‘Already Tomorrow in Hong Kong,’ a Meet-Cute Romance
summary_short: Written and directed by Emily Ting, this film tells of two Americans who run into each other on the streets of a glittering city.

headline: Review: ‘How to Be Single’ Is Another Lonely-Hearts Adaptation
summary_short: This adventure, which stars Dakota Johnson, flops even with Leslie Mann and Rebel Wilson hard at work being funny.

headline: Review: In ‘Zoolander 2,’ All Is Still Vanity
summary_short: Ben Stiller’s Derek Zoolander, 15 years later, is forever pursing his lips, striking poses and practicing his telekinetic blue-steel glare.

headline: Review: ‘Deadpool,’ a Sardonic Supervillain on a Kill Mission
summary_short: This eager-to-please comic-book movie, starring Ryan Reynolds and directed by Tim Miller, is the latest entry in the Marvel universe.

headline: Review: ‘4th Man Out,’ a Film About Friendship and Coming Out
summary_short: Adam, a mechanic in his 20s who has recently come out, tries dating apps with the encouragement of his three lifelong buddies.

headline: Review: ‘Misconduct’ Stars Josh Duhamel and Anthony Hopkins in a Tale of Corporate Evil
summary_short: This action thriller, the directorial debut of Shintaro Shimosawa, also features Al Pacino as a lawyer caught in a power struggle with a corrupt pharmaceutical executive.

headline: Review: In ‘Tumbledown,’ a Book Is the Third Party in a Love Triangle
summary_short: Rebecca Hall plays the young grieving widow of an acclaimed indie-folk singer and Jason Sudeikis his brash biographer in this dramedy directed by Sean Mewshaw.

headline: Review: In ‘The Choice,’ a Sudsy Romance That Was Meant to Be
summary_short: Based on a book by Nicholas Sparks, the film stars Teresa Palmer and Benjamin Walker as a pair who fall in love amid rain-soaked trysts and ocean sunsets.

headline: Review: ‘Southbound’ Tells Five Horror Tales, All Set on a Desolate Highway
summary_short: This anthology film, by the directors Roxanne Benjamin, David Bruckner, Patrick Horvath and the collective Radio Silence, presents characters who need to escape (and can’t).

headline: Review: ‘Pride and Prejudice and Zombies’; More Tea, Dear?
summary_short: In this undead ravishing of the Jane Austen novel, Elizabeth Bennet must deal with creatures much, much worse than Mr. Darcy.

headline: Review: In ‘Hail, Caesar!’ the Coens Revisit Old Hollywood
summary_short: Joel and Ethan Coen meander in and around their Tinseltown dream factory cracking jokes in a film set a decade after Barton Fink’s meltdown.

headline: Review: ‘Only Yesterday,’ Isao Takahata’s Time-Jumping Anime
summary_short: Mr. Takahata’s 1991 feature about a woman and her younger self gets a new voice cast (including Daisy Ridley) for its release in the United States.

headline: Review: Lovingly Tending the Livestock in ‘Boone’
summary_short: A documentary observes life — births, milking and vegetable picking — on a goat farm in Oregon.

headline: Review: ‘Disturbing the Peace’ Profiles Israelis and Palestinians United Against Violence
summary_short: Combatants for Peace, a group of individuals including many former military enemies in the Middle East, seeks solutions to the region’s agonized convulsions.

headline: Review: In ‘Making a Killing,’ Guns Do Slay People, Children Included
summary_short: This documentary focuses on the role of the National Rifle Association in blocking legislation to tighten gun laws.

headline: Review: ‘Fastball,’ on the Mechanics and Poetry of a Pitch
summary_short: This documentary, written and directed by Jonathan Hock, offers a batter’s point of view on trying to hit a superior fastball.

headline: Review: ‘Born to Be Blue,’ Portrait of a Trumpeter as a Heroin Addict
summary_short: Ethan Hawke plays Chet Baker in this extended riff on a jazz life written and directed by Robert Budreau.

headline: Review: ‘I Saw the Light,’ a Hank Williams Biopic
summary_short: The British actor Tom Hiddleston stars (and sings) as the music legend, leading with charm and a twang in this film written and directed by Marc Abraham.

headline: Review: ‘They’re Watching,’ and Reality TV Is Capturing Every Eerie Second
summary_short: This found-footage horror film from Micah Wright and Jay Lender separates itself from much of the genre’s low-budget fare with its amusing premise.

headline: Review: ‘Jane Wants a Boyfriend’ Looks at Autism Through a Sister’s Eyes
summary_short: This William C. Sullivan film follows a 20-something with autism as she searches for a significant other under her sister’s protective watch.

headline: Review: ‘My Big Fat Greek Wedding 2’ Is Something Tired, Something New
summary_short: This long-awaited sequel to the hit romantic comedy, again written by and starring Nia Vardalos, is a washed-out recycling of ethnic clichés and exhausted jokes.

display_title: Batman v Superman: Dawn of Justice
headline: Review: ‘Batman v Superman’ ... v Fun?
summary_short: The film, pitting Ben Affleck against Henry Cavill, largely serves as an extended trailer for a slate of coming DC Comics movies like “Wonder Woman.”

headline: Review: ‘Kapoor & Sons’ Centers on an Indian Family’s Flaws
summary_short: This film, directed by Shakun Batra, features comedy, drama, money troubles and at least one secret.

headline: Review: In ‘The Confirmation,’ a Troubled Father and Tender Son Bond
summary_short: This Bob Nelson character study stars Clive Owen as a troubled handyman who has more than stolen tools on his mind.

headline: Review: ‘Everything Is Copy,’ a Son’s Tribute to Nora Ephron
summary_short: Celebrities and family members discuss and honor Ephron’s tartness in this documentary from Jacob Bernstein.

headline: Review: ‘Krisha,’ a Family Drama Set Around Thanksgiving
summary_short: A house in Texas becomes the site of a woman’s undoing in Trey Edward Shults’s film.

headline: Review: In ‘My Golden Days,’ Aching for a Love Left Behind
summary_short: Arnaud Desplechin’s film tells of a middle-aged anthropologist and the women who left their imprint on different stages of his life.

headline: Review: In ‘The Preppie Connection,’ Drug Smuggling at an Elite School
summary_short: This film is inspired by events in 1984 at Choate Rosemary Hall in Connecticut, where a student was accused of smuggling cocaine to sell to classmates.

headline: Review: In ‘Ktown Cowboys,’ Men on the Prowl in Koreatown
summary_short: Based on a popular web series, the film follows characters sampling various kinds of night life in Los Angeles as grown-up problems hover.

headline: Review: In ‘The Birth of Sake,’ a Brew Made With Pride and Lots of Patience
summary_short: Erik Shirai’s documentary opens a window into the unhurried and elaborate making of the Japanese liquor at a family-owned brewery.

headline: Review: In ‘The Bronze,’ a Former Gymnast Has Losing Ways
summary_short: Melissa Rauch stars in this comedy about an Olympic medalist who is defined by her spitefulness and jealousy.

headline: Review: ‘The Program,’ a Docudrama on the Fall of Lance Armstrong
summary_short: In this Stephen Frears film, Ben Foster plays Armstrong, the cyclist disgraced and stripped of victories after a doping scandal.

headline: Review: In ‘Midnight Special,’ on the Run With a Highly Unusual Child
summary_short: Jeff Nichols’s film keeps you guessing as you follow two apparent outlaws fleeing federal agents with a young boy who has special talents.

headline: Review: ‘Allegiant’ Diverges as the End Nears
summary_short: “Allegiant,” the first part of the “Divergent” series finale, takes moviegoers to the creepy confines of the Bureau of Genetic Welfare.

headline: Review: ‘Fireworks Wednesday,’ a Domestic Drama From Iran
summary_short: Asghar Farhadi’s film, set during the boisterous New Year celebrations in Tehran, dissects the imploding marriage of an affluent couple.

headline: Review: ‘Miracles From Heaven,’ Starring Jennifer Garner as the Mother of a Sick Child
summary_short: This deus-ex-machina tale, based on Christy Beam’s memoir, centers on a family whose faith is tested by a daughter’s illness.

headline: Review: ‘The Young Messiah’ Depicts Jesus as a Boy Discovering His Powers
summary_short: Cyrus Nowrasteh’s film hits some New Testament basics as it depicts the flight of Joseph, Mary and their son from Alexandria, Egypt, to Nazareth and eventually to Jerusalem.

headline: Review: In ‘The Perfect Match,’ Weddings, Babies and One Bachelor Holdout
summary_short: Bille Woodruff’s circle-of-friends romantic comedy puts a commitment-phobic Los Angeles talent agent in the path of a ravishing mystery woman.

headline: Review: ‘Marguerite,’ a Screeching Diva Clinging to Her Operatic Dream
summary_short: Xavier Giannoli’s comedy, inspired by the life of the talentless American socialite Florence Foster Jenkins, stars Catherine Frot as an aspiring singer.

headline: Review: ‘Boom Bust Boom,’ a Pythonesque Look at Financial Crashes
summary_short: This film by Terry Jones, formerly of Monty Python, explores the 2008 financial collapse and the possibility of more crashes through animation, puppetry and interviews with economists.

headline: Review: ‘10 Cloverfield Lane’ Houses a Survivalist, His Captive and Jolts
summary_short: J.J. Abrams produced but did not direct this thriller, which is only slightly connected to his “Cloverfield” (2008) and stars Mary Elizabeth Winstead.

headline: Review: ‘Eye in the Sky,’ Drone Precision vs. Human Failings
summary_short: Gavin Hood’s movie is a riveting thriller — and often a grim, suspenseful farce — about drone warfare and its perils.

headline: Review: Tastes of Los Angeles in ‘City of Gold’
summary_short: Laura Gabbert’s documentary follows the food critic Jonathan Gold in his pursuit of excellence, which can lead to a taco truck or a high-end restaurant.

headline: Review: In ‘Me Him Her,’ Late-20-Somethings Emerge From Life’s Confusion
summary_short: A loose indie comedy, this feature debut from Max Landis shows the mark of the 1985 cult classic “Into the Night,” made by his father, John Landis.

headline: Review: ‘Creative Control,’ a Satire of Gadget-Driven Reality
summary_short: Benjamin Dickinson’s sophomore feature stars Mr. Dickinson as a stressed-out adman, an unprepossessing antihero with no control at all.

headline: Review: In Julie Delpy’s ‘Lolo,’ a Teenager Tries to Sabotage His Mother’s Romance
summary_short: Ms. Delpy plays an indulgent divorced parent whose chance at happiness is threatened by her spoiled and scheming son.

headline: Review: In ‘About Scout,’ a Young Woman Searches for Her Sister
summary_short: Scout recruits a traveling companion from a psychiatric care center to search for her younger sister, who has been taken by their absentee father.

headline: Review: ‘The Brothers Grimsby’: From Sacha, With Love
summary_short: Sacha Baron Cohen returns with a movie about two brothers — a sleek superspy and a bumbling fool — who battle a global crime syndicate.

headline: Review: ‘Rise of the Legend,’ a Kung Fu Period Film
summary_short: In 19th-century Guangzhou, two friends who have trained together, and pine for the same woman, are on opposite sides of a battle.

headline: Review: ‘Hello, My Name Is Doris,’ About an Older Woman’s Love for a Much Younger Man
summary_short: A frumpy, lower-middle-class woman in her 60s suddenly finds herself desired, which leads to a ferocious awakening.

headline: Review: ‘Here Come the Videofreex,’ Revolution via the Portapak
summary_short: This concise and informative documentary follows the early adopters of a lightweight record-playback model by Sony in 1968.

headline: Review: In ‘Zootopia,’ an Intrepid Bunny Chases Her Dreams
summary_short: As the first rabbit police officer in Zootopia, Judy Hopps is stuck writing parking tickets, but the ambitious bunny pokes her nose into a missing-mammal epidemic.

display_title: They Will Have to Kill Us First
headline: Review: ‘They Will Have to Kill Us First’ Documents Malian Music in Exile
summary_short: Johanna Schwartz’s film follows musicians in exile after Islamic jihadists banned music in their home country.

headline: Review: In ‘Ava’s Possessions,’ Fallout From a Lost Month of Demonic Activity
summary_short: There is a mysterious bloodstain beneath Ava’s rug, and there are criminal charges for assault and indecent exposure to be faced.

headline: Review: In ‘Road Games,’ a French Hitch Turns South
summary_short: Abner Pastoll’s thriller focuses on two hitchhikers and the eccentric motorist who picks them up.

headline: Review: In ‘London Has Fallen,’ the President Must Be Saved From Terrorists
summary_short: Aaron Eckhart plays American’s leader visiting London, and Gerard Butler is his Secret Service protector when bloody chaos erupts.

headline: Review: ‘The Wave’ Is a Disaster Movie Making a Big Splash
summary_short: Roar Uthaug’s disaster movie follows a family and others in a Norwegian village confronting a crumbling mountain and the cataclysm that follows.

headline: Review: In ‘Knight of Cups,’ a Writer’s Flesh Is Willing but His Spirit Is Weak
summary_short: Starring Christian Bale, Terrence Malick’s film addresses the existential, and erotic, issues of a screenwriter in Los Angeles.

headline: Review: In ‘Whiskey Tango Foxtrot,’ Tina Fey as a Wisecracking War Reporter
summary_short: Based on Kim Barker’s memoir, “The Taliban Shuffle,” the comedy depicts the battle-tested experience of a journalist in Afghanistan.

headline: Review: In ‘Emelie,’ Don’t Tell Mom the Babysitter’s Deadly
summary_short: In this horror film directed by Michael Thelin, a girl hired to mind the children in a household turns out to be a dire threat to them.

headline: Review: ‘Glassland,’ the Brittle Territory of Love and Addiction
summary_short: Alcohol is a dependable friend for a woman (Toni Collette) who has been abandoned and disappointed by life and has let others down in turn.

headline: Review: In ‘Wrestling Jerusalem,’ One Man Gives Voice to Many
summary_short: In a movie adapted from his play, the writer and actor Aaron Davidman portrays more than a dozen people affected by the Mideast conflict.

headline: Review: ‘Maurizio Cattelan: Be Right Back’ Relishes a Mischievous Artist
summary_short: The documentary explores the artworks and pranks of an Italian trickster.

headline: Review: ‘Baaghi,’ a Bollywood Rebel Tale in Search of a Cause
summary_short: Fists and feet fly in this movie with the usual grab bag of romance, comedy and drama, directed by Sabbir Khan and starring Tiger Shroff and Shraddha Kapoor.

headline: Review: In ‘Older Than Ireland,’ Centenarians Recall Early and Latter Days
summary_short: Thirty wry old-timers are impressive raconteurs in this documentary directed by Alex Fegan, released during the centenary of the Easter Rising.

headline: Review: In ‘Viva,’ a Star Is Waiting to Be Born
summary_short: A macho father released from prison decides to move in with the son he abandoned, who is a sweet-natured gay hairdresser and an aspiring drag queen.

headline: Review: ‘The Man Who Knew Infinity’ Gives a Mathematical Genius His Due
summary_short: This film centers on Srinivasa Ramanujan, a brilliant mathematician from India, and his unlikely friendship with the Cambridge professor G.H. Hardy.

headline: Review: ‘A Beautiful Planet’ Shows a Dazzling Earth From Space
summary_short: Images of the planet, and even mundane tasks, take on a fascinating quality in this documentary shot by astronauts aboard the International Space Station.

headline: Review: ‘Bourek,’ About a Group of Drifting Souls
summary_short: Assorted characters on an island bicker and lounge against a backdrop of news reports heralding social and financial catastrophe.

headline: Review: ‘Dough,’ a Sweet but Pat Tale of Bridging Religious and Racial Differences
summary_short: Jonathan Pryce and Jerome Holder star in this feature about an elderly Jewish baker in London who ends up hiring a young black Muslim as his assistant.

headline: Review: ‘Mother’s Day’ Is a Goopy, Glossy Sentimental Mess
summary_short: Jennifer Aniston, Kate Hudson and Julia Roberts star in this holiday-themed film that generates inadvertent laughs and has predictable plotlines.

headline: Review: ‘Papa: Hemingway in Cuba,’ a Mild Voyage With the Old Man and ‘the Kid’
summary_short: In Bob Yari’s autobiographical film, a young Miami journalist’s fan letter leads to a fishing trip and a long friendship with his literary hero.

headline: Review: ‘Pali Road’ Blends Romance and Suspense
summary_short: Although the acting can be wooden at times, ‘Pali Road’ is a decent film set in a gorgeous locale.

headline: Review: ‘Ratchet & Clank,’ a Stale Tale Based on a PlayStation Game
summary_short: The movie has little story to tell and few ideas to offer, but a great deal of product to sell.

headline: Review: Rainer Werner Fassbinder’s Intense World and His Films
summary_short: A fellow filmmaker examines the work of this German director from the close perspective of friendship.

headline: Review: In ‘Keanu,’ Key & Peele Break Baddish for a Beloved Kitty
summary_short: The duo star as hapless cousins who feign toughness to recover a pet from gang killers.

headline: Review: ‘Eva Hesse’ Offers a Moving Portrait of an Artist’s Brief Life
summary_short: Marcie Begleiter’s documentary explores the originality and power of Hesse, who managed to triumph in a male-dominated art world before dying at 34.

headline: Review: ‘A Hologram for the King’ Is Elevated by Tom Hanks’s Portrayal of an American Everyman
summary_short: Set in Saudi Arabia, this subdued absurdist farce reflects on American decline and runaway technology.

headline: Review: In ‘The Meddler,’ a Yakkety Mom Comes of (a Certain) Age
summary_short: As a mother and daughter, Susan Sarandon and Rose Byrne portray a mother-daughter relationship that grows up.

headline: Review: Basking in an Artist’s Sun in ‘Hockney’ Documentary
summary_short: This sunny film, with occasional clouds, looks at David Hockney’s life, his losses and his work’s reflections of his immersion in Southern California.

headline: Review: ‘Compadres,’ a Cross-Border Buddy Film
summary_short: A former Mexican police officer tracking down crime syndicate loot forms an alliance with a young American hacker who played a small role in moving it.

headline: Review: In ‘Love Thy Nature,’ It Takes a Planet
summary_short: Sylvie Rokab’s film, narrated by Liam Neeson, advocates redefining the relationship between humans and the natural world.

headline: Review: ‘Men & Chicken,’ a Gory and Quirky Danish Comedy
summary_short: Two brothers trek to a remote island to find their biological father, and slapstick violence ensues.

headline: Review: A Grocery Chain, a Family Feud and a Win for Ordinary People
summary_short: This documentary, bursting with real-life superheroes who drive trucks and bag groceries, recounts the Market Basket uprising.

headline: Review: Casting ‘Nina’ Was Controversial, but Is It a Good Movie?
summary_short: This biopic of Nina Simone was criticized for its choice of Zoe Saldana in the title role, but its problems are greater than that.

headline: Review: In ‘Elvis & Nixon,’ Michael Shannon Holds Court as the King
summary_short: The director Liza Johnson recreates the meeting between the singer and the president, to which each brought his own agenda.

headline: Review: ‘The Huntsman,’ a Study in Hollywood’s Overstuffed Playbook
summary_short: Every resonant theme in this de-imaging of a fairy tale is stripped away, replaced with a ready-made franchise-movie conceit.

display_title: How to Let Go of the World and Love All the Things Climate Can’t Change
headline: Review: ‘How to Let Go of the World’ Ups the Ante on Climate Change
summary_short: Josh Fox, the director of “Gasland,” returns with this documentary that takes a tough look at climate change — including projected catastrophes.

headline: Review: ‘13 Cameras,’ Keeping a Watchful Eye and Then Some
summary_short: A creepy landlord, a father-to-be with a wandering eye, and a lot more than a couple bargained for in renting a home.

headline: Review: ‘Our Last Tango’ Celebrates Two Virtuosos of the Form
summary_short: German Kral’s documentary is a portrait of the dancers María Nieves and Juan Carlos Copes, leading tango performers for almost 50 years.

headline: Review: ‘Barbershop: The Next Cut’: Let the Debates Resume
summary_short: This movie revives the “Barbershop” franchise, bringing back Ice Cube as the owner of a haircutting establishment on Chicago’s South Side.

headline: Review: In ‘Sky,’ a Woman Takes Refuge Among Strangers
summary_short: A woman who lives in Paris and is visiting the United States with her husband flees to Las Vegas after he drunkenly tries to rape her in their motel room.

headline: Review: ‘Sing Street’ Is an ’80s Love Affair, Hair Gel Required
summary_short: The film, directed by John Carney, who also directed ‘Once,’ is a tribute to the decade of hair gel and rock ’n’ roll.

headline: Review: In ‘Criminal,’ You Must Remember This
summary_short: In Ariel Vromen’s action film, Kevin Costner plays a convict with an altered brain used to capture a C.I.A. officer’s memories.

headline: Review: ‘Colonia’ Looks at a Dark Period in South American History
summary_short: A flight attendant is enjoying a glossy stopover in Chile with a German living there, when the 1973 Pinochet coup sweeps them up.

headline: Review: ‘The Measure of a Man,’ a Tale of a Man’s Lost Labor
summary_short: Vincent Lindon, who won a the best actor award at Cannes for his role, stars as an alienated security guard in this film from Stéphane Brizé.

headline: Review: In ‘Wedding Doll,’ Search, and Struggle, to Find Independence and Romance
summary_short: Nitzan Gilady’s fiction feature debut centers on a young woman with a mild mental disability in search of her own way.

headline: Review: ‘Echo Park,’ the Story of an Early Romance
summary_short: A woman who is coming off a long-term relationship meets a man who has seen his American dream fade and has decided to return to his native England.

headline: Review: Recycled ‘Jungle Book’ Puts a Real Boy in a Forest of Pixels
summary_short: This Disney redo, by Jon Favreau, is a live-action movie that’s heavy on C.G.I. and a sunny vibe borrowed from the 1967 original.

headline: Review: In ‘Green Room,’ a Scruffy Comic Flavor Turns Tense
summary_short: A punk band booked at a roadhouse whose patrons are skinheads unleashes a cover of the Dead Kennedys’ anthem insulting “Nazi punks.” Trouble ensues.

headline: Review: ‘My Big Night,’ a Dark Farce Juggling Behind-the-Scenes Dramas
summary_short: Álex de la Iglesia’s comedy, set at the filming of a New Year’s Eve television special, deals with murder, blackmail, riots, jealousy and a crane crash.

headline: Review: ‘Rio, I Love You,’ Stories That Make Up a Mash Note to a City
summary_short: The directors of this anthology film, a paean to Rio de Janeiro, include Paolo Sorrentino, Guillermo Arriaga and Im Sang-soo.

headline: Review: ‘The First Monday in May’ Goes Behind the Scenes at the Met
summary_short: This documentary looks at the creation of the 2015 exhibition “China: Through The Looking Glass” and the benefit that coincides with its opening.

headline: Review: ‘Mr. Right,’ With Anna Kendrick, Dips Into a Tricky Genre
summary_short: This hybrid action thriller and romantic comedy follows Martha, who meets a blithe charmer and discovers that he’s a hit man.

headline: Review: In ‘Louder Than Bombs,’ a Father and Sons Grieving
summary_short: Gabriel Byrne, Jesse Eisenberg, Isabelle Huppert and Amy Ryan head the cast of Joachim Trier’s first English-language film.

headline: Review: In ‘The Invitation,’ Welcome to a Chiller Dinner
summary_short: In this film directed by Karyn Kusama, there’s something off about the hostess, her lair of a house and some of the guests.

headline: Review: In ‘Demolition,’ It’s Hammer Time for Jake Gyllenhaal
summary_short: Mr. Gyllenhaal portrays a banker recovering from the loss of his wife, with Naomi Watts playing a customer service representative who draws his attention.

headline: Review: Melissa McCarthy Takes Charge in ‘The Boss’
summary_short: Playing a fallen investment guru, Ms. McCarthy employs her precision comedic timing in a film that’s mostly another rung on her big ladder up.

headline: Review: ‘High Strung’ Finds a Dancer and Musician Colliding
summary_short: The movie, in which two young artists fall for each other, is energized by Dave Scott’s choreography.

headline: Review: In ‘Hardcore Henry,’ a Semi-Robotic Soldier Has a Personal Mission
summary_short: This Ilya Naishuller film has the look of a first-person-shooter video game.

headline: Review: In ‘One More Time,’ a Dysfunctional Family Sings
summary_short: In this Robert Edwards film, Christopher Walken plays a crooner seeking a comeback, and Amber Heard is his daughter, who has a voice but little drive.

headline: Review: In ‘Too Late,’ Imitation Is Sincere Flattery
summary_short: Noir pays tribute to noir, with respect, in this film by Dennis Hauck, starring John Hawkes as a private investigator determined to avenge a murder.

headline: Review: ‘The Dark Horse’ Dramatizes the Tale of a Chess Coach
summary_short: “The Dark Horse,” a film inspired by a documentary, is about Gen Potini, a Maori speed-chess player who used his skill to help young players.

headline: Review: ‘Miles Ahead,’ an Impressionistic Take on Miles Davis
summary_short: Don Cheadle stars in — and directed — this biopic about the jazz trumpeter, who was a sly chameleon, both in his life and in his music.

headline: Review: In ‘Afternoon,’ Two Men Open Up
summary_short: This Tsai Ming-liang film features him and the actor Lee Kang-sheng discussing personal issues in a minimalist setting.

headline: Review: ‘Catching the Sun’ Profiles Solar Energy Entrepreneurs and Activists
summary_short: This documentary spotlights international efforts to build a green economy through solar power.

headline: Review: ‘Notfilm’ Tells How Beckett and Keaton Collaborated
summary_short: This documentary about the making of the 1965 short movie “Film” features interviews and anecdotes about the two men.

headline: Review: In ‘The Girl in the Photographs,’ Ambitious Goals Slashed
summary_short: This horror film, with Wes Craven credited as executive producer, has a hackneyed sleaziness.

display_title: Marinoni: The Fire in the Frame
headline: Review: In ‘Marinoni,’ a Racing Champion Turned Bicycle Craftsman
summary_short: This documentary follows Giuseppe Marinoni, 75, as he travels from his adopted home in Canada to Italy to compete for a speed record in his age group.

headline: Review: In ‘Everybody Wants Some!!,’ Casual Sex and Casual Philosophizing
summary_short: Richard Linklater calls his latest film, set in 1980, a “spiritual sequel” to “Dazed and Confused,” his 1970s high school masterpiece.

headline: Review: ‘April and the Extraordinary World,’ Animated Sci-Fi From France
summary_short: In an altered century with stunted technology, a Parisian and her talking cat try to figure out why so many scientists are disappearing.

headline: Review: In ‘Seoul Searching,’ Teenagers Explore Their Korean Roots to an ’80s Soundtrack
summary_short: Set in 1986, the film introduces globally scattered youngsters to their heritage in a plot that both critiques and embraces stereotypes.

display_title: Jia Zhangke, a Guy From Fenyang
headline: Review: ‘Jia Zhangke, a Guy From Fenyang,’ a Portrait of a Visionary Filmmaker
summary_short: The documentary is a decent and conscientious companion piece to Mr. Zhangke’s films.

headline: Review: ‘The Ones Below,’ Looming Parenthood and Unsettling Suspense
summary_short: For two couples sharing a London townhouse, the joys of expecting take a dark turn in this thriller, the feature debut of David Farr.

headline: Review: ‘Holy Hell,’ Inside a Cult, via Its Own Videographer
summary_short: A member pursues and documents a cult leader whose persona devolves from charismatic to creepy in this documentary.

headline: Review: ‘X-Men: Apocalypse,’ a Sequel 5,000 Years in the Making
summary_short: Directed by Bryan Singer, this latest addition to the blockbuster franchise pits the superhero team against a mutant villain from ancient Egypt.

headline: Review: ‘Alice Through the Looking Glass’ and a Trippy Time Machine
summary_short: This sequel to Tim Burton’s “Alice in Wonderland,” directed by James Bobin, offers a world of grotesque overabundance cluttered with special-effects gadgetry.

headline: Review: In ‘Unlocking the Cage,’ a Struggle to Raise the Legal Status of Chimpanzees
summary_short: This documentary centers on a lawyer’s quest to show that intelligent species like chimps and whales merit some legal protections accorded to humans.

headline: Review: In ‘Maggie’s Plan,’ Greta Gerwig Aspires to Motherhood on Her Terms
summary_short: This film, the fifth from Rebecca Miller, stars Ms. Gerwig as a millennial who, on the way to finding a sperm donor, falls for a part-time professor.

headline: Review: ‘O.J.: Made in America,’ an Unflinching Take on His Rise and Fall
summary_short: This ESPN documentary extends the narrative beyond the O.J. Simpson murder trial, as a biography and a history of race, fame, sports and Los Angeles.

headline: Review: In ‘Manhattan Night,’ Adrien Brody Navigates an Urban Underbelly
summary_short: Starring Adrien Brody as a tabloid columnist, this film deploys conventions evoking “Chinatown” and older classics but ends up feeling prosaic.

headline: Review: ‘Almost Holy’ Demonstrates a Pastor’s Tough Love for Street Kids in Ukraine
summary_short: This documentary by Steve Hoover examines Gennadiy Mokhnenko, a pastor in Ukraine who rehabilitates homeless children at his center, Pilgrim Republic.

headline: Review: ‘The Angry Birds Movie,’ a Superficially Amiable Ball of Fluff
summary_short: In this animated adaptation of the smartphone video game, Jason Sudeikis gives voice to an avian hothead suspicious of the newly arrived green pigs.

headline: Review: ‘A Moment of Silence’ Follows the Evo Morales Era in Bolivia
summary_short: This documentary centers on the first Bolivian president to rise from the country’s indigenous majority.

headline: Review: ‘Welcome to Happiness,’ With Kyle Gallner Seeking Answers
summary_short: What if we could change our past? The film, written and directed by Oliver Thompson, wonders.

headline: Review: ‘Neighbors 2: Sorority Rising’ Has an Animal House for the Fairer Sex
summary_short: Nicholas Stoller’s sequel to the 2014 original stars a returning Seth Rogen and Rose Byrne as a couple taking on new raucous collegians next door.

headline: Review: ‘The Nice Guys’ Pairs Gosling and Crowe as Slapstick Detectives
summary_short: Shane Black’s convoluted caper blends pop-culture riffs from the ’70s with a zany mix of mistaken identity, nudity and grisly murders.

headline: Review: ‘Sunset Song’ Shows a Woman’s True Grit
