summary_short: In Terence Davies’s film, scenes of Scottish rural life are stitched together in a slow-moving story rife with both natural beauty and tragedy.

headline: Review: In ‘Love & Friendship,’ Austen Meets Whit Stillman
summary_short: This adaptation, starring Kate Beckinsale, is enlivened by Mr. Stillman’s keen eye for character and Austen’s sense of fun.

headline: Review: ‘Cash Only’: Repaying a Crook, When Things Turn Gritty
summary_short: In Malik Bader’s drama, the clock is ticking fast for a desperate Detroit landlord who steals money from the wrong person.

headline: Review: Cops in ‘The Trust’ Spice Up Deadly Dull Jobs
summary_short: Nicolas Cage and Elijah Wood play police-department partners who deal with boredom, social invisibility and pent-up rage by planning a heist.

headline: Review: In ‘The Lobster,’ Colin Farrell Plays a Divorced Man in a Loner-Hating Society
summary_short: Yorgos Lanthimos’s surreal allegory about tyrannical monogamy and its direct counterpart is dosed with bitterness as well as comic whimsy.

headline: Review: ‘Kill Zone 2’ Packs a Wallop With Orchestrated Mayhem
summary_short: This Soi Cheang film, involving a principled prison guard with an ill daughter, has plot and subplot, but the action scenes are most notable.

headline: Review: ‘Pelé: Birth of a Legend’ Charts a Superstar’s Rise
summary_short: This biopic follows the ascent of the Brazilian soccer player who became the sport’s greatest ambassador.

headline: Review: ‘What We Become’ Finds Zombies in Broad Daylight
summary_short: This Danish horror film focuses on a family’s breakdown after a virus threatens an affluent suburb.

headline: Review: In ‘Money Monster,’ a Broke Investor Holds a Grudge and a Gun
summary_short: George Clooney plays a financial news talk-show host, and Julia Roberts is his producer in this self-assured hostage drama.

headline: Review: ‘Dheepan,’ About Sri Lankan Refugees, Looks Like a Prophecy
summary_short: In Jacques Audiard’s Palme d’Or-winning film, the members of a makeshift family find that a housing project near Paris feels like the war zone they just left.

headline: Review: ‘Elstree 1976,’ in a Galaxy Not Far, Far Away
summary_short: This Jon Spira documentary is about actors who played small roles in parts of the original “Star Wars” that were filmed in London.

headline: Review: In ‘Dark Horse,’ a Real-Life Steeplechase Champion Inspires a Town
summary_short: Subtitled “The Incredible True Story of Dream Alliance,” this documentary recounts the rise of a foal who restored a Welsh village’s spirits.

headline: Review: ‘Mothers and Daughters,’ in Which Souls Are Laid Bare
summary_short: Written by Paige Cameron, this movie includes many of the difficult conversations typical of these relationships, just in time for Mother’s Day.

headline: Review: ‘Beautiful Something’: Craving Love in Philadelphia
summary_short: Joseph Graham’s movie is a bleak, agonized study of gay men looking for some kind of connection.

headline: Review: ‘Those People’: Heartbreak Among the Upper Crust
summary_short: In Joey Kuhn’s directorial debut, wealthy young men in Manhattan pine for one another and play coy.

headline: Review: ‘Being Charlie,’ a Rehab Story Directed by Rob Reiner
summary_short: The director’s son Nick Reiner wrote the screenplay with Matt Elisofon, and it centers on a rebellious teenager whose father is a well-known entertainment figure.

headline: Review: ‘The Offering’: No, Thank You
summary_short: Kelvin Tong’s horror movie tries to hit as many genre notes as possible, including spinning heads and pushy demons.

headline: Review: ‘Mad Tiger,’ or the Story of Peelander-Z’s Near Breakup
summary_short: This documentary follows a punk band as rifts form when one member quits and opens a bar.

headline: Review: In ‘Captain America: Civil War,’ Super-Bro Against Super-Bro
summary_short: “Captain America: Civil War” does not in any way transcend the conventions of the genre. On the contrary: it succeeds because it doesn’t really try.

headline: Review: ‘A Bigger Splash,’ With a Speechless Tilda Swinton, Is Ready for Its Close-Up
summary_short: This film, filled with beautiful people, is a reluctant thriller about a rock star, her current lover, her former lover and a pretty young thing.

headline: Review: Kidman and Bateman Face Childhood Scars in ‘The Family Fang’
summary_short: In this adaptation of Kevin Wilson’s novel, siblings grapple with memories of an upbringing spent being used as artistic props by their parents.

headline: Review: In ‘Independence Day: Resurgence,’ the Fault Is Not in the Fireworks
summary_short: All you really need to know about this sequel to the 1996 smash hit is that it took multiple men to cook up this pottage, which hinges on humanity battling aliens.

headline: Review: In ‘Hunt for the Wilderpeople,’ Lighting Out for the Bush
summary_short: Taika Waititi’s comedy centers on a foster child in New Zealand first placed with an older couple and then on the run.

headline: Review: ‘From This Day Forward’ Attests to Love’s Adaptability
summary_short: Sharon Shattuck’s documentary tells her family story of growing up with a transgender parent.

display_title: Eat That Question: Frank Zappa in His Own Words
headline: Review: ‘Eat That Question,’ on Frank Zappa, the Media and Cultural Upheavals
summary_short: A documentary about Zappa is rich in archival interviews that say worlds about this musician — who was well known but not well understood — and his times.

headline: Review: ‘T-Rex’ Fights Like a Girl. And That’s Worth Gold.
summary_short: Claressa Shields, the first female boxer to win an Olympic gold medal, is the indomitable center of Drea Cooper and Zackary Canepari’s impressive documentary.

headline: Review: Matthew McConaughey Rebels Against Rebels in ‘Free State of Jones’
summary_short: Mr. McConaughey plays Newton Knight, the Mississippi farmer who led a dissident Confederate group in the Civil War, and a political coalition after.

headline: Review: Ranger vs. Preacher? In ‘The Duel,’ It’s No Contest
summary_short: Woody Harrelson, who plays a charismatic preacher, delivers a strong performance, but this film is largely characterized by unpersuasive story turns.

headline: Review: In ‘Right Now, Wrong Then,’ a Double Take and Its Choices
summary_short: The South Korean director Hong Sang-soo twice tells the tale of a first meeting between an older man and younger woman, with different outcomes.

headline: Review: ‘The Shallows’: Surfer Girl. Peckish Shark. Uh-Oh!
summary_short: Blake Lively stars as a young woman on a surfing mission in this thriller. But a really, really big shark has its own ravenous plans.

headline: Review: ‘Wiener-Dog,’ the Tail That Wags Through a Few Bitter Lives
summary_short: As usual, Todd Solondz focuses on the awfulness of our species, dramatized in this film through dark, deadpan comic vignettes in the presence of a dachshund.

headline: Review: In ‘The Neon Demon,’ Beauty Masks a Rotting Core
summary_short: This puerile movie from the Danish filmmaker Nicolas Winding Refn is set in the high-fashion modeling world of Los Angeles. Elle Fanning and Keanu Reeves star.

headline: Review: In ‘Breaking a Monster,’ a Plea to Play Heavy Metal
summary_short: As three black seventh-graders from Brooklyn rise as potential music stars in this documentary, they must face much more than the music.

headline: Review: ‘Septembers of Shiraz’ Revisits the 1979 Iranian Revolution
summary_short: This well-meaning yet nuance-free film focuses on a prosperous and friendly couple targeted for harassment during political upheaval.

headline: Review: ‘Yarn’: And You Thought It Was Just for Knitting Mittens
summary_short: This documentary looks in on people working in yarn, from artists making graffiti to those fashioning playground structures.

headline: Review: ‘Tickled’ Is Fun and Giggles Until It Isn’t Anymore
summary_short: Two filmmakers had barely begun their reporting for this documentary when threats from the private world of tickling began.

display_title: Bang Gang: A Modern Love Story
headline: Review: ‘Bang Gang,’ Seaside Orgies to a Soundtrack of Yawns
summary_short: This film about middle-class teenagers having group sex during a long hot summer in Biarritz, France, is remarkable for its shrugging attitude.

headline: Review: In ‘Central Intelligence,’ a Weaponized Kevin Hart
summary_short: This espionage comedy, which also stars Dwayne Johnson, accomplishes its mission of being aggressively juvenile.

headline: Review: In ‘Finding Dory,’ a Forgetful Fish and a Warm Celebration of Differences
summary_short: The friendly blue fish with short-term memory problems goes looking for her family and takes a star turn in this sequel to “Finding Nemo.”

headline: Review: ‘Call Her Applebroog,’ Beth B’s Portrait of a Still-Vital Artist
summary_short: Beth B, Ida Applebroog’s daughter, takes an intimate look at the artist’s drawings, paintings and emphatic engagement with others.

headline: Review: In ‘Len and Company,’ a Prickly Pop Producer Finds His Solitude Interrupted
summary_short: Rhys Ifans stars as a disaffected former rock star who retreats to the countryside after a meltdown, only to host some surprise guests with concerns of their own.

headline: Review: In ‘King Jack,’ a 15-Year-Old Trapped in a Cycle of Bullying
summary_short: Felix Johnson’s coming-of-age story portrays a teenage boy in a small town in which a bully exercises his capacity for cruelty.

headline: Review: In ‘The Conjuring 2,’ Ghostly Violence Has a British Accent
summary_short: James Wan’s sequel to his horror hit concerns a London poltergeist in 1977. Vera Farmiga and Patrick Wilson return as paranormal investigators.

headline: Review: ‘Genius’ Puts Max Perkins and Thomas Wolfe in a Literary Bromance
summary_short: Michael Grandage’s 1930s-era biopic is nostalgia for a supposed golden age of masculine artistic potency.

headline: Review: ‘Germans & Jews,’ a New Generation Continues a Difficult Conversation
summary_short: In Janina Quint’s documentary, a group of Jewish and non-Jewish Germans, most of them born after World War II, reckon with the past.

headline: Review: ‘Puerto Ricans in Paris’ Combines Comedy and Crime
summary_short: Two New York police officers get a break from their home lives when they are asked to help stop a counterfeiter in France.

headline: Review: Taking the Long Way Home in ‘Last Cab to Darwin’
summary_short: A dying man who works as a cabby longs to leave the world on his own terms, so he turns the wheel toward eternity.

headline: Review: ‘Now You See Me 2’ Illusionists Are Out to Save the World
summary_short: The sleight-of-hand the Four Horsemen must pull off in this cartoonish movie, directed by Jon M. Chu, would protect everyone’s computers.

headline: Review: In ‘Be Somebody,’ a Teenage Idol Goes AWOL With an Ordinary Girl
summary_short: Matthew Espinosa plays a pop star who has had enough with his tour handlers and sees how the other folks live.

headline: Review: ‘The Music of Strangers,’ on Yo-Yo Ma and the Silk Road Ensemble
summary_short: Morgan Neville’s documentary follows the ensemble and discusses the relevance of music in a violent world. Lovely to watch, it’s even more beautiful to hear.

headline: Review: In ‘Warcraft,’ Orcs of a Different Domain, Fighting With Heart
summary_short: Directed by Duncan Jones, this cinematic extension of the brand that began as a video game features invading orcs, embattled humans and much pummeling.

headline: Review: ‘’Til Madness Do Us Part’ Finds Hell and Humanity
summary_short: Wang Bing’s documentary about a mental hospital in China is overlong but sporadically extraordinary.

headline: Review: In ‘The Fits,’ a Graceful Tale of a Girl Who Follows Her Own Beat
summary_short: This debut feature from Anna Rose Holmer centers on an 11-year-old tomboy who trains as a boxer only to discover an interest in joining an all-female dance team.

headline: Review: ‘Time to Choose’ Extols Renewable Energy to Combat Global Warming
summary_short: Charles Ferguson’s documentary is a sobering polemic about climate change that balances predictions of planetary doom with a survey of innovations in energy technology.

display_title: The Thoughts That Once We Had
headline: Review: ‘The Thoughts That Once We Had,’ a Cinematic Flight
summary_short: A montage of film clips that takes us on a wild ride through cinematic history.

headline: Review: ‘The Wailing’ Will Scare You, and Break Your Heart
summary_short: Na Hong-jin’s movie about demonic possession is an expansive and often excruciating horror film from South Korea.

headline: Review: In ‘Me Before You,’ a Broken Man Meets a Free Spirit
summary_short: This floppy British romance, directed by Thea Sharrock and adapted by Jojo Moyes from her best-selling novel, stars Emilia Clarke and Sam Claflin.

headline: Review: In ‘Andron,’ Deadly Games With Alec Baldwin and Danny Glover
summary_short: A knockoff of “The Hunger Games” and “The Maze Runner,” this film adds up to less than the sum of its parts.

headline: Review: In ‘Approaching the Unknown,’ Mark Strong Trades Earth for Mars
summary_short: This Mark Elijah Rosenberg film centers on an astronaut and has echoes of movies like “2001: A Space Odyssey” and “Interstellar.”

display_title: Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles: Out of the Shadows
headline: Review: With the Latest ‘Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles,’ an Existential Crisis
summary_short: In “Out of the Shadows” the superheros contend with an apocalyptic villain and wonder what it means to be normal.

headline: Review: Andy Samberg Spoofs Pop Stars Without Spite. And That’s 4 Real.
summary_short: The Lonely Island trio has created a mockumentary featuring the fictional Conner4Real, a former boy-band star trying to make it as a solo act.

headline: Review: In ‘Gleason,’ a Devastating Diagnosis Prompts a New Mission
summary_short: Clay Tweel’s documentary chronicles the athlete Steve Gleason’s attempt to leave behind a meaningful legacy for his unborn child as A.L.S. wreaks havoc on his body.

headline: Review: ‘Indignation’ Offers a Precisely Rendered, and Repressive, 1950s America
summary_short: A period novel by Philip Roth, inspired by his own college years, is the basis of this tale about a young Jewish man and sex and morality in the Korean War era.

headline: Review: In ‘Equity,’ No Room for Sisterhood Amid Gloves-Off Wall Street Warfare
summary_short: Meera Menon’s film, starring Anna Gunn, challenges stereotypes of ambition, corruption and sexism, even as it exploits their tenacity.

headline: Review: Empty Spaces Show the Imprint of Humanity in ‘Homo Sapiens’
summary_short: Images of abandoned places built or scarred by humankind make up what could be described as an environmental documentary.

headline: Review: Three Women (and a Baby) at a Crossroads in ‘Tallulah’
summary_short: Almost a decade after “Juno,” Ellen Page and Allison Janney are paired again in this film written and directed by Sian Heder.

headline: Review: ‘Into the Forest’: Be Very, Very Quiet. The World’s Ending.
summary_short: This apocalyptic film by the Canadian filmmaker Patricia Rozema depends on atmosphere and details, rather than big incidents, to tell its story.

headline: Review: ‘Can We Take a Joke?’ The Answer Appears to Be Not Anymore
summary_short: In this one-sided documentary, comedians like Gilbert Gottfried and Lisa Lampanelli argue that people need to develop thicker skin.

headline: Review: ‘Miss Sharon Jones!’: The Shimmies and Shouts of a Survivor
summary_short: This documentary follows the soul singer through a diagnosis of pancreatic cancer, chemotherapy, recovery and musical rebirth.

headline: Review: ‘Bad Moms,’ a Comedy of Outrage Pegged to Smother Mothers
summary_short: The film is a funny, giddy, sentimental laugh-in from Jon Lucas and Scott Moore, who wrote the 2009 hit “The Hangover.”

headline: Review: In ‘Jason Bourne,’ a Midlife Crisis for a Harried Former Assassin
summary_short: Matt Damon returns in a film in which geopolitics and technology are scaffolding for what is essentially a story about human resources challenges in a large bureaucracy.

headline: Review: In ‘Nerve,’ a Shy Girl Seduced by the Internet
summary_short: Tired of playing it safe, a high-school senior joins a reality-style online game that soon escalates into dangerous stunts.

headline: Review: ‘Don’t Think Twice’: Mike Birbiglia’s Smart Comedy
summary_short: The movie follows an improv troupe and its members, who can be both supportive and catty.

headline: Review: All Aboard ‘Train to Busan’ for Zombie and Class Warfare
summary_short: Yeon Sang-ho’s film, set on a South Korean bullet train, pits passengers against the spastic undead.

headline: Review: Avenging a Sister’s Death in ‘Fight Valley’
summary_short: A street-fighting crew from New Jersey called the Knock-Around Girls is the focus of this punch-drunk action drama.

headline: Review: In ‘Hillary’s America,’ Dinesh D’Souza Warns of a Plan to ‘Steal’ the Country
summary_short: The conservative author’s film paints a forbidding portrait of Hillary Clinton and her fellow Democrats.

headline: Review: In ‘Quitters,’ a Teenager as Sinister as Iago
summary_short: Noah Pritzker’s film stars Ben Konigsberg as a defiant son who moves out of his troubled family’s home and pursues an egotistic, amoral path.

headline: Review: In ‘Lights Out’ an Invisible Friend Turns Malicious
summary_short: The director David F. Sandberg extracts maximum frights from a simple concept: an entity that appears in the dark and vanishes in the light.

headline: Review: ‘Don’t Worry Baby’ and a Case of Uncertain Paternity
summary_short: This mildly humorous Julian Branciforte film, fortified with veteran actors, centers on whether a photographer or his father is the parent of a young girl.

headline: Review: In ‘Ice Age: Collision Course,’ a Squirrel Reorders the Universe
summary_short: The fifth movie in the “Ice Age” franchise includes endless wisecracks and family-values twaddle, but the 3-D animation packs some punch.

headline: Review: ‘Absolutely Fabulous’ Brings Its Snickers and Bubbly to the Big Screen
summary_short: Jennifer Saunders and Joanna Lumley are back as Eddy and Patsy in this happily self-conscious feature-length goof, a film iteration of the BBC TV series.

headline: Review: ‘Star Trek Beyond’ Sticks to Its Brand. That’s Not Necessarily Bad.
summary_short: This film follows its immediate predecessors, “Star Trek” and “Into Darkness,” in sacrificing some of the old spirit to blockbuster imperatives.

headline: Review: ‘Equals,’ a Futuristic Tale of Defying Deadly Conformity
summary_short: Kristen Stewart and Nicholas Hoult star as workers in a dystopian commune who break the rules by experiencing feelings for each other.

headline: Review: In ‘How He Fell in Love,’ an Extramarital Bond Unfolds
summary_short: This Marc Meyers film focuses on how the relationship between a young musician and a middle-age woman affects them and others in their orbit.

headline: Review: In ‘Phantom Boy,’ an Ailing Hero Takes On a Villain
summary_short: This animated film by Alain Gagnol and Jean-Loup Felicioli (“A Cat in Paris”) tells the story of a boy whose illness has given him a gift.

headline: Review: ‘Café Society’ Isn’t Woody Allen’s Worst Movie
summary_short: This ambivalent return to 1930s Hollywood mostly rearranges the director’s old themes. But, overall, it’s an amusing little picture.

headline: Review: In ‘The Infiltrator,’ Bryan Cranston Tunnels Into a Menacing Drug Network
summary_short: Based on a memoir, the film depicts a federal agent who poses as a money launderer to combat Pablo Escobar’s cocaine cartel.

headline: Our ‘Ghostbusters’ Review: Girls Rule. Women Are Funny. Get Over It.
summary_short: This redo lets women, especially Kate McKinnon, be as simply and uncomplicatedly funny as men, and still leaves room for Chris Hemsworth.

headline: Review: Viggo Mortensen Captivates in ‘Captain Fantastic’
summary_short: Mr. Mortensen is just one of the reasons to see this film about a family forced to leave their home in the woods and become reacquainted with society.

headline: Review: ‘Zero Days’ Examines Cyberwarfare’s Potential Online Apocalypse
summary_short: This Alex Gibney documentary describes the origin of Stuxnet, malware devised by Israel and the United States with grave implications for the future.

headline: Review: Fraternal Dysfunction in the Old South in ‘Men Go to Battle’
summary_short: This film, which takes place during the early years of the Civil War, pushes back against the rigid formality of the period genre.

headline: Review: ‘Fathers and Daughters,’ a Sappy Tale Unredeemed by Star Power
summary_short: Blunt dialogue and infuriatingly coy storytelling pervade this weepy melodrama starring Amanda Seyfried and Russell Crowe.

display_title: Mike and Dave Need Wedding Dates
headline: Review: ‘Mike and Dave Need Wedding Dates,’ Antics to Not Love nor Cherish
summary_short: This aggressively stupid movie has nothing going for it other than some wasted talent.

display_title: Norman Lear: Just Another Version of You
headline: Review: About Norman Lear, Who Gave Us Archie Bunker
summary_short: The documentary “Norman Lear: Just Another Version of You” is a portrait of the 1970s TV hitmaker who broke ground with issue-oriented humor.

headline: Review: ‘Cell’ Offers Zombified Victims and an Unfocused Narrative
summary_short: This film, dated, despondent and pretty much a disaster, plays like a series of nods to other science fiction-horror hybrids.

headline: Review: ‘Cold War 2,’ a Brisk Exercise in Hong Kong Suspense
summary_short: This action film by Longman Leung and Sunny Luk follows the 2012 crime film “Cold War,” a tense, engaging cop thriller.

headline: Review: ‘The Debt’ in This Barney Elliott Film Is a Commodity
summary_short: Peru’s agricultural landscape is the setting for this film about corporate greed and the persistence of native farmers.

headline: Review: Is the Indian Point Nuclear Plant Safe? Nobody Knows
summary_short: The documentary “Indian Point,” directed by Ivy Meeropol, focuses on complaints about the safety of this power plant, about 45 miles from Midtown Manhattan.

headline: Review: ‘The Secret Life of Pets’ Amuses, but Misses Opportunities
summary_short: This film is clearly the work of dog people, and traffics — like nearly every other movie in its genre — in some tired anti-feline stereotypes.

headline: Review: A Professor Drawn to the Mob in ‘Our Kind of Traitor’
summary_short: The film, based on John le Carré’s 2010 novel of the same name, includes complications both geopolitical and conjugal.

headline: Review: ‘The Purge: Election Year’ Offers a Campaign Platform of Blood Lust
summary_short: In the third chapter of James DeMonaco’s dystopian series, a senator joins insurgents who oppose the yearly overnight killing spree in the title.

headline: Review: Bruce Willis Is a Banker With Issues in ‘Marauders’
summary_short: In this film, robberies vex Mr. Willis’s character and an F.B.I. agent played by Christopher Meloni.

headline: Review: A ‘Tarzan’ With a Few Twists in the Hollywood Vine
summary_short: Alexander Skarsgard is Tarzan, who returns to the jungle with his man-muscles, in Congo, with an American who believes people are being enslaved.

headline: Review: In ‘The BFG,’ Walking Gently and Wearing Huge Shoes
summary_short: In Steven Spielberg’s adaptation of a Roald Dahl story, restraint and Mark Rylance prevail in the face of digital wizardry and belabored wonderment.

headline: Review: ‘Swiss Army Man’ Is a Buddy Movie in Which One Pal Is Dead
summary_short: Starring Daniel Radcliffe and Paul Dano, this impossible-to-categorize film about a castaway and a corpse is an original mix of the macabre and the magical.

headline: Review: ‘Uncle Kent 2,’ How’s Your Tolerance for Hipster Milquetoasts?
summary_short: Kent Osborne returns as the starring character in this sequel to the 2011 film “Uncle Kent.”

display_title: The Seasons in Quincy: Four Portraits of John Berger
headline: Review: ‘The Seasons in Quincy: Four Portraits of John Berger’ Lauds a Renaissance Man
summary_short: These four film shorts, each by a different director, evoke aspects of a brilliant art historian and essayist living in the French Alps.

headline: Review: Jason Statham in ‘Mechanic: Resurrection,’ a Hit Man on Cruise Control
summary_short: The latest foray for the Mechanic takes him around the world after his nemesis arranges a triple assassination he can’t refuse.

headline: ‘Mia Madre’ Review: Mom’s in the Hospital. The Riot Scene Needs Retakes.
summary_short: Nanni Moretti’s film, starring Margherita Buy as a movie director and John Turturro as an American star, makes a case for blurriness in art and life.

headline: Review: ‘In Order of Disappearance’ Emits a Dash of ‘Fargo’
summary_short: Stellan Skarsgard stars in this dark comedy, in which drug dealers feel the wrath of a father who has lost his son.

headline: Review: ‘Hands of Stone’ Returns Robert De Niro to the Ring but Pulls Its Punches
summary_short: Jonathan Jakubowicz’s film has scattered pleasures, like Mr. De Niro’s performance as Roberto Durán’s trainer. But the boxing scenes do not come within swinging distance of “Raging Bull.”

headline: Review: In ‘Blood Father,’ Mel Gibson Plays With Pulp Fiction
summary_short: The movie, directed by Jean-François Richet, finds the grizzled loner of a hero fighting to protect his daughter.

headline: Review: ‘Don’t Breathe’: Whose Bright Idea Was It to Rob a Blind Man?
summary_short: With solid suspense, murky lighting and “gotcha!” scares, Fede Alvarez’s film will probably please fans intrigued by those elements.

headline: Review: Rachel Weisz Toys With Identity in ‘Complete Unknown’
summary_short: In Joshua Marston’s film, a man with a shaky marriage meets an unnerving old flame who has lived under a series of assumed personas.

headline: Review: ‘Floyd Norman: An Animated Life’: He Broke Barriers at Disney
summary_short: Mr. Norman, the first African-American animator on Disney’s staff, hand-drew scenes for classics including “The Jungle Book” and “Sleeping Beauty.”

headline: Review: ‘The Hollars’: Domestic Meltdowns in Middle America
summary_short: John Krasinski directs and stars in a story of a man who finds that although he can go home again, the place remains a mess.

headline: Review: In ‘The Intervention,’ There’s a Big Chill in the Air
summary_short: The film, written and directed by Clea DuVall, finds a group of 30-somethings gathering to encourage a married couple to break up.

headline: Review: In ‘Level Up,’ Yanked From a Video Game Stupor to a Real Mission
summary_short: This British indie offers a cynical vision of technology-fostered callousness, a running-man cocktail of brutality spiked with low-level humor.

headline: Review: Love, Loss and Spiritual Torment in ‘The Sea of Trees’
summary_short: Matthew McConaughey stars as a professor who enters a Japanese forest to end his life. There he meets a businessman, played by Ken Watanabe, with the same goal.

headline: Review: In an Obama Biopic, the Audacity of Hagiography?
summary_short: The writer-director Richard Tanne builds on the Obamas’ first date, in Chicago, in this worshipful film.

headline: Review: ‘Kate Plays Christine,’ a Blurring of Fact and Fiction in a Suicide Story
summary_short: This movie is a sequel of sorts to Robert Greene’s “Actress,” which focuses on boundaries between actors playing themselves and fictional characters.

headline: Review: In ‘Kubo and the Two Strings,’ Origami Fuels an Animated Quest
summary_short: This movie from Laika Films (“Coraline” and “ParaNorman”) combines stop-motion animation and computer-generated backgrounds with a moving and magical tale.

headline: Review: ‘War Dogs,’ an Absurd (and True) Gunrunning Tale
summary_short: Jonah Hill and Miles Teller play 20-something entrepreneurs who plunge into the weaponry business and end up in over their heads.

headline: Review: ‘Morris From America’: A 13-Year-Old Stranger in a Strange Land
summary_short: An American teenager seeks his place in the world in Heidelberg, Germany.

headline: Review: ‘Ben-Hur’ Is a Savage Update for a New Generation
summary_short: Timur Bekmambetov’s adaptation of the sword-and-sandals spectacle offers a rip-roaring chariot race but is largely devoid of pious posturing.

display_title: Lo and Behold, Reveries of the Connected World
headline: Review: ‘Lo and Behold,’ the Danger, and Potential, of the Digital Revolution
summary_short: Werner Herzog interviews experts and others about the internet, robots, artificial intelligence and other aspects of our technology-driven world.

headline: Review: ‘Kingsglaive: Final Fantasy XV,’ Where the Bad Guys Sport Silly Hats
summary_short: Unless you’re a fan of the hugely successful Final Fantasy video game series, this big-screen version is too ludicrous for words.

headline: Review: In ‘Spaceman,’ a Pitcher Specializing in Brashness
summary_short: Josh Duhamel portrays the ballplayer Bill Lee at a stage when he is slowly realizing that his major-league days are over.

display_title: A Tale of Love and Darkness
headline: Review: From Natalie Portman, Israel’s Birth Distilled in Mood and Memory
summary_short: “A Tale of Love and Darkness,” based on Amos Oz’s memoir, depicts a family caught up in the conflict and confusion leading to Israel’s war of independence.

headline: Review: ‘When Two Worlds Collide’ Portrays a Battle for the Amazon
summary_short: This dutiful documentary casts indigenous protesters against the government and commercial interests intent on exploiting Peru’s rich natural resources.

headline: Review: ‘Mohenjo Daro’ Depicts a Go-To Hero’s Exertions in Antiquity
summary_short: Set in 2016 B.C., this Ashutosh Gowariker film is a standard epic adventure with music and romance.

headline: Review: A Waltz Across Texas in ‘Hell or High Water’
summary_short: Brothers on a bank-robbing spree make their way through a desert of economic decline in this film by David Mackenzie.

headline: Review: A Mission Against All Odds in the Wartime Thriller ‘Anthropoid’
summary_short: Cillian Murphy and Jamie Dornan star as Resistance fighters in Czechoslovakia who set out to assassinate one of the chief architects of the Holocaust.

headline: Review: In ‘Joshy,’ Wedding’s Off, Bachelor Party’s a Go
summary_short: Written and directed by Jeff Baena, this comedy features Thomas Middleditch and Adam Pally, among others, enjoying a weekend of middle-class debauchery.

headline: Review: In ‘My King,’ Blindly Falling Fast and Furious
summary_short: Told in flashback, this film follows the collision and decade-long duel between a guarded lawyer and an impulsively charismatic restaurateur.

headline: ‘Sausage Party’ Is an Animated Sex Comedy About Food ... and God
summary_short: In this free-spirited romp through the supermarket, potty-mouthed foodstuffs give voice to matters both humorous and spiritual.

headline: Review: In ‘Edge of Winter,’ an Unstable Dad With a Gun
summary_short: Underage driving and drinking, mental illness, firearms and jealousy in a hunting-trip thriller: What could go wrong?

headline: Review: ‘Operation Chromite’ Revisits a Korean War Invasion
summary_short: John H. Lee’s drama concerns a squad of South Koreans who infiltrate North Korean forces and secure a lighthouse critical to the Battle of Inchon.

headline: Review: In ‘Pete’s Dragon,’ a Magical Bond in Peril Again
summary_short: This reboot from the director David Lowery tells its standard-issue story at a nice clip.

headline: Review: Beyond the Politics in ‘Abortion: Stories Women Tell’
summary_short: Both sides are addressed in this documentary, which largely focuses on viewpoints and personal experiences in Missouri and Illinois.

headline: Review: In ‘Disorder,’ Danger Lurks in Many Corners, or None at All
summary_short: This movie from Alice Winocour follows a veteran returning to France from Central Asia who takes what seems to be a fairly straightforward security job.

headline: Review: ‘Florence Foster Jenkins,’ Singing So Wretched It’s Legendary
summary_short: Meryl Streep stars in an enjoyable look back at a would-be singer and a Carnegie Hall concert remembered for how awful it was.

headline: Review: In ‘Nine Lives,’ a Man’s Life Is Like a Litter Box
summary_short: Kevin Spacey, Jennifer Garner and Christopher Walken star in a film about a distracted father who must turn into a cat to learn his lesson.

headline: Review: In ‘Little Men,’ Boys Develop a Bond That Is Threatened by Money
summary_short: In an adventure story edged with unspoken risks, the young actors take the kind of chances that their more careful elders have been trained to avoid.

headline: Review: Fanciful Classic ‘The Little Prince’ Is Turned Into Modernist Fable
summary_short: A gray corporate world rendered in computer graphics enfolds the stop-motion universe of Antoine de Saint-Exupéry’s tender tale.

headline: Review: Soul of Calypso Elevates the Bollywood-Flavored ‘Bazodee’
summary_short: This romance finds an Indian family from London visiting another in Trinidad and Tobago for a party celebrating their children’s engagement.

headline: Review: In ‘Front Cover,’ Struggling for Self-Acceptance
summary_short: This gay romance, written and directed by Ray Yeung, takes a gentle, thoughtful look at the intersection of ethnicity and sexuality.

headline: Review: In ‘The Brooklyn Banker,’ Troy Garity Shows Promise (With the Mob)
summary_short: The latest entry in the gangster genre, this drama concerns a number cruncher who proves more useful for local gangsters than is healthy.

headline: Review: War Made Terrifyingly Palpable in ‘Citizen Soldier’
summary_short: This documentary powerfully uses footage to track a group of American soldiers during a tour of duty in Afghanistan in 2011.

headline: Review: ‘Five Nights in Maine’ Probes the Pain of Loss
summary_short: In Maris Curran’s delicate drama, a man whose wife has died goes to visit her mother, and the two slowly examine their grief.

headline: Review: ‘Suicide Squad’ Chases Nihilistic Swagger but Trips Over Its Own Feet
summary_short: The death toll is high, and the weapons are nasty, but the overall mood is cautious in this superhero movie from David Ayer.

headline: Review: ‘One More Time With Feeling’ Listens to Nick Cave’s Darkness
summary_short: Andrew Dominik’s 3-D black-and-white documentary focuses on the making of Mr. Cave’s 16th album, “The Skeleton Tree.”

headline: Review: ‘Thank You for Your Service,’ Stories of Soldiers and Suicide
summary_short: This documentary spotlights the lack of support for combat veterans struggling with mental health problems and the tragic consequences of that neglect.

headline: Review: In ‘Theo Who Lived,’ a Journalist Tells of His Capture by Al Qaeda
summary_short: A documentary follows Theo Padnos as he recreates his kidnapping and detainment by anti-American forces in Syria.

headline: Review: ‘M.S. Dhoni: The Untold Story’ Recalls a Cricketer’s Ascent
summary_short: The life of the captain of the winning 2011 World Cup team is recounted in this biopic from Neeraj Pandey.

display_title: Miss Peregrine’s Home for Peculiar Children
headline: Review: In ‘Miss Peregrine’s Home,’ Chasing Grandpa’s Stories Down a Rabbit Hole
summary_short: Tim Burton’s adaptation of the novel by Ransom Riggs describes the adventures of an adolescent who travels through time to prove his grandfather right.

headline: Review: ‘Harry & Snowman’ Recalls a Man and a Horse of Powerful Haunches
summary_short: Ron Davis’s documentary is about Snowman, a white gelding and championship show jumper in his time, and Harry deLeyer, who raised him.

headline: Review: In ‘Amanda Knox,’ a Murder and Journalism Run Amok
summary_short: This documentary about the case of an exchange student killed in Italy focuses less on an accused killer and more on unprincipled journalism and unapologetic sexism.

headline: Review: Youthful Recklessness Finds Adventure on the Road in ‘American Honey’
summary_short: Andrea Arnold’s new feature (her first set in the United States), with a cast mostly of newcomers, follows a band of aimless youths around the country.

headline: Review: In ‘Denial,’ Confronting a Holocaust Revisionist in Court
summary_short: The libel trial of a historian, brought by a Holocaust denier, is dramatized in this sober and methodical film. But the movie lacks an emotional flash point.

headline: Review: The Animated ‘Long Way North’ Finds a Girl on a Journey
summary_short: The movie follows 14-year-old Sacha in the late 1800s as she goes off in search of her lost grandfather.

headline: Review: In ‘A Man Called Ove,’ Don’t Let That Scowl Fool You
summary_short: Adapted from a best-selling Swedish novel, this film stars Rolf Lassgard as a gruff, unemployed railroad worker who befriends immigrants who are his new neighbors.

headline: Review: ‘Masterminds,’ a Tale of Grand Larceny and Meager Gray Matter
summary_short: This comedy from Jared Hess stars Zach Galifianakis as a real-life felon who tried to steal millions of dollars in 1997.

headline: Review: ‘Passage to Mars,’ an Otherworldly Voyage on Earth
summary_short: Scientists train for Mars exploration during a long mission in the unyielding cold of the Arctic, testing equipment that may one day be used in space.

headline: Review: In ‘Deepwater Horizon,’ Oil, Fire and Greed
summary_short: Peter Berg’s film dramatizes a familiar story and stands as a work of popular narrative for an age of corporate impunity.

headline: Review: ‘Chicken People,’ Pampering Royalty That Clucks
summary_short: This documentary, directed by Nicole Lucas Haimes, looks at devotees of these fair fowl on the show circuit.

headline: Review: In ‘Queen of Katwe,’ a Pawn Finds Her Crown Through Chess
summary_short: In this stirring underdog story directed by Mira Nair, Madina Nalwanga plays a young Ugandan with a gift for chess, supported by Lupita Nyong’o as her mother.

headline: Review: In ‘The Lovers and the Despot,’ a Harrowing Korean Ordeal
summary_short: This documentary looks at how and why a South Korean actress, Choi Eun-hee, and a once successful film director, Shin Sang-ok, landed in North Korea.

headline: Review: In ‘Goat,’ Frat Brothers Unleash Their Sadistic Terror
summary_short: Nick Jonas and Ben Schnetzer star in this disturbing tale about the urge to belong, no matter what the cost.

headline: Review: In ‘I.T.,’ Smart House, Dumb Owner
summary_short: This thriller features a computer-controlled home owned by a businessman who isn’t very savvy when it comes to guarding his privacy from wrongdoers.

headline: Review: ‘My Blind Brother,’ Who Is Also a Major Pain
summary_short: Sibling rivalry arises between an arrogant blind athlete and his helpful underdog brother when they end up in a love triangle with an appealing young woman.

headline: Review: ‘1000 Rupee Note,’ a Poor Widow’s Blessing and Curse
summary_short: In this film, set in the Maharashtra State of India, a villager sets off on a fraught shopping trip after receiving a few 1,000-rupee notes at a political rally.

headline: Review: In ‘The Ruins of Lifta,’ a Dispute Amid the Rubble
summary_short: This documentary by Menachem Daum and Oren Rudavsky focuses on the fate of an old Arab village on the outskirts of Jerusalem.

headline: Review: In ‘Seed: The Untold Story,’ It’s Farmers Versus Big Business
summary_short: This documentary raises alarm about declining crop diversity, genetically altered seeds and the ownership of nature.

headline: Review: In ‘The Dressmaker,’ a Femme Fatale Wants Vengeance
summary_short: Tilly Dunnage (Kate Winslet) returns to the dusty Australian hometown where she was bullied by a rich kid and blamed for his death.

headline: Review: ‘Storks,’ an Uneasy Return to Delivering Babies
summary_short: A new animated film, aimed at young children, has an infant that needs a home and a bird on a mission.

headline: Review: Denzel Washington Rides High in ‘The Magnificent Seven’
summary_short: Ethan Hawke, Chris Pratt and Vincent D’Onofrio help round out the cast of this western remake, as outlaws who band together to protect a terrorized town.

headline: Review: ‘Operation Avalanche,’ a Tale of Film Nerds on a Kubrick Caper
summary_short: Matt Johnson and Owen Williams star in this period comedy-thriller about film nerds on a spy mission sneaking onto a set of “2001: A Space Odyssey.”

headline: Review: ‘Blair Witch’: Don’t Go Back Into the Woods
summary_short: This follow-up to the 1999 hit “The Blair Witch Project” offers more gore, more gadgets and 89 minutes of screaming, flashlight waving and falling trees.

headline: Review: In ‘Southwest of Salem,’ 4 Women Convicted of Sexual Assault Fight for Justice
summary_short: The documentary bears witness to crucial moments, such as a relative’s recanted accusation, and persuasively argues that the charges against the women were implausible.

headline: Review: ‘The Vessel’: Learning to Forge Ahead After Wrenching Loss
summary_short: Julio Quintana’s film centers on a young man who arouses ire when he sets out to build a boat after witnessing tragedies in his seaside village.

display_title: The Beatles: Eight Days a Week
headline: Review: ‘The Beatles: Eight Days a Week’ Taking the World by Storm
summary_short: Ron Howard’s documentary explores the wild ride John, Paul, George and Ringo took in the early 1960s, helping to usher in the youth-culture age.

headline: Review: ‘Cardboard Boxer’: Homeless Man’s Redemption via a Diary
summary_short: Thomas Haden Church stars as a lonely skid row denizen whose life gains a new dimension after he finds a disheartened child’s diary.

headline: Review: ‘A Family Affair,’ or Airing Dirty Laundry
summary_short: The Dutch documentarian Tom Fassaert pursues his own history, beginning with his 95-year-old grandmother in South Africa.

headline: Review: In ‘Hillsong — Let Hope Rise,’ a Strumming Ministry Packs in Crowds
summary_short: This sleepy documentary about Hillside United is a portrait of singing “worship leaders” and swaying fans who join in generic anthems at a Los Angeles concert.

display_title: Is That a Gun in Your Pocket?...
headline: Review: A Sex-or-Guns Comedy That Might Make Aristophanes Wince
summary_short: “Is That a Gun in Your Pocket?...” is a clumsy comedy that transports the premise of “Lysistrata” to small-town Texas, with a twist.

headline: Review: ‘Silicon Cowboys’ Tracks the Rise of Compaq Computer
summary_short: This documentary grounds itself in people and technology as it tells the story of a company that was bold at an opportune time in the 1980s.

headline: Review: ‘Snowden,’ Oliver Stone’s Restrained Portrait of a Whistle-Blower
summary_short: This is a movie that does not dazzle or enrage in its evocation of recent history, but creates a cloud of discomfiting doubt.

headline: Review: A Zany Renée Zellweger and Mystery Daddy in ‘Bridget Jones’s Baby’
summary_short: The latest film in this series revolves around the pregnancy of Ms. Zellweger’s character and the two dreamboats most likely to be the father.

headline: Review: ‘When the Bough Breaks,’ Blame a Scary Pregnancy Surrogate
summary_short: This movie, about a well-off couple and the woman they hire to carry their embryo, looks for suspense in a genre that has little left.

headline: Review: In ‘Kicks,’ the Promise (and Perils) of Those Air Jordans
summary_short: This debut feature depicts a 15-year-old in a tough neighborhood who buys the shoes of his dreams — and the desperation he feels when they are taken from him.

headline: Review: In ‘Demon,’ Wedding Jitters From the Uninvited Dead
summary_short: A modern ghost story haunted by the Holocaust, this film by the Polish director Marcin Wrona reconceptualizes the Jewish mythology of the dybbuk.

headline: Review: In ‘As I Open My Eyes,’ Feeling a Revolution Coming
summary_short: A headstrong singer comes of age on the eve of Tunisia’s Jasmine Revolution.

headline: Review: Sully Landed the Plane. Then He Had to Endure the Spotlight.
summary_short: “Sully,” Clint Eastwood’s film about US Airways Flight 1549, largely involves what happens after he, his crew and his passengers are plucked from the Hudson.

headline: Review: ‘Starving the Beast’ Traces the Burdens of Higher Education Defunding
summary_short: This documentary by Steve Mims describes an ideological war over public higher education that is being conducted state by state.

headline: Review: ‘Defying the Nazis’: An American Couple on a Rescue Mission
summary_short: Ken Burns and Artemis Joukowsky’s documentary tells of Waitstill and Martha Sharp, who traveled to Czechoslovakia in 1939 to help Jews and others flee persecution.

headline: Review: ‘Author: The JT Leroy Story’ Renders a Literary Charlatan
summary_short: Jeff Feuerzeig’s documentary charts the invention of an underage H.I.V.-positive hustler, and how the famous and nonfamous were taken in until the hoax was exposed.

headline: Review: ‘Brother Nature’: Fish Out of Water With the Future In-Laws
summary_short: Taran Killam and Bobby Moynihan of “Saturday Night Live” are among the cast in an unfunny comedy set in the woods.

headline: Review: In ‘The Wild Life,’ Island Critters School a Castaway
summary_short: This animated film, long on amiability if not complexity, features amusing animal characters learning to collaborate with a shipwrecked Crusoe.

headline: Review: In ‘Other People,’ a Son’s Anxieties Mount as Tragedy Looms
summary_short: A deeply personal tale from the writer-director Chris Kelly, the movie follows a gay comedy writer in New York who returns home to care for his mother.

headline: Review: ‘Come What May,’ an Ode to French Villagers Displaced by War
summary_short: Christian Carion’s event-packed World War II film lines up an impressive cast but leans toward the sentimental and schematic.

headline: Review: ‘Equal Means Equal’ Asks How Far Women Have Really Come
summary_short: Kamala Lopez’s fact-packed documentary features legal experts, ordinary women and feminists like Eleanor Smeal and Gloria Steinem.

headline: Review: ‘White Girl,’ a Tale of Cocaine, Sex and Privilege
summary_short: Elizabeth Wood’s film stars Morgan Saylor as a wild college ingenue who winds up struggling when her new drug-dealing boyfriend is arrested.

headline: Review: In ‘Zoom,’ Everyone Feels Certain Body Parts Are Too Small
summary_short: Alison Pill, Jason Priestley, Gael García Bernal and Mariana Ximenes star in Pedro Morelli’s amusing mix of animation and live action.

headline: Review: A Baby in a Boat Changes Everything in ‘The Light Between Oceans’
summary_short: Michael Fassbender and Alicia Vikander play an Australian couple who long for a child — and happen to find one — in this post-World War I romance.

headline: Review: ‘Max Rose’ Has Jerry Lewis Tearful Over a Hint of Infidelity
summary_short: Mr. Lewis, for all his outsize comic credentials, can be a formidable dramatic actor, but this film provides no space for the story’s darker corners.

headline: Review: In Kevin Smith’s ‘Yoga Hosers,’ Enlightenment Is Elusive
summary_short: This film, the second in a comedy-horror trilogy, features a quirky Johnny Depp and two heroines named Colleen.

headline: Review: ‘The 9th Life of Louis Drax.’ So, Little Boys Get Nine Lives, Too?
summary_short: “The 9th Life of Louis Drax” starts with a disastrous ninth birthday and some unanswered questions.

headline: Review: Jokes, Not Punches, Land With a Thud in ‘Skiptrace’
summary_short: In “Skiptrace,” Jackie Chan tries the unlikely-buddy conceit again, this time with Johnny Knoxville.

headline: Review: In ‘Kickboxer: Vengeance,’ Duty Calls for an Unpracticed Fighter
summary_short: In John Stockwell’s film, a man seeking to avenge his slain brother trains under a martial-arts master. Guess who: Jean-Claude Van Damme.

headline: Review: ‘The Pickle Recipe’ Is a Sweet and Sour Caper
summary_short: In this comedy, a grandson in need of money plots with an uncle to steal the recipe for his grandmother’s famous pickles.

headline: Review: Iggy Pop Bares All, and Nothing, in ‘Gimme Danger’
summary_short: Jim Jarmusch’s reverent documentary on Iggy Pop, a provocateur, is prim: It includes no retrospective scenes of drug use or the bandmates’ fights.

headline: Review: In ‘Inferno,’ Breathlessly Globe-Trotting and Decoding to Save the World
summary_short: The symbologist played by Tom Hanks returns in another Dan Brown tale told at Ron Howard speed.

headline: Review: ‘By Sidney Lumet’ Puts the Director in Front of the Camera
summary_short: The documentary began as a series of interviews shot in 2008 in which the director talks about his life and work.

headline: Review: In ‘Mr. Donkey,’ a Village School’s Ruse Farcically Backfires
summary_short: A parable about China’s past and perhaps its present underlies this mildly stagy and intermittently manic adaptation.

headline: Review: ‘The Unspoken’: If You Move Here, Find a Realtor Fast
summary_short: This thriller features a creaky building where something eerie once happened, and where Jodelle Ferland plays the nanny to a boy who has just moved in.

headline: Review: In ‘Supersonic,’ the Band Oasis and Its Combative Brothers
summary_short: This documentary looks at the rock group’s founding members, Liam and Noel Gallagher, through older footage and animated re-creations.

headline: Review: ‘Boo! A Madea Halloween’ Finds Tyler Perry in the Usual Costume(s)
summary_short: Mr. Perry’s most popular character is back again to crack wise and deliver advice in this comedy. He plays some other people, too.

headline: Review: In ‘Ouija: Origin of Evil,’ a Youngster Who Nails ‘Creepy’
summary_short: In this prequel to “Ouija,” Lulu Wilson delivers chills as a girl with a psychic link to a malevolent board game.

headline: ‘Moonlight’: Is This the Year’s Best Movie?
summary_short: Our critic A.O. Scott says this film about a young black man’s coming of age is both a disarmingly personal film and an urgent social document.

headline: Review: Tom Cruise Has a Familiar Furrow in ‘Jack Reacher: Never Go Back’
summary_short: Mr. Cruise returns as this title character to fight menace in Edward Zwick’s film.

headline: Review: ‘American Pastoral,’ Philip Roth’s Fiery 1960s at Low Heat
summary_short: Ewan McGregor’s directorial debut is a shallow but watchable gloss on this Roth novel, conjuring a searing image of the disintegrating American dream.

headline: Review: Don’t Mess With the Dog in ‘In a Valley of Violence’
summary_short: A mysterious stranger rides into a decaying mining town with horse and collie. He didn’t mean to kick up trouble.

headline: Review: ‘Keeping Up With the Joneses’ Might Not Be Worth It
summary_short: This film about a spy couple has star power in Jon Hamm, but utilitarian construction and a lack of chemistry are downfalls.

headline: Review: ‘It Had to Be You’ Is a Witty Rom-Com With a 1950s Feel
summary_short: Cristin Milioti plays an ambivalent woman weighing commitment in this film with a throwback touch.

headline: Review: In ‘The Uncondemned,’ Rwandan Rape Survivors Seek Justice
summary_short: Facing an uphill battle, a small legal team puts a former Rwandan mayor on trial for his role in encouraging and ordering rapes during the country’s 1994 genocide.

headline: Review: In ‘Before the Flood,’ Leonardo DiCaprio Sounds the Climate-Change Alarm
summary_short: A new documentary chronicles environmental degradation that leads to global warming and suggests steps to reduce it.

headline: Review: In ‘Miss Hokusai,’ an Apprentice to the Artistic Life
summary_short: This extraordinary film is a lively inquiry into the life of the daughter of the 19th-century Japanese painter Katsushika Hokusai.

headline: Review: In ‘Kevin Hart: What Now?,’ a Stadium Brimming With Brash Stand-Up
summary_short: The comedian documents his popular 2015 tour in ways surprising and satisfying two-thirds of the time.

headline: Review: In ‘Christine,’ Why Did She Pull the Trigger? We Don’t Know
summary_short: In this dramatization of a true story, Rebecca Hall is riveting as Christine Chubbuck, a television news reporter who killed herself on the air.

headline: Review: ‘Certain Women’ Are Worlds Unto Themselves
summary_short: Kelly Reichardt’s film centers on a collection of women in a small town, and their individual tensions, sorrow and longing.

headline: Review: ‘Coming Through the Rye’ Tracks Down J.D. Salinger
summary_short: The film, written and directed by James Sadwith, is a fictionalized version of Mr. Sadwith’s meeting with J.D. Salinger.

headline: Review: A Crooked Cop Is Caught Between 2 Brutal Masters in ‘Asura: The City of Madness’
summary_short: This film offers diversion but not sociological scope. Blood flows freely.

headline: Review: Stranded Migrants Are Easy Marks for a Madman in ‘Desierto’
summary_short: Lots of carnage and only a little back story equal a grim movie.

headline: Review: ‘Huntwatch’ Chronicles a Hard-Fought Battle to Protect Seals
summary_short: This film, one-sided in its approach, offers painful footage of the bludgeoning of pups in charting the decades-old movement against seal hunting.

headline: Review: For ‘Jack Goes Home,’ Cue the Horror Soundtrack
summary_short: Rory Culkin plays a magazine editor who returns to his hometown after his father is killed in a car crash, and delves into a past that’s deeply troubled.

display_title: Maya Angelou: And Still I Rise
headline: Review: ‘Maya Angelou: And Still I Rise,’ a Life Well Lived
summary_short: Photographs and film footage, as well as interviews with her son and artists who worked with her, add another dimension this documentary of a storied life.

headline: Review: In ‘The Accountant,’ Ben Affleck Plays a Savant With a Dark Secret
summary_short: The film stars Mr. Affleck as a genius on the autism spectrum whose proficiency with numbers leads him into a shady world.

headline: Review: ‘Godzilla’ Returns, Again, With a Wink
summary_short: “Shin Godzilla” puts Tokyo in peril. Can the bumbling bureaucrats get their act together in time?

headline: Review: ‘Middle School,’ Where the Principal Is Mean and the Pranks Messy
summary_short: This movie, adapted from a book from James Patterson’s library, follows a protagonist struggling with life in a new school and a nasty administrator.

headline: Review: An Undetonated Missile and Evil Spirits Lurk in ‘Under the Shadow’
summary_short: In this horror film, a woman with a husband away on the front is left with her daughter, an unexploded missile and possibly a supernatural visitor.

headline: Review: ‘Voyage of Time,’ the Cosmology of Terrence Malick (the Short Version)
summary_short: Brad Pitt narrates a 45-minute Imax version of Mr. Malick’s documentary, a tour of astrophysics, biology, philosophy and religion. A feature-length cut will be released later to conventional theaters.

headline: Review: In ‘Mirzya,’ Echoes of ‘Romeo and Juliet,’ Lushly Shot
summary_short: Fine leading performances lift this film, which is based on a Punjab folk tale of star-crossed lovers.

headline: Review: ‘37,’ a Fictional Retelling of the Kitty Genovese Story
summary_short: This version of the story returns to the popular, but discredited belief that dozens of people deliberately ignored the cries of Ms. Genovese.

headline: Review: ‘The Great Gilly Hopkins,’ a Child’s Story Elevated by Grown-Ups
summary_short: Although this film centers on an unruly foster child adapting to a new home, the real heart of the movie lies in the performances of Kathy Bates and Glenn Close.

headline: Review: ‘The Late Bloomer,’ About a Sex Therapist Who Missed Puberty
summary_short: This comedy, directed by Kevin Pollak, searches somewhat desperately for laughs in the premise of 30-year-olds acting like frat boys.

headline: Review: In Nate Parker’s ‘The Birth of a Nation,’ Must-See and Won’t-See Collide
summary_short: This film about Nat Turner’s slave rebellion is an ambitious attempt to corral the contradictions of history within the conventions of popular narrative.

headline: Review: In ‘The Girl on the Train,’ a Boozy Emily Blunt Never Winks
summary_short: In this adaptation of the best-selling mystery by Paula Hawkins, Ms. Blunt is one of three unreliable narrators, a heavy-drinking fantasist at that.

headline: Review: ‘Homeland: Iraq Year Zero’ Chronicles a War-Torn Family
summary_short: This two-part film from Abbas Fahdel gives a before-and-after account of his relatives’ lives around the time of the 2003 conflict.

headline: Review: Compassion Is Expensive for a Cabby in ‘Old Stone’
summary_short: Chen Gang plays a Chinese taxi driver trapped in a bureaucratic nightmare after he accidentally hits a motorcyclist.

headline: Review: In ‘Dear Zindagi,’ a Conflicted Woman in Search of a Truer Life
summary_short: Gauri Shinde’s sharply observed film depicts a young cinematographer torn between various impulses who finds guidance from a psychologist.

headline: Review: Two Friends Take a Trip, Heavy Baggage in Tow, in ‘Always Shine’
summary_short: Actresses try to renew their friendship during a weekend visit to Big Sur, Calif., but jealousies and old resentments bubble up.

headline: Review: ‘Evolution’ Goes to a Magical Place You Wouldn’t Want to Live In
summary_short: A young boy’s creepy childhood in a picturesque seaside village with an unsettling goings-on.

headline: Review: The Nature Documentary ‘Seasons’ Looks at Land Animals
summary_short: Jacques Perrin and Jacques Cluzaud, whose projects include ‘Winged Migration’ and ‘Oceans,’ explore the fate of the forests that once covered Europe.

headline: Review: ‘Mifune: The Last Samurai’ Celebrates a Fearless Actor
summary_short: The documentary, narrated by Keanu Reeves, interviews directors, actors and others to gain insights into Toshiro Mifune’s sword-fighting bravado and stoicism.

headline: Review: ‘Lion’ Brings Tears for a Lost Boy, Wiped Dry by Google
summary_short: Saroo’s journey begins when he accidentally travels more than 1,000 miles from his home in central India to the streets of Calcutta.

headline: Review: A Chilly ‘Miss Sloane’ Makes a Lecture Out of Lobbying
summary_short: Jessica Chastain stars as a win-at-all-costs lobbyist in this Washington-based political thriller.

headline: Review: ‘Allied,’ With Brad Pitt and Marion Cotillard, Uncorks a Favorite Vintage
summary_short: “Allied” is not so much a work of art as a triumph of craft, possibly the purest and most relaxed demonstration of the director Robert Zemeckis’s mastery.

headline: Review: ‘Rules Don’t Apply’ Features Warren Beatty as Howard Hughes
summary_short: This film takes comic aim at Hollywood absurdity and at Hughes, the eccentric mogul.

headline: Review: ‘Moana,’ Brave Princess on a Voyage With a Chicken
summary_short: In Disney’s new animated adventure, the daughter of a chief must prove herself while music plays and the sun shines on the sea.

headline: Review: ‘Bad Santa 2’ Works Through Mommy Issues
summary_short: This sequel addresses two unnecessary questions: What if bad Santa weren’t so bad? And what if he had an estranged and equally foul mother?

headline: Review: ‘Bleed for This’ Is a Boxing Movie That Gets Boxing
summary_short: The film tells the true story of the brash fighter Vinny Pazienza, who fractured his neck in a car accident but earned his place back in the ring.

headline: Review: ‘The Edge of Seventeen’ Takes Teenage Movies to a Higher Place
summary_short: In its raw honesty, “The Edge of Seventeen,” like “Clueless,” is among the best films about high school kids in years.

headline: Review: ‘Uncle Howard’ Looks Back at a Filmmaker’s Work Cut Short
summary_short: This documentary is a dual portrait of intertwined artists: Howard Brookner, who died of AIDS early in his career, and his nephew Aaron Brookner, now also a filmmaker.

headline: Review: A Pickpocket Is Recruited by the C.I.A. in ‘The Take’
summary_short: Idris Elba and Richard Madden star in this well-executed variation of the buddy-cop formula, set in Paris.

headline: Review: ‘Blood on the Mountain’ Looks at the Ravages of Coal Mining
summary_short: This documentary about the industry in West Virginia is not well made but raises timely issues.

headline: Review: ‘A Street Cat Named Bob’ Helps His Owner Detox
summary_short: With Bob on his shoulder, a homeless busker, James, is able to face just about anything — a negligent father, street ruffians and drug withdrawal.

headline: Review: ‘I Am Not Madame Bovary’ Takes Man Trouble to New Levels
summary_short: A Chinese comedic melodrama, with a divorce of convenience followed by a real jilting, has situational intrigue marred by a labored approach.

headline: Review: ‘Magnus’ Delves Into the Life of a ‘Mozart of Chess’
summary_short: Even fans of chess might struggle to connect with the cursory approach to this documentary’s subject, the prodigy Magnus Carlsen, and to the game itself.

headline: Review: ‘Manchester by the Sea’ and the Tides of Grief
summary_short: The film, written and directed by Kenneth Lonergan and starring Casey Affleck, finds a man quietly dealing with tragedies.

display_title: Fantastic Beasts and Where to Find Them
headline: Review: ‘Fantastic Beasts’ Unleashes J.K. Rowling’s Magic on Old New York
summary_short: Eddie Redmayne stars as a visitor to the city with a very stuffed magic suitcase in “Fantastic Beasts and Where to Find Them.”

headline: Review: ‘The Illinois Parables’ Soothes and Inflames Feelings About America
summary_short: This hourlong essay film by Deborah Stratman juxtaposes pastoral images with a chronicle of violence, dispossession and disaster.

headline: Review: ‘Hunter Gatherer’ Profiles Two Men Living on the Margins
summary_short: Running in place is the point of Josh Locy’s film, which spotlights the repetitive daily struggles of those with few resources beyond optimism and resolve.

headline: Review: ‘Shut In’ (Naomi Watts Should Really Get Out More)
summary_short: Ms. Watts plays a widowed child psychologist in a big, rambling house with one boy in a vegetative state and another who may be a ghost.

headline: Review: Aliens Drop Anchor in ‘Arrival,’ but What Are Their Intentions?
summary_short: In Denis Villeneuve’s film, Amy Adams plays a linguist struggling to understand interplanetary visitors checking in at 12 spots around the globe.

headline: Review: In ‘Elle,’ Isabelle Huppert Subverts the Role of Rape Victim
summary_short: Paul Verhoeven’s film is a psychological thriller, a strangely dry-eyed melodrama, a kinky sex farce and a savage comedy of bourgeois manners.

headline: Review: ‘Almost Christmas,’ a Home-for-the-Holidays Comedy
summary_short: David E. Talbert’s film is often disarmingly entertaining, with an appealing and talented cast that includes Danny Glover, Gabrielle Union and Mo’Nique.

headline: Review: ‘National Bird’ Follows Whistle-Blowers in America’s Drone War
summary_short: Sonia Kennebeck’s elegantly unsettling documentary explores the United States’ reliance on aerial combat drones and the emotional and collateral damage.

headline: Review: ‘The Anthropologist’ Tells a Mother-Daughter Story, With Rising Seawater
summary_short: This documentary from the makers of “The Linguists” uses subtle juxtaposition to meditate on change and adaptability.

headline: Review: A Pianist Adrift Encounters a Cougar in ‘Dreamland’
summary_short: Robert Schwartzman’s understated sex comedy, his first feature, is a bittersweet study of a man who hasn’t yet taken control of his life.

headline: Review: ‘Come and Find Me.’ Then Again, Maybe Not.
summary_short: Aaron Paul of “Breaking Bad” and Annabelle Wallis star as a couple torn asunder in this thriller, which Zack Whedon wrote and directed.

headline: Review: In ‘Lazy Eye,’ Yakking Ex-Lovers Reconnect
summary_short: After a graphic designer in California invites his ex-boyfriend to spend the weekend, lovemaking and much talk ensue.

headline: Review: ‘Billy Lynn’s Long Halftime Walk’: Ang Lee’s Super-High-Definition Take on the Iraq War
summary_short: “Billy Lynn’s Long Halftime Walk” is Mr. Lee’s film about innocence, adapted from a novel about the gulf that separates modern soldiers from everyone else.

headline: Review: In ‘Loving,’ They Loved. A Segregated Virginia Did Not Love Them Back.
summary_short: Jeff Nichols’s “Loving” is a fictionalization of the story of Mildred and Richard Loving, an interracial couple whose civil rights case went to the Supreme Court.

headline: Review: ‘The Prison in Twelve Landscapes’ Reveals the Invisible Tentacles of Mass Incarceration
summary_short: An unexpectedly moving look at the elements of the confinement industry that hide in plain sight.

headline: Review: ‘Doctor Strange’ and His Most Excellent Adventure
summary_short: This film is so giddily enjoyable and visually transfixing, you might forget that it’s part of Marvel’s strategy for world domination.

headline: Review: ‘The Ivory Game’ Follows the Fight to Protect Elephants
summary_short: This documentary, filmed in Africa and China, ruminates on the high stakes of poachers killing these animals for their tusks.

headline: Review: ‘Ivory. A Crime Story,’ or the Plight of African Elephants
summary_short: This documentary from Sergey Yastrzhembsky treats the unpleasant subject of the elephants and ivory smuggling with the harshness it deserves.

headline: Review: The ‘Trolls’ Embark on a High-Haired Rescue Mission
summary_short: This DreamWorks film, voiced by stars like Anna Kendrick and Justin Timberlake, follows the adventures of a colorful group and their nemesis.

headline: Review: ‘My Dead Boyfriend’ Shares a Life, After the Fact
summary_short: Heather Graham plays a woman in 1990s New York who begins to learn about her boyfriend only after he’s dead, in this film directed by Anthony Edwards.

headline: Review: In ‘Rainbow Time,’ Big Brother’s Watching (and Lusting)
summary_short: Linas Phillips’s film revolves around a developmentally disabled 40-year-old virgin — a bully who uses his condition to guilt others into excusing his bad behavior.

headline: Review: In ‘Trash Fire,’ a Familiar Formula Fails
summary_short: Adrian Grenier stars in this black comedy from Richard Bates Jr.

headline: Review: ‘Hacksaw Ridge’ Has the Guts and the Glory. But Where’s the Gun?
summary_short: Mel Gibson’s new film tells the true story of Desmond Doss, a conscientious objector who refused to bear arms but still won the Medal of Honor in World War II.

display_title: Accidental Courtesy: Daryl Davis, Race & America
headline: Review: ‘Accidental Courtesy’ Is Gentle Persuasion for Bigots
summary_short: A man who confronts racism with friendliness in his travels.

headline: Review: In Jim Jarmusch’s ‘Paterson,’ a Meditative Flow of Words Into Poetry
summary_short: This story of a soulful bus driver and basement poet is deceptively simple and nearly perfect, with a likely nod to William Carlos Williams.

headline: Review: In ‘Toni Erdmann,’ Dad’s a Prankster Trying to Jolt His Conformist Daughter
summary_short: The funniest almost-three-hour German comedy you will ever see, Maren Ade’s film is a thrilling act of defiance against the toxicity of doing what is expected.

headline: Review: A Father’s Dreams, Recast by His Daughters in ‘Dangal’
summary_short: This Bollywood film about a father who trains his two daughters to be wrestlers sets emotions to full blast and wears it heart firmly on its sleeve.

headline: Review: ‘Why Him?’ Better Yet, Why This Movie?
summary_short: Proving definitively that slapping James Franco’s scenery-eating grin on any old drivel doesn’t guarantee entertainment, this film is trite, crass and moronic.

headline: Review: Another Woman on the Verge in Almodóvar’s ‘Julieta’
summary_short: Pedro Almodóvar’s heroine in his new movie about loss is drawn from the stories of Alice Munro; both artists are attuned to the inner lives of women.

headline: Review: ‘Assassin’s Creed’ Whisks Michael Fassbender to 1492 Spain
summary_short: Mr. Fassbender plays a convict who experiences the actions of his assassin ancestor in this time-bending film based on the video game of the same name.

headline: Review: Two ‘Passengers’ Trapped on a Spaceship Find Love Amid Despair
summary_short: Jennifer Lawrence stars in this interplanetary romance aboard a mechanically doomed spacecraft making a 120-year voyage.

headline: Review: ‘Sing’ Gives Animated Belters a Stage
summary_short: In this cartoon musical directed by Garth Jennings, a koala voiced by Matthew McConaughey tries to revive his fortunes with a singing competition.

headline: Review: Beneath the Bombast, ‘Fences’ Has an Aching Poetry
summary_short: Starring Denzel Washington, who also directed, and Viola Davis, this film adaptation of August Wilson’s play features performances of unmatched force.

headline: Review: ‘Neruda’ Pursues the Poet as Fugitive
summary_short: Pablo Larraín’s biopic about the Chilean poet pits the state versus the sensual.

headline: Review: Lots of Plastic in the Face of ‘Collateral Beauty’
summary_short: The movie, starring Will Smith, riffs on “A Christmas Carol” as it tells a story of a man who experiences the loss of a child.

headline: Review: A ‘Short Stay,’ but Long Stuck in a Rut
summary_short: This Ted Fendt film centers on a young man who gets a small jolt, but still can’t escape from his drab existence.

headline: Review: ‘Two Lovers and a Bear’ Walk Onto Some Arctic Ice
summary_short: Kim Nguyen’s film focuses on a pair of damaged young souls enveloped in beauty, absurdity and, despite the cold air, a lot of overheated romanticism.

headline: Review: ‘The Wasted Times,’ a Hopscotching Shanghai Crime Tale
summary_short: Cheng Er’s gangland drama unwinds nonchronologically, like episodes of a mini-series shown out of order.

display_title: Rogue One: A Star Wars Story
headline: Review: ‘Rogue One’ Leaves ‘Star Wars’ Fans Wanting More and Less
summary_short: This film, masquerading as a heroic tale of rebellion, falls short of the insurgent energy of its predecessors in the franchise.

headline: Review: Ryan Gosling and Emma Stone Aswirl in Tra La La Land
summary_short: Ms. Stone and Mr. Gosling sing and dance their way to art and love in Damien Chazelle’s new movie.

headline: Review: Katie Holmes Directs Her First Feature, ‘All We Had’
summary_short: A teenage girl and her downtrodden mother struggle to build a normal life, but any progress they make seems to unravel.

headline: Review: ‘Frank & Lola,’ Retreading Old Ground
summary_short: Frankie and Johnny’s story returns, written and directed by Matthew Ross, but not much has changed except the actors and how well they fit together.

headline: Review: A Trip to Hell, via the VCR, in ‘Beyond the Gates’
summary_short: In this horror movie, two brothers play an old-school board game with a videotape and run into Barbara Crampton of “Re-Animator.”

headline: Review: An Afghan in a Strange Land (California) in ‘Burn Country’
summary_short: A former assistant to a war journalist resettles in small-town America, where culture clashes turn mysterious and dangerous.

headline: Review: ‘Harry Benson: Shoot First,’ on Photographing the Beatles and Others
summary_short: This adulatory profile focuses on a photojournalist who has documented many high-profile figures, but it skips some hard questions.

headline: Review: You’ve Got to Fight for Your Right to an ‘Office Christmas Party’
summary_short: Directed by Josh Gordon and Will Speck, this bawdy comedy is full of familiar faces, including Kate McKinnon and Courtney B. Vance, behaving badly.

headline: Review: ‘Slash’ Has Proud Outcasts With Bold Imaginations
summary_short: This sweet-natured coming-of-age movie is perhaps more complicated than most by having characters whose sexual orientations are in flux.

headline: Review: You Quit? Think Again, ‘Sword Master’
summary_short: A swordsman has grown tired of his work and his love in this remake of “Death Duel,” a nod to the Chinese magic-and-martial arts genre wuxia.

headline: Review: ‘Best and Most Beautiful Things,’ About a Disabled Woman’s Place in the World
summary_short: This documentary follows a young woman who is legally blind and has Asperger’s syndrome as she enters adulthood and explores a new identity.

headline: ‘Jackie’: Under the Widow’s Weeds, a Myth Marketer
summary_short: Natalie Portman is perfect in Pablo Larraín’s multifaceted portrait of the former first lady Jacqueline Kennedy as an embodiment of grief and as an architect of brilliant political theater.

headline: Review: ‘The Duelist’ Is a Good Shot. A Very Good Shot.
summary_short: In this Aleksey Mizgirev film set in 1860 St. Petersburg, an ex-nobleman makes his living as a proxy in honor matches of shooting skill.

headline: Review: ‘Man Down’ Looks at Combat Trauma Through a Marine’s Eyes
summary_short: Dito Montiel’s film, which stars Shia LaBeouf as a scarred veteran, imparts the urgency of its issue more effectively with statistics than with its script.

headline: Review: That ‘Pet’ at the Shelter Looks Like a Caged Woman
summary_short: This Carles Torrens film centers on a psychological duel between an animal shelter worker and a former crush.

headline: Review: ‘Siren’ Suggests Grooms-to-Be Ought to Stay Home
summary_short: A bachelor party goes horribly awry in this feature-length treatment by Gregg Bishop of a segment in the horror anthology “V/H/S.”

headline: Review: ‘Sky on Fire,’ or Is That Just a Gleaming C.G.I. Skyscraper?
summary_short: A corporate conspiracy with a medical company is at the center of this classical Hong Kong action film directed by Ringo Lam.

headline: Review: ‘Nocturnal Animals,’ Brutality Between the Pages and Among the Fabulous
summary_short: This thriller, directed by Tom Ford, toggles between the life of a wealthy woman (Amy Adams) and the events in a novel she is reading by her ex-husband.

display_title: Backstreet Boys: Show 'Em What You're Made Of
headline: Back When They Were Fab
summary_short: In “Backstreet Boys: Show ’Em What You’re Made Of,” members of that boy band reminisce, relax and occasionally rehearse.

headline: With Ability to Script Success, What Could Go Wrong?
summary_short: “Project Almanac,” portrayed as if the film’s footage were shot by the characters, traces a group of friends as they try to manipulate their lives through time travel.

headline: Take My Iraqi Niece, Please
summary_short: In Sean Mullin’s “Amira & Sam,” an Army veteran and aspiring comedian becomes the protector of his old Iraqi translator’s beautiful relative.

headline: Race Relations on the Family Tree
summary_short: In “Black or White,” Kevin Costner and Octavia Spencer battle each other for custody of their biracial granddaughter.

headline: Jewish American Pilots Fighting for Israel
summary_short: The documentary “Above and Beyond” recounts the story of Jewish American pilots who secretly fought for Israel during its War of Independence.

headline: Not Quite Sure About Happily Ever After
summary_short: In “We’ll Never Have Paris,” a florist on the cusp of proposing to his longtime girlfriend begins to wonder what it would be like to see other women.

headline: When Hunky Neighbor Becomes Homicidal Stalker
summary_short: Jennifer Lopez plays a teacher who comes to regret a one-night stand in “The Boy Next Door.”

headline: To Fight, Flee or Simply Join Them?
summary_short: “Son of a Gun” teams a hardened criminal portrayed by Ewan McGregor with his 19-year-old protégé in a brutish Australian action-adventure fantasy.

headline: Pleasure, Dealt Painfully
summary_short: In ‘R100,” by Hitoshi Matsumoto, a salaryman hires a sadism service to deliver dominatrixes wielding punishment on a regular basis.

headline: Comes an Aristocrat, Mustache Flaring
summary_short: In “Mortdecai,” Johnny Depp plays a rakish aristocrat who hopes to pay off an enormous tax debt by tracking down and selling a missing Goya painting.

headline: Sparring in the Boxing Ring, in Politics and in Life
summary_short: The documentary “Manny” is the story of Manny Pacquiao, a tiny Filipino boxer who emerged as a champion, a congressman and a natural showman.

headline: Spilling a Love Potion on a Fairy Princess
summary_short: Gary Rydstrom’s animated “Strange Magic” is based on a story by George Lucas inspired by “A Midsummer Night’s Dream” and populated with fairies, elves and goblins.

headline: The Grief Spread Across the Road to Recovery
summary_short: Jennifer Aniston plays a woman recovering from a horrific accident in “Cake,” a drama directed by Daniel Barnz.

headline: A Rum Crew Jettisons All Reason
summary_short: In “Black Sea,” Jude Law stars as a sailor who seizes on a chance to explore for undersea gold with a rough and greedy crew.

headline: Unshackled Hacker Dons a White Hat
summary_short: In Michael Mann’s “Blackhat,” a hacker is provisionally released from prison to combat a cybercriminal who has sabotaged a nuclear plant and manipulated a financial market.

headline: Adventures of a Peruvian Immigrant (the Furry Variety)
summary_short: The beloved bear of children’s books makes his big-screen debut in Paul King’s “Paddington.”

headline: An Education on Camera and Behind It
summary_short: College students helped make “Northern Borders,” a coming-of-age film set in Vermont.

headline: Have Tux, Will Babysit Groom
summary_short: In “The Wedding Ringer,” a comedy directed by Jeremy Garelick, Kevin Hart plays a professional best man for grooms who lack friends.

headline: Contrapuntal Hum of a Worker’s Hive
summary_short: Denis Côté’s semi-documentary “Joy of Man’s Desiring” captures the humanity of factory workers as they encounter frustrations and the occasional moment of satisfaction.

headline: Focusing on the Margins of Society
summary_short: Adam Rifkin’s new documentary follows Giuseppe Andrews as he rounds up his neighbors at a trailer park (and assorted transients) to shoot his latest film.

headline: A Dance Instructor Amid Twists and Reversals
summary_short: In “Match,” Patrick Stewart plays a dance professor at Juilliard who becomes involved in a confrontation with a woman interviewing him for her dissertation and her husband.

headline: Another Avenging Rampage
summary_short: Liam Neeson returns as the retired government agent Bryan Mills in “Taken 3.”

headline: Seeking Solace Elsewhere, Before Encountering It at Home
summary_short: “Valley of Saints” tells the story of two men whose plans are disrupted by a military curfew and whose friendship is threatened by a shared love interest.

headline: Finding Her Way Back in Small, Slow Steps
summary_short: In “Something, Anything,” a young newlywed disrupts her closest relationships as she tries to put her life back together after a traumatic loss.

headline: Codes and Vendettas, Frozen in Time
summary_short: A Civil War legacy cascades through the backwoods of North Carolina in the 1970s in “The World Made Straight,” an overcooked adaptation of a Ron Rash novel.

headline: When Traveling Through Time, Pack a Change of Identities
summary_short: Based on a short story by the science-fiction writer Robert A. Heinlein, “Predestination” tracks the journeys of a Temporal Agent assigned to right wrongs before they happen.

headline: Captive, and Not Just to the Internet
summary_short: In “Dark Summer,” a teenager becomes the victim of his online obsession.

headline: Challenging Corruption in the Niger Delta
