summary_short: “Black November,” a blood-for-oil drama directed by Jeta Amata, follows a Nigerian activist who mobilized opposition after a deadly explosion.

display_title: The Woman in Black 2: Angel of Death
headline: A Ghost With a Grudge (Watch Out, Kids!)
summary_short: In “The Woman in Black 2: Angel of Death,” a ghost with a vendetta against the young leaves behind the Edwardian setting of its predecessor for 1941.

headline: Finding Meaning in a Dish
summary_short: Ian Cheney’s documentary “The Search for General Tso” is about history, heritage and struggle as much as about a certain chicken dish popular in Chinese restaurants.

headline: Heating Oil Mixed With Trouble
summary_short: A family, its heating-oil business and New York are at the center of J. C. Chandor’s “A Most Violent Year.”

headline: A 50-Mile March, Nearly 50 Years Later
summary_short: Ava DuVernay’s film “Selma” follows civil rights demonstrators in March 1965 across an Alabama bridge and into a new era for black Americans, with progress made and promises unkept.

headline: Review: ‘American Sniper,’ a Clint Eastwood Film With Bradley Cooper
summary_short: Clint Eastwood’s latest film is about Chris Kyle, a Navy SEAL who served tours of duty in Iraq.

headline: Noir Days of Sun, Los Angeles Smog and Marijuana Haze
summary_short: “Inherent Vice,” Paul Thomas Anderson’s adaptation of the Thomas Pynchon novel, is a labyrinthine noir set in sunny Los Angeles, circa 1970.

headline: Taken Down by Twisted Ambition
summary_short: Starring Steve Carell and Channing Tatum, “Foxcatcher,” directed by Bennett Miller, tells the true-crime story of an Olympic wrestler and his multimillionaire sponsor.

headline: Oscar Shorts, From Surreal to Oh So Real
summary_short: The short-film nominees for Oscars — animated, live action and documentaries, from around the world — can be viewed together in three collections.

headline: Portrait of Youth
summary_short: In “Miss Granny,” a woman whose family plans to place her in a retirement home suddenly turns back into her 20-year-old self.

headline: A Boy Finds a Lost Generation
summary_short: “Life Is Strange” is an oral history of displaced European Jews, as survivors recall their childhoods before and during the Holocaust, with narration by a boy.

headline: Airlifting Big Cats From Circus Hell
summary_short: The documentary “Lion Ark” follows a team of rescuers as they track down lions exploited in Bolivian shows.

headline: Review: ‘Field Niggas’ Is a Meditation on Life on the Streets of East Harlem
summary_short: The director Khalik Allah shows people existing in a form of bondage, often created by drug addiction, but he manages to find radiance as well.

headline: Review: ‘Around the World in 50 Concerts,’ a Documentary, Follows an Orchestra
summary_short: Heddy Honigmann’s film looks at the Royal Concertgebouw Orchestra on its 125th anniversary tour in 2013.

headline: Review: In ‘Futuro Beach,’ a Haunted Lifeguard Searches for Peace
summary_short: This elliptical gay romance by the Brazilian writer and director Karim Aïnouz follows its heroes from the warmly golden beach of the title to the cool dampness of Berlin.

headline: Review: In ‘Bluebird,’ Momentary Distraction Sets Off a Chain of Misery
summary_short: In this film set in a Maine logging town, a school-bus driver deals with the repercussions of a tragic mistake.

headline: Review: ‘The Widowmaker,’ a Heart Care Documentary
summary_short: Patrick Forbes’s film looks at doctors’ treatment recommendations after heart attacks, comparing the coronary calcium scan with the more expensive, more frequently used surgically implanted stent.

headline: Review: In ‘The Lazarus Effect,’ Young Scientists Play God
summary_short: Olivia Wilde stars as a researcher brought back from the dead in David Gelb’s horror thriller.

headline: Review: In ‘Focus,’ a Grifter (Will Smith) as Life Coach
summary_short: Mr. Smith plays a seasoned con man who schools a novice (Margot Robbie) in more sophisticated scams.

headline: Review: David Cronenberg Dissects Hollywood in ‘Maps to the Stars’
summary_short: The film imagines Los Angeles as an inferno of narcissism, greed and sexual perversity.

headline: Review: ‘Wild Canaries’: Love, Death and Suspicious Minds
summary_short: In this caper by Lawrence Michael Levine, a young Brooklyn couple suspect the worst after a neighbor is found dead.

headline: Review: In ‘McFarland, USA,’ Kevin Costner Coaches Cross-Country Runners
summary_short: In “McFarland USA,” Mr. Costner leads a team of Hispanic high schoolers to a championship, while getting closer to them and their families.

headline: Review: ‘Hot Tub Time Machine 2’ Heads Back to the Bubbles
summary_short: The sequel to “Hot Tub Time Machine” features Rob Corddry and Craig Robinson playing characters who have benefited from learning about the future in the first film.

headline: Review: In ‘The DUFF,’ a Wounded Teenage Girl Combats Mockery
summary_short: When a student learns she is called the “designated ugly fat friend,” she sets out on a makeover without realizing that vindictiveness is the real problem.

display_title: What We Do in the Shadows
headline: Review: ‘What We Do in the Shadows,’ a Vampire Comedy
summary_short: The film, directed by Jemaine Clement and Taika Waititi, is set in New Zealand and follows four ghouls who have problems adapting to the modern world.

headline: Review: ‘Wyrmwood: Road of the Dead’ Puts Zombies in the Outback
summary_short: A mechanic is pitted against the undead in this go-for-broke style film set in an apocalyptic Australian outback.

headline: Review: In ‘White Rabbit,’ a Bullied Teenager Is Pushed to the Edge
summary_short: The director Tim McCann’s drama about a disturbed loner stars Nick Krause, Britt Robertson and Sam Trammell.

headline: Review: In ‘The Rewrite,’ Hugh Grant Is an Author Seeking a Comeback
summary_short: Marc Lawrence’s comedy focuses on a formerly successful screenwriter who takes a teaching job at Binghamton University.

headline: Review: In ‘Kingsman: The Secret Service,’ Colin Firth Get His Suits Splattered
summary_short: There’s a fine cast — including Michael Caine, Mark Strong and Samuel L. Jackson — as well as exploding heads and endangered dogs in Matthew Vaughn’s gory action movie.

headline: Review: ‘Da Sweet Blood of Jesus,’ Spike Lee’s Vampire Movie
summary_short: This remake of Bill Gunn’s “Ganja and Hess” is a stylishly shot, coolly contemplative homage to the original.

headline: Review: ‘Costa da Morte’ Lustrously Depicts Extreme Coastlines
summary_short: The filmmaker Lois Patiño’s subject, the Coast of Death in Galicia, Spain, earned its name from a history of shipwrecks.

headline: Review: In ‘Fifty Shades of Grey’ Movie, Sex Is a Knotty Business
summary_short: The film dabbles in romantic comedy and splashes around in melodrama, but the one thing it can’t be is what E. L. James’s novel was, trashily and triumphantly: pornography.

headline: Cleaning Lady Has No Idea of Her Crucial Role in the Cosmos
summary_short: In “Jupiter Ascending,” Mila Kunis plays an earthling who turns out to be the reconstituted queen of the universe.

display_title: Matt Shepard is a Friend of Mine
headline: Shifting the Spotlight Back to the Man They Knew
summary_short: “Matt Shepard Is a Friend of Mine” seeks to return a human symbol of hate crimes against gay people to a state of ordinary but beloved individuality.

headline: Dreams of Flight, National Pride and Love à la Bollywood
summary_short: “Hawaizaada” wraps itself in a love story, but its main focus is on a pair of aviation pioneers in India who are said to have designed an airplane in 1895, before the Wright brothers.

headline: Losing Her Bearings in Familiar Places
summary_short: In “Still Alice,” Julianne Moore plays a Columbia linguistics professor who receives a devastating diagnosis.

headline: Very Modern Problems Set in a Navajo World
summary_short: “Drunktown’s Finest,” by Sydney Freeland, gives a look into the lives of young Native Americans in New Mexico.

headline: Review: ‘A Space Program’ Adds Whimsy to a Mission to Mars
summary_short: Van Neistat’s film is the record of the artist Tom Sachs’s installation that amused audiences at the Park Avenue Armory in 2012.

headline: Review: ‘L for Leisure,’ Vignettes of Graduate Students on Vacation
summary_short: Set in the early 1990s, this experimental comedy from Lev Kalman and Whitney Horn offers ample opportunities to watch ostensibly smart people behaving stupidly.

headline: Review: In ‘Maya the Bee Movie,’ a Young Dreamer Escapes the Hive Mentality
summary_short: Maya hears nothing but “don’ts” from grown-ups: “Bees don’t dream” and “Bees don’t sing” and “Bees don’t have fun.”

headline: Review: In ‘Cupcakes,’ an Impromptu Cellphone Video Is Noticed
summary_short: Eytan Fox’s dramedy sends six more or less ordinary Israelis to a Paris song competition.

headline: Review: ‘The Barber’ Stars Scott Glenn as a Suspected Serial Killer
summary_short: The film, directed by Basel Owies, finds the son of a police detective searching for a murderer that his father couldn’t convict.

headline: Review: ‘Man From Reno,’ a Mystery of Missing Persons and Priceless Turtles
summary_short: This Japanese film directed by Dave Boyle has an undercurrent of dark comedy as an oddball pair of sleuths (a mystery writer and a sheriff) investigate two disappearances.

headline: Review: In ‘Nightlight,’ Fun and Games in a Forest Turn Deadly
summary_short: In this found-footage horror film, a group of friends playing a variation on hide-and-seek encounter a malevolent spirit.

headline: Review: ‘Home,’ With Rihanna and Jim Parsons
summary_short: Jim Parsons and Rihanna star in this animated film about an intergalactic friendship.

headline: Review: ‘Get Hard,’ With Will Ferrell and Kevin Hart
summary_short: The comic premise of this film could hardly be simpler: Mr. Ferrell is white. Mr. Hart, in contrast, is black.

headline: Review: Bradley Cooper and Jennifer Lawrence Felling Trees in ‘Serena’
summary_short: Logging and love in Appalachia are mingled in this film by the Danish director Susanne Bier, shot in the Czech Republic.

headline: Review: ‘The Kidnapping of Michel Houellebecq’ Blurs Fiction and Reality
summary_short: Inspired by a real disappearance in 2011, this film is an often comically absurd story about a novelist who finds something like happiness after being abducted.

headline: Review: In ‘Zombeavers,’ the Flesheaters Have Overbites
summary_short: The undead chompers are bucktoothed in the cheesy, gory “Zombeavers,” directed by Jordan Rubin.

headline: Review: In ‘Tracers,’ Taylor Lautner Joins a Shady Parkour Gang
summary_short: Part urban crime film, part romantic fantasy, Daniel Benmayor’s film shows love not just for stunts but for the dynamic surfaces of the city.

headline: Review: In ‘The Gunman,’ Sean Penn Plays a Remorseful Sniper on the Run
summary_short: This globe-trotting action thriller is also, in passing, a melodrama of male sexual jealousy, an indictment of Western meddling in Africa and a concussion-awareness public service announcement.

headline: Review: ‘Insurgent’ Brandishes a Tougher Shailene Woodley
summary_short: In the second of the “Divergent” series of dystopic action films, Tris Prior, the lead character, is a more comfortable lock-and-load renegade.

headline: Review: ‘Backcountry,’ a Wilderness Survival Thriller
summary_short: “Backcountry” unfolds in a dense forest where two hapless hikers meet with all manner of terrors.

headline: Review: In ‘It Follows,’ a Shape-Shifting Horror Stalks a Teenager
summary_short: David Robert Mitchell’s second feature film is set in a Detroit suburb, where a deadly menace is passed from one person to another through sex.

headline: Review: In ‘Eva,’ Robot Designer Loves Cute Kid
summary_short: In Kike Maíllo’s Spanish drama, a prodigy returns to his hometown to work on programming an android with the emotional life of a real child.

headline: Review: ‘The Lovers’ Portrays Romances Intertwined Across Time
summary_short: In this film from Roland Joffé, the fortunes of two rings in 1778 India have a ripple effect on a diving mission hundreds of years later.

headline: Review: ‘The Cobbler,’ With Adam Sandler, a World in Others’ Shoes
summary_short: This Tom McCarthy film centers on a shoe repairman who can assume the appearance of his customers by donning their footwear.

headline: Review: In ‘Run All Night,’ Liam Neeson Sticks to What Works
summary_short: In yet another action film, Mr. Neeson plays a longtime underworld enforcer who goes on a killing spree to save his son’s life.

headline: Review: In ‘Cinderella,’ Disney Polishes Its Glass Slippers
summary_short: Much of the fairy tale remains the same in the latest version, but the writer does add some dimensionality to the standard conception of the stepmother.

headline: Review: ‘Champs’ Tyson, Holyfield and Hopkins Recount Careers
summary_short: This documentary by Bert Marcus assesses boxing through three success stories.

headline: Review: In ‘Of Horses and Men,’ the Animals Often Walk on Two Legs
summary_short: The director Benedikt Erlingsson looks at the human-equine relationship in a small, Icelandic community.

headline: Review: Vladan Nikolic’s ‘Allure’ Shows New York Through Immigrants’ Eyes
summary_short: The Occupy movement is a backdrop to this film about four women from different countries and diverse backgrounds and their American experiences.

headline: Review: In ‘Faults,’ Mind Games Don’t End Beyond the Cult
summary_short: This twisty, winningly unsettling feature debut of the director Riley Stearns adds a sometimes darkly comic strain to cult-centric movies.

display_title: The Second Best Exotic Marigold Hotel
headline: Review: ‘The Second Best Exotic Marigold Hotel’ Ups the Ante
summary_short: The director John Madden and the screenwriter Ol Parker hype the pageantry in this sequel to the 2012 hit about Britons recruited to spend their sunset years in Jaipur, India.

headline: Review: ‘The Mafia Kills Only in Summer’ Is a Comical Look at the Mob
summary_short: Pierfrancesco Diliberto plays a virginal klutz whose lifelong brushes with mob misbehavior in Italy parallel his ceaseless yearning for a beautiful woman.

headline: Review: ‘Kidnapping Mr. Heineken’ Revisits a 1983 Dutch Crime
summary_short: Anthony Hopkins is the title character in this uninvolving fictionalized account that plays out as a shopworn tale of greed, stupidity and comeuppance.

headline: Review: In ‘Unfinished Business,’ Vince Vaughn and Sienna Miller Are Rivals
summary_short: The slick, innocuous comedy “Unfinished Business” fails to seal the deal.

headline: Review: In ‘Two Men in Town,’ a Parolee Is Hounded by a Cop
summary_short: Forest Whitaker plays an ex-convict who faces formidable obstacles as he tries to rebuild his life.

headline: Review: ‘Earth’s Golden Playground,’ a Documentary on Prospecting in the Yukon
summary_short: This film removes any luster from prospecting in the Canada territory where the Klondike gold rush took place more than a century ago.

headline: Review: In ‘Chappie,’ a Smart Robot Runs With the Wrong Crowd
summary_short: The latest film from the director of “District 9” and “Elysium” is set in the usual bummer future and wavers uncertainly between laughter and tears.

headline: The Eyes of a Beholder of Hardship
summary_short: “The Salt of the Earth,” a film by Wim Wenders and Juliano Ribeiro Salgado, illustrates the way Sebastião Salgado’s photographs create beauty by capturing pain, violence and deprivation.

headline: Marquise of O..., The (Die Marquise von O...) (Movie)
Review: ‘Childless,’ a Film of Connected Monologues, Stars Joe Mantegna
summary_short: The movie, written and directed by Charlie Levi, follows a group of Angelenos dealing with problems, among them the death of a child.

headline: Review: In ‘Iris,’ Albert Maysles Explores Iris Apfel’s Style
summary_short: Mr. Maysles’s penultimate documentary shows the 93-year-old Ms. Apfel in all her bedecked glory, and the confused reactions she elicits.

display_title: Soul Boys of the Western World
headline: Review: ‘Soul Boys of the Western World’ Revisits Spandau Ballet
summary_short: This documentary chronicles the British band from its beginnings in 1980s London to its later dissolution.

headline: Review: ‘Wa-shoku,’ a Documentary, Recounts How Japanese Dishes Took Hold in the U.S.
summary_short: Through interviews with chefs and others, the documentary “Wa-shoku: Beyond Sushi” explores the growing popularity of Japanese cuisine in American cities.

headline: Review: ‘The Forger’ Stars John Travolta as a Convict and Painter
summary_short: In this film, a prison inmate must fabricate a Monet as part of a shadowy deal to get out of prison early.

headline: Review: ‘The Age of Adaline’ Coasts Through the Decades
summary_short: “The Age of Adaline,” starring Blake Lively, follows the immortal Adaline, who is forever 29.

headline: Review: ‘Little Boy’ is a Fable About Faith Versus Magical Thinking
summary_short: Alejandro Monteverde’s new film is set during World War II.

headline: Review: ‘Laugh Killer Laugh’ Works the Noir Waterfront
summary_short: The hard-boiled protagonist of Kamal Ahmed’s movie works for a mob boss and writes Mickey Spillane-style stories that he knows are more fact than fiction.

headline: Review: In Courteney Cox’s ‘Just Before I Go,’ a Settling of Accounts
summary_short: In this directorial debut, a pet store manager decides to commit suicide, but not before confronting people who hurt him while he was growing up.

headline: Review: ‘Gardeners of Eden’ Tracks the Killing of Elephants for Ivory
summary_short: The film interviews a poacher as well as those trying to save the elephant population in Africa.

headline: Review: A ‘Kung Fu Killer’ Doesn’t Follow the Rules
summary_short: Teddy Chen’s martial arts movie stars Donnie Yen, who faces a furious nemesis played by Wang Baoqiang.

headline: Review: ‘Paul Blart: Mall Cop 2,’ Starring Kevin James, Heads to Las Vegas
summary_short: Mr. James stars in this sequel about a security guard from New Jersey who heads west.

headline: Review: ‘Felix and Meira,’ a Portrait of a Tempted Hasidic Wife
summary_short: Longing to feel alive, a restless young woman is drawn to someone from a different world in this film directed by Maxime Giroux.

headline: Review: ‘Unfriended,’ in the Scariest Ways You Can Think Of
summary_short: A horror movie with a touch of classic Val Lewton, but tailored to your electronic device, partly shot on GoPro and organized into computer windows.

headline: Review: ‘True Story’ Stars Jonah Hill and James Franco
summary_short: Rupert Goold’s film adaptation of a book by the discredited journalist Michael Finkel focuses on his wary friendship with a man charged with murder who had impersonated him.

headline: Review: ‘Tangerines’ Is a Tale of War and Honor
summary_short: Set in the former Soviet Republic of Georgia during the 1992 war in the Abkhazia region, the film has the economy of a short story, unfolding in a mood of slightly sentimental masculine stoicism.

headline: Review: ‘Monkey Kingdom’ Invests a Wild Chimp With Girl Power
summary_short: This Disneynature film examines a band of toque macaque monkeys in Sri Lanka, likening their caste system to a human pecking order.

headline: Review: In ‘The Human Experiment,’ We’re the Unwitting Guinea Pigs
summary_short: This documentary by Don Hardy and Dana Nachman explores the perils of the largely unregulated and potentially dangerous substances we encounter each day.

headline: Review: In ‘Alex of Venice,’ a Career Workaholic Learns to Shoulder Family Burdens
summary_short: Mary Elizabeth Winstead plays a character much like Dustin Hoffman’s in “Kramer vs. Kramer” in Chris Messina’s directorial debut.

headline: Review: In ‘Lost River,’ by Ryan Gosling, Surreal Scenes of Urban Decline
summary_short: Bleak Michigan scenery is the backdrop for a form of horror film that ponders people and places left behind in the name of progress.

headline: Review: In ‘Ex Machina,’ a Mogul Fashions the Droid of His Dreams
summary_short: In Alex Garland’s film, an Internet mogul creates a gorgeous robot named Ava, with unsettling consequences.

headline: Review: In ‘Clouds of Sils Maria,’ a Celebration Turns Into a Memorial
summary_short: “Clouds of Sils Maria,” directed by Olivier Assayas, examines female friendships, female rivalries, tabloid notoriety and the loss of privacy in the Internet age.

headline: Review: ‘Reset,’ an Elliptical Tale of Breaking With the Past
summary_short: “Reset,” an offbeat film written and directed by Paul Bojack, tells the story of a man who repeatedly returns to his hometown with the intention of avoiding anyone he once knew.

headline: Review: ‘Kill Me Three Times,’ and Then Some, Set in a Murderous Surf Town
summary_short: The movie recalls “Pulp Fiction” in its collection of human types and its surreal violence.

headline: Review: In ‘The Longest Ride,’ the Nicholas Sparks Brand Endures
summary_short: A young couple from different worlds find the road to enduring love is paved with complications, some preposterous, some life-threatening.

headline: Review: In ‘Song From the Forest,’ Louis Sarno Links Africa and America
summary_short: A father-son relationship, music and the Bayaka of the Central African Republic are central to this documentary.

headline: Review: ‘Dior and I,’ a Documentary That Peers Into a Storied Fashion House
summary_short: This documentary largely takes place in 2012, when Dior’s legacy is placed in the hands of Raf Simons, who has just eight weeks to produce his first couture collection for the company.

headline: Review: ‘Broken Horses,’ Vidhu Vinod Chopra’s Modern Western
summary_short: Brotherly love and American cowboy-film conventions are interpreted here by an Indian director in an English-language film.

headline: Review: ‘Detective Byomkesh Bakshy!,’ a Calcutta Whodunit
summary_short: The detective, who first appeared in the 1930s in stories by Saradindu Bandyopadhyay, tackles a mystery in a film by Dibakar Banerjee.

headline: Review: ‘Last Knights’ Has Sword Swinging and Cape Twirling in the Name of Revenge
summary_short: This medieval-esque potboiler has a simple code of devotion to one’s master, and mostly involves men, honor, vengeance, dramatic fights and the fantasy of the good death.

headline: Review: ‘Lambert & Stamp’ Recalls the Duo Who Helped Ignite the Who
summary_short: In a mix of archival footage and interviews, this nostalgic documentary portrays an unlikely music-world partnership.

headline: Review: In ‘The Girl Is in Trouble,’ a Pretty Face Masks Danger
summary_short: A modern-day noir starring Columbus Short and Wilmer Valderrama focuses on how the tensions of immigration and gentrification have shaped the Lower East Side.

headline: Review: In ‘Manos Sucias,’ Brothers Reconnect on a Drug Run
summary_short: In this Josef Kubota Wladyka film, two Colombian brothers with a cargo of cocaine reconnect during a trip along the Pacific Coast.

headline: Review: In ‘Furious 7,’ a Franchise Continues to Roar
summary_short: Lots of familiar faces and speed demons are back for the latest in the franchise.

headline: Review: ‘Woman in Gold’ Stars Helen Mirren in Tug of War Over Artwork
summary_short: This drama based on real-life traces the legal battle by Ms. Mirren’s character to regain possession of a priceless canvas stolen from her family by the Nazis 60 years earlier.

headline: Review: In ‘While We’re Young,’ a Coupling of Gen X and Y
summary_short: In Noah Baumbach’s film, Ben Stiller and Naomi Watts play a couple in their 40s who become captivated by a younger pair who seem to freely embrace experience.

headline: Review: Al Pacino in ‘Danny Collins’ Plays a Dissolute Pop Star
summary_short: In Dan Fogelman’s comic drama, a 40-year-old letter from John Lennon could change a jaded older singer’s life.

headline: Review: ‘Dreams Rewired,’ a Futuristic Look at the Past
summary_short: This documentary fuses film clips from the 1880s to the 1930s, illustrating the human response to new technology.

headline: Review: ‘Uncertain Terms’ Enters a Home for Pregnant Young Women
summary_short: In this film by Nathan Silver, an unhappily married handyman is dropped into an emotional maelstrom.

headline: Review: In ‘Survivor,’ a Thriller About Terrorism, Milla Jovovich Is on the Run
summary_short: A security inquiry into visa requests leads to assassination attempts in this film directed by James McTeigue.

headline: Review: ‘Heaven Knows What’ Dramatizes a Young Junkie’s Life
summary_short: Directed by Josh and Benny Safdie, “Heaven Knows What” chronicles an addict and her pursuits on the streets of New York.

headline: Review: ‘Unfreedom,’ a Raj Amit Kumar Tale of Sex, Religion and Tradition
summary_short: Abduction, sexual orientation and violence are at the core of this drama.

headline: Review: ‘The True Cost’ Investigates High Price of Fashion Bargains
summary_short: This documentary by Andrew Morgan details the exploitation of workers in garment factories and cotton fields around the world.

headline: Review: In ‘San Andreas,’ Dwayne Johnson Rushes to Rescue His Collapsing World
summary_short: The big earthquake in this film has its pros and cons: On the one hand, tearing California asunder. On the other, bringing a family together.

headline: Review: ‘Aloha,’ a Hangout Movie With Bradley Cooper and Emma Stone in Hawaii
summary_short: Cameron Crowe’s loose and leisurely film can be enjoyed the way you enjoy a catch-up beer with an old friend you don’t have much in common with anymore.

headline: Review: ‘Tomorrowland,’ Brad Bird’s Lesson in Optimism
summary_short: There is nothing casual or whimsical about this movie’s celebration of hope, imagination and joy.

headline: Review: ‘The Farewell Party’ Finds Laughs in Euthanasia
summary_short: In Tal Granit and Sharon Maymon’s Israeli comedy, set at a Jerusalem retirement home, an amateur inventor devises a “mercy-killing machine.”

headline: Review: ‘Sunshine Superman,’ About the High-Flying Daredevil Carl Boenish
summary_short: This documentary, directed by Marah Strauch, is a bittersweet take on a man who looked at very tall things and saw an opportunity to jump.

headline: Review: ‘Seeds of Time,’ a Documentary on a Crusader for Crop Diversity
summary_short: The urgency of expanding the world’s seed portfolio is made eminently clear in this film directed by Sandy McLeod.

headline: Review: ‘Bombay Velvet’ Is a Bollywood Ode to American Gangster Movies
summary_short: Anurag Kashyap’s movie about an evolving Bombay shows evidence of a changing Indian film scene.

headline: Review: ‘Mad Max: Fury Road,’ Still Angry After All These Years
summary_short: This George Miller film, with Tom Hardy as the hero, has the spirit of a sequel to the original: Speed and efficiency are of the essence, leavened with nasty biker wit and distaste for authority.

headline: Review: ‘Good Kill’ Stars Ethan Hawke Fighting Enemies Half a World Away
summary_short: This Andrew Niccol film is a blunt critique of remote-control warfare, which is transforming the reality of battle into a video game whose casualties are pixels on a screen.

headline: Review: ‘Where Hope Grows,’ a Baseball Career Lost and Relationships Found
summary_short: Chris Dowling’s film begins with a clichéd character, the failed athlete with a drinking problem, and features a young man with Down syndrome in his first acting role.

headline: Review: ‘Pitch Perfect 2,’ With Anna Kendrick and More Fat Amy
summary_short: This sequel pits the Barden Bellas, the all-girl a cappella group, against some highly disciplined German singers, and gives Fat Amy a solo.

headline: Review: ‘Our Man in Tehran’ Recounts Iran Hostage Crisis Escape
summary_short: The tale of how the Canadian ambassador and others helped six American Embassy workers escape Iran in 1980 makes a watchable documentary.

display_title: In the Name of My Daughter
headline: Review: ‘In the Name of My Daughter,’ a Family-Business Scandal
summary_short: This film dramatizes the Affaire Le Roux, a true-crime story about a mother who runs a casino, and the lawyer who manipulates her daughter to take control of it.

headline: Review: In ‘The Film Critic,’ a Snob Is Tripped Up by His Heartstrings
summary_short: The Argentine director Hernán Guerschuny skewers the pretensions of movie criticism in this film, starring Rafael Spregelburd.

headline: Review: In ‘Know How,’ Teenagers Portray Their Plight in Foster Care
summary_short: The film presents stories drawn from the life experiences of its fledgling actors.

display_title: I'll See You In My Dreams
headline: Review: In ‘I’ll See You in My Dreams,’ Blythe Danner Seeks Fulfillment
summary_short: Ms. Danner plays a former singer who, with the help of colorful friends, strikes out in search of possible male companionship.

headline: Review: In ‘Animals,’ a Couple in Love With Heroin
summary_short: A college-educated, middle-class couple create a self-contained civilization in which heroin is a powerful force within their personal love story.

headline: Review: With ‘One Cut, One Life,’ Ed Pincus and Lucia Small Document His Illness
summary_short: In his final years, the documentary pioneer Ed Pincus joined with the filmmaker Lucia Small, to record his medical struggles and their own collaboration.

display_title: The 100-Year-Old Man Who Climbed Out the Window and Disappeared
headline: Review: ‘The 100-Year-Old Man Who Climbed Out the Window and Disappeared’
summary_short: This often droll Swedish movie is a new entry in the genre that might be called Old People Behaving Hilariously.

headline: Review: ‘The Seven Five,’ a Documentary About a Corrupt New York Cop
summary_short: Tiller Russell’s documentary focuses on Michael Dowd, a Brooklyn police officer who in the late 1980s was earning $4,000 a week from illegal dealings with drug organizations.

headline: Review: ‘Preggoland.’ It’s a Nice Place to Visit. Sort Of.
summary_short: Jacob Tierney’s comedy focuses on a single, childless and irresponsible woman who pretends to be pregnant after a mistaken assumption.

headline: Review: ‘Playing It Cool,’ with Chris Evans
summary_short: Cut loose from the flash-bang-wallop of the “Captain America” and “Avengers” franchises, Chris Evans seems lost.

headline: Review: ‘Noble,’ the Crusade of a Children’s Rights Activist
summary_short: The film follows Christina Noble, who emerged from a traumatic childhood in Dublin to build a foundation that helps thousands of children in Vietnam and Mongolia.

headline: Review: In ‘The D Train,’ Jack Black and James Marsden in a Steamy Bromance
summary_short: In this bromantic comedy, Mr. Black’s character wants Mr. Marsden’s to attend their high school reunion, but he gets a great deal more.

headline: Review: In ‘Piku,’ Amitabh Bachchan Plays a Dad to Deepika Padukone
summary_short: A young career woman and her demanding, aging father bicker at home and on the road in this Hindi film directed by Shoojit Sircar.

headline: Review: In ‘Hot Pursuit,’ Sofia Vergara and Reese Witherspoon on the Run
summary_short: The women, one the wife of a criminal and the other a police officer, are thrown together by improbable circumstances in this buddy comedy.

headline: Review: In ‘Bravetown,’ a Bad Boy Redeems Himself Through D.J. Magic
summary_short: The film is part high school dance competition movie and part shameless flag-waver.

headline: Review: In ‘5 Flights Up,’ a Marriage of Morgan Freeman and Diane Keaton
summary_short: Mr. Freeman and Ms. Keaton play a Brooklyn couple who need to sell their fifth-floor walk-up. They find that in New York, real estate isn’t easy.

headline: Review: Kristen Wiig as a Troubled Lottery Winner in ‘Welcome to Me’
summary_short: Ms. Wiig’s character decides to spend a major financial windfall on buying her own talk show in this dark comedy directed by Shira Piven.

headline: Review: In ‘Ride,’ Helen Hunt Goes Surfing
summary_short: Directed and written by Ms. Hunt, this movie follows a high-strung New Yorker editor as she tracks down her son on the West Coast.

headline: Review: In ‘Hyena,’ a Rogue Cop Finds Himself in Too Deep
summary_short: As kingpins do battle in London in Gerald Johnson’s drama, there’s plenty of human trafficking, drug smuggling and viscera.

headline: Review: ‘Far From the Madding Crowd,’ the Rom-Com
summary_short: Carey Mulligan stars in Thomas Vinterberg’s adaptation of the Thomas Hardy novel, with Matthias Schoenaerts, Tom Sturridge and Michael Sheen as her Victorian suitors.

headline: Review: ‘Cas & Dylan,’ a Road Movie Starring Richard Dreyfuss
summary_short: The film follows a pair of mismatched travelers heading across Canada.

headline: Review: ‘Avengers: Age of Ultron’ Gets the Superband Back Together
summary_short: The new installment in the “Avengers” franchise adds characters, including the Scarlet Witch and Quicksilver, even as its familiar heroes fight battles terrestrial and galactic.

headline: ‘Days of Grace,’ a Mexican Film by Everardo Gout
summary_short: The film uses three plotlines that take place during successive World Cups, in 2002, 2006 and 2010.

headline: Review: ‘Creep,’ a Horror Film With the Look of Found Footage
summary_short: The actor and director Mark Duplass stars as a man seeking to leave a legacy for his unborn child.

headline: Review: In ‘A Little Chaos,’ a Guileless Kate Winslet Offsets a Lavish Versailles
summary_short: Ms. Winslet plays a gardener well ahead of her time in this Louis XIV-era costume drama directed by and starring Alan Rickman.

headline: Review: ‘Fresh Dressed’ Follows Hip-Hop From the Streets to the Runway
summary_short: This documentary charts how hip-hop fashion initially absorbed what was around it, and then eventually became the inspiration for everyone else.

headline: Review: ‘Big Game’ Stars Samuel L. Jackson as a President in Dire Straits
summary_short: In this adventure, a Scandinavian teenager encounters the American president, who has bailed out of a doomed Air Force One over the Finnish woods.

headline: Review: ‘The Midnight Swim’ Investigates a Mother’s Watery Death
summary_short: Sarah Adina Smith’s chiller about three sisters at a lakeside home has one foot in its genre and one in a whole other place.

headline: Review: ‘The Little Death’ Plays With Narrative Form and Fetish
summary_short: Josh Lawson’s polite sex comedy has the soul of a sitcom.

headline: Review: Noah Buschel’s ‘Glass Chin,’ an Updated Working-Class Noir
summary_short: This story of a New York-area loan shark, restaurateur and boxing coach is full of hyperstylized shots, philosophizing speeches and no-way-out plotting.

headline: Review: In ‘Ted 2,’ the Foulmouthed Bear Tries to Prove He’s Human
summary_short: In a quest to be a husband and father, the character voiced by Seth MacFarlane aligns his struggle with that of enslaved black Americans.

headline: Review: In ‘Runoff,’ a Rural Family Hits Desperate Times
summary_short: Kimberly Levin’s directorial debut centers on the Freemans (Neal Huff and Joanne Kelly), struggling to raise a family and save their farm and business.

headline: Review: In ‘Max,’ a Shellshocked Dog Reverts to His Heroic Self
summary_short: Boaz Yakin’s film, a blend of detective story and animal tale, depicts the healing of a slain marine’s military dog under the care of the man’s brother.

display_title: Batkid Begins: The Wish Heard Around the World
headline: Review: In ‘Batkid Begins’, a Boy’s Simple Wish Whips Up Frenzied Adulation
summary_short: Dana Nachman documents the overwhelming response to a 5-year-old cancer patient’s wish to become Batman.

headline: Review: In ‘7 Minutes,’ From Jay Martin, a Bank Robbery Plan Implodes
summary_short: Three friends decide to commit a crime, greatly underestimating the difficulty.

headline: Review: ‘Escobar: Paradise Lost’ Stars Benicio Del Toro as Drug Lord
summary_short: In this fictional account of the Colombian kingpin, Pablo Escobar pulls an American surfer into his circle.

headline: Review: ‘What Happened, Miss Simone?’ Documents Nina Simone’s Rise as Singer and Activist
summary_short: This documentary, directed by Liz Garbus, chronicles the life of Nina Simone, the singer-musician whose social circle and civil rights activism grew along with her fame.

headline: Review: Pixar’s ‘Inside Out’ Finds the Joy in Sadness, and Vice Versa
summary_short: Pete Docter’s new animated film, with the voices of television comedians like Amy Poehler, Mindy Kaling and Bill Hader, brings to life an 11-year-old’s interior drama.

headline: Review: ‘Phantom Halo,’ a Crime Caper With Thomas Brodie-Sangster
summary_short: Rebecca Romijn and Luke Kleintank are also in the cast of this drama, which focuses on the sons of a dissolute father.

headline: Review: ‘Eden,’ a D.J.’s Passion for Electronic Music, by Mia Hansen-Love
summary_short: The film chronicles the electronic music scene in 1990s Paris, from boom to burnout.

headline: Review: ‘Balls Out,’ a Sports-Movie Satire Packed With ‘S.N.L.’ Talent
summary_short: “This isn’t about winning,” says the coach of the motley intramural football team at the center of this comedy. “It’s about winning at the last possible second.”

headline: Review: ‘The Face of an Angel’ Dabbles in Murder and Culpability
summary_short: The death of Meredith Kercher, a British student, in Italy preoccupied the news media and the public. This film by Michael Winterbottom is a fictional take on the event.

headline: Review: In ‘The Overnight,’ Newcomers Try Hard to Make Friends
summary_short: Bland meets bold in “The Overnight,” a comedy that coyly dips its toe and a few other body parts in the new sexual revolution.

headline: Review: ‘Infinitely Polar Bear’ Traces a Dad’s Ups and Downs
summary_short: This debut feature from the writer-director Maya Forbes concerns a family whose father (Mark Ruffalo) has manic depression, as seen by his young daughter.

display_title: Hippocrates: Diary of a French Doctor
headline: Review: ‘Hippocrates’ Offers Life, Death and Teachable Moments
summary_short: This film, subtitled “Diary of a French Doctor,” unfolds pretty much like an average episode of “ER,” though with more French flag waving and less storeroom romancing.

headline: Review: ‘Gabriel’ Stars Rory Culkin as a Young Man With Mental Illness
summary_short: An obsessive and troubled Gabriel leaves a psychiatric hospital and strains the lives of his loving mother and childhood girlfriend in this tense film.

headline: Review: ‘Burying the Ex,’ a Joe Dante Zombie Tale
summary_short: A looming breakup doesn’t go as planned in the first feature in six years from the director of the “Gremlins” movies and “The ’Burbs.”

headline: Review: ‘ABCD 2,’ TV Dance Stars Try to Rebuild Their Team and Reputation
summary_short: The leader of the Mumbai Stunners troupe hopes to turn around the group’s fortunes in this Remo D’Souza Bollywood sequel.

headline: Review: ‘Dope,’ a Teenage Comedy, Plays With Stereotypes
summary_short: In Rick Famuyiwa’s film, Malcolm, a smart student and musician prepping for a Harvard interview, does a favor for a drug dealer and winds up with a gun and a backpack of contraband.

headline: Review: ‘Hamari Adhuri Kahani’ Tours a Bad Marriage and the Jungle
summary_short: Mohit Suri’s melodramatic film finds time amid its globe-trotting adventure to comment on domestic abuse in India.

headline: Review: In ‘The Yes Men Are Revolting,’ Prankster Activists Take On Climate Change
summary_short: The third documentary follows this comic duo through some personal struggles as they train their sights on global warming.

headline: Review: ‘Set Fire to the Stars’ Unleashes Dylan Thomas on America
summary_short: The film follows the poet to the United States in an era when the romantic notion that drunkenness was a shortcut to enlightenment held sway.

headline: Review: ‘Madame Bovary’ Features Mia Wasikowska as a Notorious Adulteress
summary_short: This costume-drama adaptation of Flaubert’s “Madame Bovary” stays true to the plot.

headline: Review: ‘Live From New York!’ Celebrates 40 Years of ‘Saturday Night Live’
summary_short: This documentary, directed by Bao Nguyen and part of the Tribeca Film Festival, chronicles that TV comedy show as a cultural institution but fails to explore its inner workings.

headline: Review: In ‘The 11th Hour,’ Fertility Anxiety Gets Thriller Treatment
summary_short: A woman desperate to be a mother and a heroin-addicted dwarf journey to Eastern Europe for a baby.

headline: Review: In ‘Jurassic World,’ the Franchise Feeds the Beast
summary_short: The latest installment of the Jurassic franchise, set in a luxury resort, reminds you what a great action god Steven Spielberg is.

headline: Review: ‘An Open Secret’ Spotlights Child Sexual Abuse in Hollywood
summary_short: In this documentary, directed by Amy Berg, former child actors recount the manipulations, cover-ups and exploitations they encountered in the entertainment industry.

headline: Review: ‘Love & Mercy’ Gets Inside Brian Wilson’s Head
summary_short: In Bill Pohlad’s Beach Boys biopic, Paul Dano plays Mr. Wilson in the 1960s, making “Pet Sounds,” and John Cusack plays him in the 1980s, making peace.

headline: Review: ‘Insidious: Chapter 3’ Keeps a Franchise Rolling
summary_short: In this prequel to the original movie, directed by Leigh Whannell, a teenager enlists ghost hunters to try to connect with her dead mother.

headline: Review: ‘Wild Horses,’ a Film by and Starring Robert Duvall
summary_short: This melodrama, Mr. Duvall’s first directorial effort since “Assassination Tango” in 2003, also stars James Franco and Josh Hartnett.

headline: Review: ‘The Nightmare,’ Rodney Ascher’s Look at Sleep Paralysis
summary_short: Mr. Ascher uses re-enactments to help tell the stories of eight people with this disorder.

headline: Review: In ‘Spy,’ Melissa McCarthy Is a C.I.A. Drudge Who Goes Rogue
summary_short: Ms. McCarthy leads a starry cast in this action-comedy about an intelligence officer who proves her mettle in heroic and ridiculous ways.

headline: Review: In ‘Patch Town,’ Animated Toys Work the Factory Line
summary_short: The director Craig Goodwill’s musical fairy tale, inspired by Eastern European folklore, features vivified toys that revolt against an unscrupulous corporate overlord.

headline: Review: ‘Freedom’ Stars Cuba Gooding Jr. as a Slave Fleeing to Canada
summary_short: Peter Cousens’s film follows two narratives: one set in Virginia and points north in 1856, the other on a trans-Atlantic slave ship in 1748.

headline: Review: ‘Doomsdays,’ a Jaunt Into Strangers’ Homes in the Catskills
summary_short: Two vagabonds go on a Catskills adventure in this film from Eddie Mullins.

headline: Review: ‘Every Last Child,’ a Front-Line View of the Polio Crisis in Pakistan
summary_short: Tom Roberts’s documentary examines the struggles of health workers in Pakistan to vaccinate children against polio in the face of mistrust and Taliban attacks.

headline: Review: ‘Entourage,’ the Screen Is Bigger, but Nothing Is Better
summary_short: By the time the show reached the end of its HBO run in 2011, it had grown staler than last night’s Axe body spray. The passing of a few more years has not improved the aroma.

headline: Review: In ‘Antarctic Edge,’ a Region of Retreating Ice
summary_short: This documentary about a scarcely charted place underlines the sheer labor of exploration and the global dangers posed by shrinking sea ice.

headline: Review: ‘Bonobos: Back to the Wild,’ a Sanctuary’s Rehab Mission
summary_short: This docudrama looks at the efforts of a conservationist named Claudine André, who runs a bonobo sanctuary in the Democratic Republic of Congo.

headline: Review: ‘Two Step’ Scuffles Around With Petty Criminals
summary_short: Alex R. Johnson’s feature-length debut is a nasty, well-acted little gem that goes deep inside its characters’ psyches.

headline: Review: ‘Wild City’ Follows Two (Very) Good Samaritans in Hong Kong
summary_short: This movie, directed by Ringo Lam, features a former cop and his cab-driving stepbrother who take extravagant risks in protecting a woman from triad gangsters.

headline: Review: ‘Paulo Coelho’s Best Story’ Hopscotches Through an Author’s Career
summary_short: This Brazilian film depicts Mr. Coelho’s rebellious youth, setbacks, grand adventures and literary success.

headline: Review: ‘Mission: Impossible — Rogue Nation’ With Tom Cruise and Plenty of Stunts
summary_short: For the fifth “Mission: Impossible” movie, Mr. Cruise is joined by, among others, Jeremy Renner, Ving Rhames, Simon Pegg and Rebecca Ferguson.

headline: Review: ‘Jenny’s Wedding,’ a Lecture on Tolerance
summary_short: This movie, directed by Mary Agnes Donoghue and starring Katherine Heigl as a closeted lesbian, is about secrets, lies and bigotry.

headline: Review: In ‘That Sugar Film,’ a Bitter Truth
summary_short: For this documentary, the director and actor Damon Gameau subjects himself to a high sugar diet, by way of juice, yogurt and cereal.

headline: Review: In ‘Dark Awakening,’ a Haunted House and Surfeit of Gore
summary_short: Dean C. Jones’s film depicts a small-town prosecutor who moves with his family into his deceased mother’s house, only to be pestered by its spectral residents.

headline: Review: In ‘A Lego Brickumentary,’ Master Builders Working and Playing
summary_short: A movie explores the uses, from artistic to therapeutic, of a ubiquitous toy.

headline: Review: ‘I Am Chris Farley,’ a Brief Life, Lived for Laughs
summary_short: In this documentary about the comedian, colleagues recall Mr. Farley’s exuberantly physical humor and invented characters, including the motivational speaker who lived “in a van down by the river.”

headline: Review: ‘Counting,’ a Meditation in Story Shards
summary_short: Jem Cohen turns out to be a type of space-age traveler, if one who’s crossing cinematic time.

headline: Review: ‘Best of Enemies’ Recalls Gore Vidal and William F. Buckley Jr.’s TV Battles
summary_short: This documentary from Robert Gordon and Morgan Neville mines the Buckley-Vidal skirmishes around the 1968 political conventions for nuggets of historical insight.

headline: Review: In ‘Vacation,’ Christina Applegate and Ed Helms Travel to Walley World
summary_short: This comedy about a family’s theme park journey is a sequel to “National Lampoon’s Vacation,” the 1983 Chevy Chase film.

headline: Review: ‘Listen to Me Marlon’ Explores Brando’s Life of Contention
summary_short: The documentary “Listen to Me Marlon,” directed by Stevan Riley, draws on audio recordings in which the actor talked about his life and career.

headline: Review: ‘Unexpected,’ a Tale of 2 Pregnancies That Unite and Divide
summary_short: Kris Swanberg’s film depicts a Chicago schoolteacher who discovers that she is pregnant just as one of her top students does, and peppers her protégée with advice.

headline: Review: ‘The Young Kieslowski’ Is a Sobering Comedy of Consequences
summary_short: Two college students, a first sexual encounter and one pregnancy — with twins — in this uncomfortable comedy.

headline: Review: ‘The Outrageous Sophie Tucker’ Recalls a Jazz Powerhouse
summary_short: This documentary details the life and career of Tucker, a hobnobbing 20th-century jazz singer known for her big voice.

headline: Review: ‘Phoenix’ Shows Rebirth and a Ruse in Postwar Germany
summary_short: Never less than intriguing, coolly intelligent and flawlessly paced, “Phoenix” often feels trapped in the logic of its conceit.

headline: Review: ‘Paper Towns’ Tries to Fold Significance Into the Everyday
summary_short: A story about boy meets girl, girl forgets boy, girl returns to boy, based on a book by John Green, author of “The Fault in Our Stars.”

headline: Review: ‘Lucky Stiff,’ Still Farcical, Returns as a Movie
summary_short: An update of the play that opened Off Broadway in 1988, this film is about a shoe salesman who learns that an uncle he never met has left him a large inheritance.

headline: Review: In ‘Southpaw,’ Jake Gyllenhaal Tries to Box His Way Back From Tragedy
summary_short: Antoine Fuqua’s ode to boxing also stars Forest Whitaker as a tenacious trainer and Rachel McAdams as a loving tough-cookie wife.

headline: Review: In ‘Pixels,’ Attack of the Retro Video Games
summary_short: Adam Sandler fights Pac-Man (yes, that beloved character is a “bad guy”) to save the country.

headline: Review: ‘Frank the Bastard,’ a Trip Back to Old Crimes at the Commune
summary_short: Hidden and traumatic histories and multiple intrigues and motivations populate this diffuse melodrama, set in a rustic Maine town.

headline: Review: ‘Dark Was the Night’ Confronts a Demon in the Woods
summary_short: The director Jack Heller’s horror film draws its talent from television: Kevin Durand, Lukas Haas and Bianca Kajlich.

headline: Review: ‘Big Significant Things’ Compares Landmarks in Life and on the Road
summary_short: In this film, Harry Lloyd plays a character who runs from commitment in search of highway novelties.

headline: Review: ‘Trainwreck’ Delivers the Full Amy Schumer Experience
summary_short: The movie, directed by Judd Apatow from Ms. Schumer’s script, is a romantic comedy packed with pop-cultural references and edged with social critique.

headline: Review: ‘The Stanford Prison Experiment’ Revisits the Psychology of Power and Abuse
summary_short: The film is about the notorious 1971 psychological study in which students were recruited to play either guards or inmates in a make-believe prison.

headline: Review: ‘The Look of Silence’ Confronts Individuals and Ideology of Indonesian Massacre
summary_short: This documentary by the American filmmaker Joshua Oppenheimer, like its companion film, “The Act of Killing,” examines the mass killings that began in the country in 1965.

headline: Review: In ‘Twinsters,’ Separated-at-Birth Twins Tell Their Own Story
summary_short: This film, which one of the twins helped direct, uses Facebook and Skype communication as a narrative device.

headline: Review: In ‘Northern Limit Line,’ the Koreas Do Battle
summary_short: The writer and director Kim Hak-soon seeks to dramatize a real 2002 clash near a disputed maritime border.

headline: Review: In ‘Lila and Eve,’ a Grieving Mother Turns Gun-Toting Vigilante
summary_short: Viola Davis and Jennifer Lopez star in this revenge thriller, directed by Charles Stone III (“Drumline”).

headline: Review: For Ian McKellen’s ‘Mr. Holmes,’ Retirement Is Afoot
summary_short: “Mr. Holmes” imagines the later years of Arthur Conan Doyle’s beloved detective, who hasn’t quite given up making brilliant deductions.

headline: Review: ‘Famous Nathan’ Tells How Nathan Handwerker Built a Hot Dog Empire
summary_short: Mr. Handwerker’s grandson Lloyd uses interviews and archival footage to chronicle the driving force behind Nathan’s Famous.

headline: Review: ‘Ant-Man,’ With Paul Rudd, Adds to a Superhero Infestation
summary_short: Directed by Peyton Reed, this movie is a passable piece of drone work from the ever-expanding Marvel-Disney colony.

headline: Review: ‘Tangerine,’ a Madcap Buddy Picture About Transgender Prostitutes
summary_short: Sean Baker’s fast, funny comedy, shot on iPhones, doesn’t dive deep into transgender identity but shows that femininity is a mask that can be slipped on and off.

display_title: What We Did On Our Holiday
headline: Review: ‘What We Did on Our Holiday’ Transfers Sitcom Formula to the Big Screen
summary_short: David Tennant and Rosamund Pike star as squabbling parents in this family movie directed by the team from the BBC sitcom “Outnumbered.”

headline: Review: ‘The Gallows’ Somehow Finds More Horror Footage
summary_short: This movie about high school students trapped in a seemingly haunted auditorium has plenty of rickety camerawork, but that doesn’t add to the scariness.

headline: Review: ‘Tap World’ Documentary Features a Variety of Quick-Stepping Dancers
summary_short: Dean Hargrove’s film focuses on an assortment of tap dancers proclaiming their love for the art, although it is light on the nuts and bolts of the discipline.

headline: Review: ‘Stations of the Cross,’ a Portrait of Religious Fervor
summary_short: This movie by the German director Dietrich Brüggemann can be viewed three ways: as a critique, a spiritual work or a sly comedy.

headline: Review: ‘SlingShot’ Documentary Pitches Solution to Global Water Crisis
summary_short: The inventor of the water purifier, Dean Kamen, thinks his device can bring fresh water to the world.

headline: Review: Robin Williams as a Hustler-Hiring Husband in ‘Boulevard’
summary_short: Mr. Williams plays a 60-year-old bank officer in a passionless marriage whose life is shaken up by the company of a male hustler.

headline: Review: Positions Wanted by Minions Experienced at Serving Evildoers
summary_short: Those look-alike yellow guys become miserable when they have no one to help, albeit incompetently, in the first movie that’s all about them.

headline: Review: ‘Meet Me in Montenegro,’ Romance for Ex-Lovers
summary_short: The directors Linnea Saasen and Alex Holdridge both wrote and starred in this film, which is a semi-autobiographical love story of their own lives.

headline: Review: In ‘Strangerland,’ Relocating Does Little to Ease a Family’s Strains
summary_short: This fiction feature debut from Kim Farrant centers on a family of new arrivals in an Australian desert town, which is soon clouded by mystery and a dust storm.

headline: Review: In ‘Self/less,’ Immortality at a Cost
summary_short: Ben Kingsley plays a terminally ill real estate magnate who pays a lot of money to have his consciousness uploaded into Ryan Reynolds’s body.

headline: Review: In ‘Mad Women,’ a Small-Town Political Family With Issues
summary_short: Characters in Jeff Lipsky’s dramedy include a mother running for mayor, a father facing a rape charge and a daughter trying to help her mother manage.

headline: Review: In ‘10.000 km,’ Lovers an Ocean Apart Struggle to Connect
summary_short: Carlos Marques-Marcet’s film about a couple’s shift to a long-distance relationship looks at the role technology plays in negotiating absence.

headline: Review: ‘Amy,’ an Intimate Diary of Amy Winehouse’s Rise and Destruction
summary_short: Asif Kapadia’s documentary is a harrowing look at the singer’s life that drives home the costs of celebrity and fandom.

headline: Review: In ‘Jackie & Ryan,’ a Handsome Drifter Guides the Way
summary_short: Ami Canaan Mann’s film portrays a romance between a singer who fled her marriage for her hometown in Utah and an itinerant musician who arrives there on the back of a freight train.

headline: Review: In ‘Cartel Land’ Documentary, Vigilantes Wage Drug Wars
summary_short: Matthew Heineman’s on-the-ground film profiles leaders of two vigilante groups fighting drug gangs, one in Arizona and the other in Michoacán, Mexico.

headline: Review: ‘Magic Mike XXL,’ Fleshing Out a Sequel With Heart as Well as Pecs and Abs
summary_short: Channing Tatum returns in this comedy, which transports the audience to a world of sexual intrigue that feels as safe and wholesome as a child’s birthday party.

headline: Review: In ‘Terminator Genisys,’ Ageless Cyborgs and a Deathless Franchise
summary_short: Arnold Schwarzenegger returns, it’s 1984 again, and Sarah Connor is at risk once more.

headline: Review: ‘Mala Mala’ Shares Experiences of Being Transgender in Puerto Rico
summary_short: The directors of this documentary, Dan Sickles and Antonio Santini, interview prostitutes, drag queens, small-business owners and activists about their transitions and relationships.

display_title: Me and Earl and the Dying Girl
headline: Review: In ‘Me and Earl and the Dying Girl,’ a Comfort Zone That Cannot Last
summary_short: Adapted from the young-adult novel, the movie centers on a teenage auteur, his filmmaking colleague and “the dying girl,” who balks at sentimentality.

headline: Review: In ‘The Looking Glass,’ an Aging Actress Mentors a Troubled Granddaughter
summary_short: Two generations try to connect in this film, starring Dorothy Tristan, who also wrote the film, and is directed by her husband, John Hancock.

headline: Review: ‘The Moving Creatures,’ Three Tales of Family Ordeals
summary_short: Written and directed by Caetano Gotardo, this three-part movie about Brazilian families is a chilling reminder that a simple life is no shield against the disastrous.

headline: Review: ‘My Voice, My Life,’ a Story of Hong Kong Student Actors
summary_short: This documentary from Ruby Yang, about students who are not the expected high achievers, captures the feeling of spreading one’s wings onstage for the first time.

headline: Review: In ‘Z for Zachariah,’ an End-of-Days Love Triangle
summary_short: Margot Robbie stars in Craig Zobel’s post-apocalyptic film about three survivors of the nuclear holocaust caught in a triangle.

headline: Review: ‘Zipper’ Stars Patrick Wilson as a Sex Addict
summary_short: The film, directed by Mora Stephens, finds a straight-arrow prosecutor with an out-of-control libido.

headline: Review: Korean Warriors Seek Vengeance in ‘Memories of the Sword’
summary_short: Park Heung-sik’s martial-arts spectacle is set during the Goreyo era in Korea’s history.

headline: Review: ‘I Touched All Your Stuff,’ a Documentary About a Technician’s Story
summary_short: An American computer technician serving time in a Brazilian jail recounts his ill-fated obsession with a mysterious femme fatale who may or may not exist.

headline: Review: In ‘Unsullied,’ a Competitive Racer Must Run for Her Life
summary_short: Directed by the former N.F.L. defensive end Simeon Rice, this lurid low-budget thriller recalls 1970s exploitation revenge pictures.

headline: Review: In ‘The Second Mother,’ a Guest Flouts Boundaries
summary_short: In Anna Muylaert’s Brazilian drama, the maid’s teenage daughter comes to visit and doesn’t seem to care for a lot of the rules.

headline: Review: ‘Fever,’ a French Tale of High School Homicide and Consequences
summary_short: Raphael Neal’s drama explores a murder committed by two high school seniors in Paris and their subsequent moral struggles.

headline: Review: In ‘We Are Your Friends,’ Angelenos Long for Life Beyond the Valley
summary_short: Zac Efron plays a D.J. under the wing of a dissolute mentor (Wes Bentley) in Max Joseph’s debut feature.

headline: Review: ‘No Escape,’ Starring Owen Wilson as a Man in the Cross Hairs
summary_short: An American businessman and his family are trapped in the middle of a gruesome uprising in a Southeast Asian country.

headline: Review: ‘The Iron Ministry’ Uses Train Passengers to Tell China’s Story
summary_short: J. P. Sniadecki spent nearly three years filming this documentary on the trains that carry tens of millions across the nation each year.

headline: Review: ‘Learning to Drive’ Charts a Culture-Bridging Friendship
summary_short: This grown-up drama stars Patricia Clarkson as a New York book critic, and Ben Kingsley as her Indian-American driving instructor.

headline: Review: In ‘Youth,’ Strains of Family and Country Fall on Brothers’ Shoulders
summary_short: Crude fantasy seems to merge with the daily reality of a militarized society as brothers try to save their family from financial ruin in this Tom Shoval film.

headline: Review: In ‘Guidance,’ a High School Counselor as a Rotten Role Model
summary_short: Pat Mills wrote, directed and stars in this black comedy about a former child star who fraudulently gets a job of giving advice to teenagers.

display_title: Searching For Home: Coming Back From War
headline: ‘Searching for Home,’ a Cross-Generational Look at Military Veterans
summary_short: Eric Christiansen’s documentary explores the struggles of veterans who returned home from World War II and succeeding conflicts, from the wars in Korea and Vietnam to those in Iraq and Afghanistan.

headline: Review: ‘Some Kind of Beautiful’ Stars Pierce Brosnan as a Serial Seducer
summary_short: Mr. Brosnan plays a womanizing college professor who impregnates a student (Jessica Alba) and then connects with her sister (Salma Hayek) after she dumps him.

headline: Review: ‘She’s Funny That Way’ Offers Tomfoolery Amid the Floodlights
summary_short: Peter Bogdanovich’s first feature in more than a dozen years is a screwball comedy centered on a Broadway director and his circle.

headline: Review: Rupert Friend and Zachary Quinto in a Pas de Bullets, ‘Hitman: Agent 47’
summary_short: In Aleksander Bach’s revival of a franchise based on a video game, Mr. Friend plays the genetically engineered assassin-hero.

headline: Review: In ‘Sinister 2,’ a Murderous Being Returns for More Mayhem
summary_short: In this horror sequel, a woman takes refuge in a rural home with her twin sons, who are then manipulated by evil.

headline: Review: In ‘American Ultra,’ Jesse Eisenberg Is a Stoner and a Target
summary_short: Kristen Stewart and Mr. Eisenberg pair up again in this film, an action adventure with C.I.A. trouble and occasional laughs.

headline: Review: Hapless Brothers and Their Lovers Intersect in ‘The Mend’
summary_short: Two brothers contend with girlfriends past and present in John Magary’s character-driven study of masculinity.

headline: Review: ‘Digging for Fire,’ a Comedy by Joe Swanberg
summary_short: While taking care of a client’s home, a couple whose marriage is already strained takes some time apart.

headline: Review: A Despairing Librarian Is Ready to Check Out in ‘After Words’
summary_short: Romance is the last thing on the mind of Marcia Gay Harden’s character when she begins a tour of Costa Rica with a personal guide.

headline: Review: In ‘Slow Learners,’ Aspirational Hedonists Doff Their Glasses
summary_short: This comedy stars Adam Pally and Sarah Burns as awkward schoolteachers who resolve to live on the wild side over summer break.

headline: Review: ‘Brothers ... Blood Against Blood,’ Set in the Mean Streets of Mumbai
summary_short: This Bollywood movie, directed by Karan Malhotra, is dense with back story about two siblings who train for a mixed martial arts tournament.

headline: Review: ‘We Come as Friends’ Explores Potential Exploitation of South Sudan
summary_short: Hubert Sauper’s documentary blends striking visuals with a pointed argument that outside investors seeking profits played a big role in the region’s independence movement.

headline: Review: ‘Ten Thousand Saints,’ a Coming of Age in the East Village, Circa 1980s
summary_short: A troubled Vermont teenager is sent to live with his estranged father in New York and finds himself there during a defining cultural moment.

headline: Review: ‘Rosenwald,’ on a Philanthropist Who Created Schools for Blacks in the Jim Crow South
summary_short: Aviva Kempner’s documentary offers a stirring portrait of a Sears executive whose Rosenwald Fund dispensed fellowships to black artists and academics including W. E. B. Du Bois and James Baldwin.

headline: Review: ‘Mistress America,’ a Noah Baumbach Comedy on Getting By in a Backbiting World
summary_short: This smart, fast-paced film, advertised as a screwball comedy, subverts this most buoyant of genres with a steady undertow of anxiety, dread and anger.

headline: Review: ‘Meru’ Follows an Expedition Up Shark’s Fin Peak in the Himalayas
summary_short: This film about mountain climbers pokes at the psychology of extremity, zeroing in on push-the-limits personalities for whom calculating risk is a way of life.

headline: Review: In ‘Tom at the Farm,’ Psychosexual Games Down at the Farm
summary_short: Xavier Dolan directs and stars in this film about a bereaved lover who discovers that his boyfriend’s family had no idea that he had a gay companion.

headline: Review: ‘Fort Tilden,’ a Comic Odyssey to the Beach
summary_short: Two self-centered young women from New York embark on a picaresque bike ride and encounter all sorts of complications.

headline: Review: ‘The Man From U.N.C.L.E.’ Resurrects a Glossy, Action-Packed ’60s
summary_short: Guy Ritchie’s big-screen rendering of the 1960s television series tries hard not to be a museum piece, partly with a slick, agitated style.

headline: Review: In ‘Return to Sender,’ Rosamund Pike Connects With Her Attacker
summary_short: A rapist’s victim visits him in prison, raising the question of whether she’s interested in his rehabilitation or something else.

headline: Review: In ‘People Places Things,’ Jemaine Clement Navigates Life as a Newly Single Dad
summary_short: In Jim Strouse’s comedy, Mr. Clement plays a graphic artist, teacher and father who must start over after his wife betrays him.

headline: Review: In ‘Big Sky,’ Starring Bella Thorne, Mortal Fears Collide
summary_short: Ms. Thorne plays a teenager with a dread of open spaces who must surmount her terror to save her mother and herself.

headline: Review: In ‘Air,’ Norman Reedus and Djimon Hounsou Keep Hope, and Themselves, Alive
summary_short: In this sci-fi film set in an underground missile silo, the actions of two men could decide the fate of civilization.

headline: Review: ‘The Gift,’ a Stalker Thriller That Isn’t What It Seems
summary_short: Directed by Joel Edgerton, this movie about a prosperous couple and their ominous new acquaintance takes several turns even after abandoning its formulaic premise.

display_title: The Diary of a Teenage Girl
headline: Review: In ‘The Diary of a Teenage Girl,’ a Hormone Bomb Waiting to Explode
summary_short: Bel Powley stars as a 15-year-old who candidly chronicles the passion, anxieties and adventures of adolescence.

headline: Review: ‘God Bless the Child’ Follows Neglected Siblings at Play
summary_short: Robert Machoian and Rodrigo Ojeda-Beck’s drama creates a seemingly oblivious world of make-believe, goofing off and hanging out after a mother distressingly drives off.

headline: Review: ‘The Runner’ Stars Nicolas Cage as a Politician After an Oil Spill
summary_short: Written and directed by Austin Stark, this movie follows a Louisiana congressman trying to clean up his life after the Deepwater Horizon catastrophe.

headline: Review: ‘Ricki and the Flash’ Puts Meryl Streep Behind a Telecaster
summary_short: Diablo Cody wrote and Jonathan Demme directed this film about a rocker who returns to mend a crisis in the family she abandoned.

headline: Review: ‘Kahlil Gibran’s The Prophet’ Turns Essays Into a Family Movie
summary_short: This animated film, based on a volume of poetic writings by that early-20th-century Lebanese writer, is determined to sanctify its subject.

headline: Review: In ‘Sneakerheadz,’ an Obsession Over Something More Than Footwear
summary_short: This fans-only documentary about sneaker enthusiasts draws connections among style, sports and popular culture.

headline: Review: In ‘Cop Car,’ a Joyride by 2 Runaway Boys Takes a Wrong Turn
summary_short: Jon Watts’s film, in its self-consciousness and breezy, instrumental violence, ambitiously announces itself as the latest spawn of neo-exploitation artists like Quentin Tarantino.

headline: Review: ‘Fantastic Four,’ the Reboot (Wanted or Not)
summary_short: Directed by Josh Trank, this reframing of the Marvel Comics superhero group features Miles Teller, Kate Mara, Michael B. Jordan and Jamie Bell.

headline: Review: ‘Call Me Lucky,’ About the Comedian-Activist Barry Crimmins
summary_short: Bobcat Goldthwait’s documentary about his mentor chronicles the work he has done not only as a comic but also to rid the Internet of child pornography.

headline: Review: ‘Assassination,’ With Twists and Hired Guns in 1930s Seoul and Shanghai
summary_short: This historical drama, written and directed by Choi Dong-hoon, is set mainly in the 1930s, when Korea was chafing under Japanese occupation.

headline: Review: In ‘Shaun the Sheep Movie,’ a Flock Heads to the City to Find Its Farmer
summary_short: In this stop-motion animation film, from the studio that made “Wallace & Gromit,” the sheep run into trouble in their urban adventure.

headline: Review: Woody Allen’s ‘Irrational Man’ Explores Life’s Randomness
summary_short: Joaquin Phoenix stars as a college philosophy professor who capriciously decides to commit a crime.

display_title: The Life and Crimes of Doris Payne
headline: Such a Charming Old Lady, but Hide Your Diamonds
summary_short: The documentary “The Life & Crimes of Doris Payne” tells the story of a career criminal, a jewel thief now in her 80s, who pretends to be one of the rich in order to steal from them.

display_title: Drunk Stoned Brilliant Dead: The Story of the National Lampoon
headline: Review: The Good Old Tasteless Days in ‘Drunk Stoned Brilliant Dead’
summary_short: Douglas Tirola’s documentary about The National Lampoon brings back the 1970s, when “We’ll kill this dog” was an acceptable magazine cover line.

headline: Review: ‘Mission to Lars’ Follows Siblings’ Quest to Fulfill Their Disabled Brother’s Dream
summary_short: This documentary focuses on a man with fragile X syndrome whose lifelong wish has been to meet Lars Ulrich, the drummer for Metallica.

headline: Review: ‘Finders Keepers’ Finds Humor and Humanity in the Bizarre
summary_short: This custody battle between an amputee and the man who unwittingly bought his leg is as authentic as the North Carolina vernacular in which it unfolds.

headline: Review: ‘Wildlike’ Pits a Teenage Girl Against the Alaskan Wilderness
summary_short: Frank Hall Green’s film stars Ella Purnell as a 14-year-old escaping a sexually abusive uncle, and Bruce Greenwood as a backpacker who helps.

headline: Review: In ‘The Intern,’ She’s the Boss, but He’s the Star
summary_short: Robert De Niro plays Ben, a gentle father figure who comes equipped with a laundered handkerchief, in Nancy Meyers’s latest film.

headline: Review: In ‘The Keeping Room,’ 3 Women Under Siege in the Civil War
summary_short: The British director Daniel Barber labors to impress in this Southern period thriller with two Union soldiers preying on two sisters and a slave.

headline: Review: In ‘The Green Inferno,’ Eli Roth Turns Collegians Into Prey
summary_short: This film, set in the Peruvian Amazon, revisits the cannibal subgenre whose heyday was in the 1970s and ’80s.

headline: Review: In ‘Sleepless in New York,’ the Misery of the Lovelorn
summary_short: This documentary introduces three city dwellers who are reeling from breakups, with general commentary on lovesickness from a biological anthropologist.

headline: Review: In ‘Pay the Ghost,’ Nicolas Cage Is on a Mission
summary_short: In this film, Mr. Cage’s character searches for his son after the boy is abducted at a Halloween carnival.

headline: Review: In ‘Hotel Transylvania 2,’ Dracula Yearns for a Little Monster of a Grandson
summary_short: In this sequel, Dracula’s daughter has married a human and begotten a son, and her father worries that the boy may not be vampirish enough.

headline: Review: ‘Ashby’ Pairs a Retired C.I.A. Killer With a High School Nerd
summary_short: Mickey Rourke stars as the former assassin and Nat Wolff as the student who wants to hear his life story in this semicomic film from Tony McNamara.

display_title: A Brave Heart: The Lizzie Velasquez Story
headline: Review: ‘A Brave Heart: The Lizzie Velasquez Story,’ One Woman’s Push for Acceptance
summary_short: Sara Hirsh Bordo, directing her first feature, keeps the scenes bright and fast-moving, but several important topics about Ms. Velasquez are are barely addressed.

headline: Review: ‘Stonewall’ Doesn’t Distinguish Between Facts and Fiction
summary_short: Roland Emmerich’s film wants to be as specific as possible in reconstructing the Stonewall riots, but it also wants to be sweeping social allegory.

headline: Review: ‘Uncle John’ Is Steeped in Secrets
summary_short: The first feature from Steven Piet unfolds with murkiness and ambiguity.

display_title: The Man Who Saved the World
headline: Review: ‘The Man Who Saved the World’ Recounts a Cold War Near Miss
summary_short: This hybrid documentary centers on the life of Lt. Col. Stanislav Petrov, who was in charge of the Soviet early warning systems overnight on Sept. 26, 1983.

headline: Review: ‘Racing Extinction’ Charts the Slaughter of Vital Species
summary_short: From the makers of “The Cove,” this documentary centers on the slaughter of creatures for profit without regard for the environmental consequences.

headline: Review: In ‘Veteran,’ an ’80s Cop Comedy Vibe From South Korea
summary_short: The film follows an honest detective taking on the pampered, sociopathic heir to a family-owned business conglomerate.

headline: Review: In ‘The New Girlfriend,’ a Widower’s Secret Life Is Revealed
summary_short: The director François Ozon offers a serio-comic exploration of cross-dressing, gender fluidity and desire in his adaptation of a dark story by Ruth Rendell.

headline: Review: ‘Songs From the North’ Works to Understand a People and Their Country
summary_short: The director Soon-Mi Yoo looks to penetrate presumptions of North Korea in this film, a personal essay built on three trips she took to the nation.

headline: Review: ‘Some Kind of Hate,’ a Bullying-Revenge Slasher Tale
summary_short: The blood flows and flows in this horror thriller, featuring Ronen Rubinstein and Sierra McCormick as two kids — one of them’s dead — trying to get back at their tormentors.

headline: Review: ‘Prophet’s Prey,’ a Documentary About Mormon Fundamentalists
summary_short: Amy Berg’s film chronicles the rise and fall of Warren Jeffs, the leader of the Fundamentalist Church of Latter-day Saints.

headline: Review: ‘Olvidados’ Revisits Rightist Terror in South America
summary_short: This Bolivian film depicts a retired general who is haunted by his past role in the torture and deaths of leftist activists.

headline: Review: ‘Maze Runner: The Scorch Trials’ Pits Hardy Teenagers Against a Mysterious Organization
summary_short: In the second installment in this film series, the heroes find themselves in a desolate landscape where humans have been ravaged by a deadly virus.

headline: Review: ‘Everest’ Revisits a Fateful Adventure in 3-D
summary_short: Baltasar Kormakur’s film is a breathless, large-scale 3-D action spectacle about an ill-starred attempt to scale the planet’s highest peak.

headline: Review: ‘Cooties,’ Back to School With Zombies and Gore
summary_short: Tainted chicken nuggets in the cafeteria lead to a blood bath as teachers battle an undead uprising.

headline: Review: In ‘Black Mass,’ Johnny Depp Is the Dead-Eyed Killer Whitey Bulger
summary_short: Scott Cooper’s film conjures a highly familiar gangster world of gamy characters, whackings and splattered brains.

headline: Review: ‘The Fool’ Is Yuri Bykov’s Look at Corruption
summary_short: In this film, Mr. Bykov’s main character is frustrated after noticing a structural flaw that could lead to a building’s collapse.

headline: Review: ‘Pawn Sacrifice,’ Another Take on the Royal Game
summary_short: Edward Zwick directs this film interpretation of the superpowers’ chess battle waged by Bobby Fischer and Boris Spassky in 1972.

headline: Review: In ‘The Perfect Guy,’ a Stalker Is Stirred
summary_short: Michael Ealy plays a computer-security analyst and Sanaa Lathan the object of desire he just can’t quit in this thriller directed by David M. Rosenthal.

headline: Review: Twin Terrors Haunt ‘Goodnight Mommy’
summary_short: When Mommy comes back from the hospital a changed person with bandages obscuring her face, her twins take action.

headline: Review: ‘Paul Taylor: Creative Domain’ Shows a Choreographer at Work
summary_short: Kate Geis’s absorbing new documentary follows a Taylor dance, “Three Dubious Memories,” as it takes shape in a matter of weeks.

headline: Review: ‘The Visit’ Is ‘Hansel and Gretel’ With Less Candy and More Camcorders
summary_short: M. Night Shyamalan’s new movie is one of those tales of child peril that have reliably spooked audiences for generations.

headline: Review: ‘The Beauty Inside’ Features 123 Actors for One Leading Man
summary_short: This quirky romance from South Korea is about a life that begins each day in a different body.

headline: Review: ‘Listening,’ a World Where Your Thoughts Are Not Your Own
summary_short: Khalil Sullins directed this techno-paranoia fable about mind control and hard-wired telepathy.

headline: Review: In ‘Meet the Patels,’ a Son Submits to a Marriage Quest
summary_short: In this documentary, the wisecracking son of Indian-born parents agrees to look for a spouse with a similar background.

headline: Review: ‘Breathe,’ the Story of a Scary Teenage Romance
summary_short: This movie by Mélanie Laurent conveys insight into the psychology of late adolescence, when childhood fantasies can combust with adult sexuality.

headline: Review: ‘A Brilliant Young Mind’ Facing Infinite Obstacles
summary_short: A young mathematical genius played by Asa Butterfield struggles with his autism and the aftermath of his father’s death.

headline: Review: ‘90 Minutes in Heaven,’ Then a Long Road Back
summary_short: This movie, based on a best-selling memoir, dwells on the physical and spiritual recovery of Don Piper, a Texas pastor who was declared dead in a car crash.

headline: Review: In ‘Blind,’ Perception and Fantasy Converge in a Writer’s Mind
summary_short: A Norwegian woman who recently lost her sight struggles to keep in touch with the visual world in Eskil Vogt’s debut feature.

headline: Review: ‘The Transporter Refueled’ Has a New Guy Behind the Wheel
summary_short: Jason Statham sits out the fourth installment of this series, and the main returning cast member is a souped-up Audi.

headline: Review: In ‘Contracted: Phase II’ Misfortune Multiples an Encounter at a Time
summary_short: This splatterfest directed by Josh Forbes wastes no time picking up where 2013’s “Contracted” left off.

headline: Review: ‘Dragon Blade’ Features Jackie Chan, Romans and a Lot of Mayhem
summary_short: This eyeball-popping extravaganza features Jackie Chan, John Cusack, Adrien Brody and lots of horse-riding extras.

headline: Review: ‘Dirty Weekend,’ Neil LaBute’s Tale of an Unexpected Layover
summary_short: Matthew Broderick and Alice Eve play colleagues stranded in Albuquerque who try to piece together what happened the last time one of them was there.

headline: Review: ‘A Walk in the Woods,’ With Robert Redford, Is a Scenic Trek Spoiled
summary_short: Mr. Redford stars with Nick Nolte in this film based on Bill Bryson’s 1998 chronicle of hiking the Appalachian Trail with an old friend.

headline: Review: In ‘Grandma,’ Lily Tomlin Energizes an Intergenerational Road Trip
summary_short: Paul Weitz’s new film, centering on a feminist poet in her 70s and her granddaughter, is a comedy of conflict and solidarity.

headline: Review: ‘The Price We Pay’ Maps a Web of Offshore Tax Havens
summary_short: Harold Crooks’s documentary shows how the global financial system abets the growing concentration of wealth within a narrow minority.

headline: Review: ‘The Armor of Light’ Follows 2 Unlikely Allies Against Gun Violence
summary_short: This documentary depicts a white evangelical conservative and the mother of a black shooting victim in Florida as they press their case.

display_title: Scouts Guide To The Zombie Apocalypse
headline: Review: ‘Scouts Guide to the Zombie Apocalypse’
summary_short: In Christopher Landon’s horror comedy, three teenage boys and a strip-club dancer battle the undead.

headline: Review: ‘McCullin’ Captures a Photojournalist’s View of Covering the World
