summary_short: This documentary takes a plain-spoken approach to covering the career of Don McCullin, a longtime correspondent for The Sunday Times of London who has photographed strife around the world.

headline: Review: ‘Love,’ Gaspar Noé’s Romance Told Through Sex
summary_short: This fourth film from the Argentine director tells the story of a couple through physical encounters.

headline: Review: In ‘Our Brand Is Crisis,’ the War Room Goes to Bolivia
summary_short: This comedy, a fictional version of a documentary by the same name about the 2002 Bolivian election, mostly provides a stage for Sandra Bullock.

headline: Review: In ‘Hard Labor,’ a Brazilian Couple’s Unsettling Struggle
summary_short: The filmmakers at times evoke the ambient dread and decay of, say, Roman Polanski’s “Repulsion.”

headline: Review: In ‘Bare,’ a Bored Woman Takes Up Pole Dancing
summary_short: Dianna Agron of “Glee” stars as someone who flees a staid existence after meeting a drug-dealing drifter.

headline: Review: ‘Heneral Luna’ Is a Patriotic Biopic That Aspires to Epicness
summary_short: The film tells the story of Antonio Luna, who in the late 1800s led the Philippine Revolutionary Army during the Philippine-American War.

headline: Review: ‘Burnt,’ With Bradley Cooper as a Chef Fresh From Rehab
summary_short: In John Wells’s film, a bad-boy restaurant star tries to make a new start with the help of Sienna Miller.

headline: Review: ‘Paranormal Activity: The Ghost Dimension’: Goodbye to All That
summary_short: The lucrative horror series adds a specter to Christmas, and bows out.

headline: Review: ‘Tokyo Tribe,’ Sion Sono’s Hip-Hop Musical
summary_short: A near-future Tokyo is ruled by rival gangs that dance, run and fight in the latest film from this Japanese provocateur.

headline: Review: ‘The Last Witch Hunter,’ Holding a Grudge for 800 Years
summary_short: Vin Diesel has been doing battle with an evil queen since medieval times, and their animosity has just become nastier.

headline: Review: ‘Jem and the Holograms’ Are Shadows of Their Former Selves
summary_short: “Jem and the Holograms,” once an animated series, has been thawed out and refashioned into a movie.

headline: Review: ‘Extraordinary Tales,’ Short Films Inspired by Edgar Allan Poe
summary_short: This movie strings five animated short films into a curiosity of torture, murder, pestilence and madness.

headline: Review: ‘Difret’ Confronts Sexism in Ethiopia
summary_short: This docudrama centers on a girl who is taken in by a lawyer after being charged with murder for shooting a man who tried to kidnap her for the purpose of marriage.

headline: Review: ‘Crumbs,’ a Post-Apocalyptic World Clings to Pop Culture
summary_short: Ninja Turtles, Michael Jackson records and sports celebrities are the crumbs of civilization that hold what’s left of the world in thrall, in this feature debut by Miguel Llansó.

headline: Review: In ‘Rock the Kasbah,’ Who Cares About War When There’s Money to Be Made?
summary_short: Bill Murray plays a has-been music promoter in Los Angeles who finds himself in Afghanistan,placing a young woman on an Afghan TV talent show.

headline: ‘Jason and Shirley’ Reimagines the Making of a Landmark Documentary
summary_short: Stephen Winter speculates what happened behind the camera in the 1967 documentary “Portrait of Jason,” about a gay African-American hustler.

headline: Review: ‘Truth’ Treads a Perilous Political Tightrope
summary_short: “Truth,” starring Cate Blanchett and Robert Redford, looks back at a “60 Minutes II” report and its fallout.

headline: Review: In ‘Experimenter,’ Are They Following Orders or Instincts?
summary_short: In the intellectually playful portrait of the social psychologist Stanley Milgram, the director, Michael Almereyda, turns a biopic into a mind game.

headline: Review: ‘The Boy From Geita,’ a Harrowing Tale of Albino Persecutions
summary_short: Vic Sarin’s documentary chronicles vicious attacks against people born with albinism in rural Tanzania.

headline: Review: ‘Tab Hunter Confidential,’ About a Heartthrob
summary_short: Jeffrey Schwarz’s documentary charts the rise and fall of a onetime screen pretty boy.

headline: Review: ‘Mi America,’ on the Murder of Migrant Laborers in a Small Town
summary_short: This crime drama was written and directed by Robert Fontaine, who plays a detective in an economically distressed town with decades of wounds.

headline: Review: ‘Homemakers,’ an Ode to the Do-It-Yourself Ethos
summary_short: This jagged-edged indie from Colin Healey is about a wild-child drama queen who moves to Pittsburgh to renovate a house her grandfather has left her.

headline: Review: ‘Goosebumps’ Brings R.L. Stine’s Monsters to Life
summary_short: The bulk of this movie is a jam-packed pop-up book in the form of computer-generated imagery.

headline: Review: ‘Beasts of No Nation,’ a Brutal Tale of Child Soldiers in Africa
summary_short: In this film, written and directed by Cary Joji Fukunaga, the line between innocence and evil is thinner than the blade of a machete.

headline: Review: ‘All Things Must Pass’ Tells Story of Tower Records
summary_short: This documentary tracks the rise and fall of the Tower franchise and notes its influence on some of the biggest names in music.

headline: ‘Crimson Peak,’ a Guillermo del Toro Gothic Romance in High Bloody Style
summary_short: The horror and sci-fi specialist Guillermo del Toro explores a genre that has receded in recent years, adding gore, ghosts and smatterings of Henry James.

headline: Review: ‘A Ballerina’s Tale’ Chronicles the Rise of Misty Copeland
summary_short: Nelson George’s documentary delves into the talent and drive — and the career-threatening injuries — of American Ballet Theater’s first black female principal dancer.

headline: Review: ‘The Final Girls’ Looks Over Its Shoulder at Horror Tropes
summary_short: This movie proves that with the right actors you can make an amusing movie even if a lot of the ideas are borrowed.

headline: Review: ‘Steve Jobs,’ Apple’s Visionary C.E.O. Dissected
summary_short: The movie burnishes the image of Apple’s co-founder even as it tries to peek behind the curtain at the gimcrack machinery of omnipotence.

headline: Keanu Reeves, as a Cheating Husband, Endures a Comeuppance in ‘Knock Knock’
summary_short: The actor plays a father who succumbs to a pair of women on a stormy night, only to awaken afterward to find himself tormented by them.

display_title: Winter on Fire: Ukraine's Fight for Freedom
headline: ‘Winter on Fire’: The View From the Trenches of a Political Uprising
summary_short: This documentary by Evgeny Afineevsky captures the immediacy of the street protests in Kiev in early 2014 that resulted in the ouster of Ukraine’s president.

headline: Review: ‘Unbranded,’ a 3,000-Mile Trek on Wild Horses
summary_short: This documentary by Phillip Baribeau combines adventure and advocacy, following four recent Texas A&M graduates on a ride from Mexico to Canada.

headline: Review: Stephen Daldry’s ‘Trash’ Is in the ‘Slumdog Millionaire’ Vein, With Sugar
summary_short: A coming-of-age story with a political twist, set against the backdrop of a colorful garbage dump.

headline: Review: ‘Short Skin,’ an Anatomical Sex Comedy
summary_short: Duccio Chiarini’s film follows the plight of a 17-year-old boy with phimosis, which stands in the way of acting on his libido.

headline: Review: ‘Pan’ Proposes Peter and Captain Hook’s Origin Stories
summary_short: Hugh Jackman, Rooney Mara, Garrett Hedlund and Levi Miller star in Joe Wright’s take on how and why a certain orphan ended up in Neverland.

headline: Review: In Takashi Miike’s ‘Yakuza Apocalypse,’ Blood and Fur Flies
summary_short: This Maximalist plotter of chaos smashes together yakuza gangsters and vampires in his latest comic adventure.

headline: Review: In ‘Dukhtar,’ a Mother and Daughter’s Dangerous Dash for Freedom
summary_short: In Afia Serena Nathaniel’s directorial debut, a Pakistani woman and her 10-year-old take to the road to escape plans for the child to be wed to an adult.

headline: Review: ‘A Woman Like Me,’ About Grappling With Terminal Illness
summary_short: Dying of cancer, the director Alex Sichel kept a video diary while creating a fictional account of her treatment.

headline: Review: ‘A Faster Horse’ Tells the Ford Mustang’s Story
summary_short: This film celebrates the 50th anniversary of the car, from its mid-1960s beginnings to today.

headline: Review: ‘(T)error’ Documentary Follows an Informant in an F.B.I. Inquiry
summary_short: This documentary raises questions about the agency’s methods, as an informant is told to persist with an inquiry after he concludes that its target is not a serious threat.

headline: Review: ‘Talvar,’ With Irrfan Khan, Depicts a Double Murder’s Muddied Waters
summary_short: Meghna Gulzar’s film is a fictionalized account of a sensational true-life crime in India.

headline: Review: In ‘The Martian,’ Marooned but Not Alone
summary_short: Matt Damon plays a stranded astronaut scrambling to stay alive and return to Earth in this science-fiction thriller by Ridley Scott.

headline: Review: ‘Shout Gladi Gladi,’ on the Fight to Curb Fistula
summary_short: Meryl Streep narrates this documentary about a devastating medical problem among African women.

headline: Review: ‘Partisan,’ Training Assassins Without a Cause
summary_short: Vincent Cassell stars in Ariel Kleiman’s film as a cult leader fighting unspecified outsiders.

headline: Review: In ‘Shanghai,’ John Cusack Is a Naval Intelligence Operative in a Bind
summary_short: Mr. Cusack plays an operative in this espionage thriller set in the 1940s.

headline: Review: In ‘Deathgasm,’ Listening to Heavy Metal Has Nasty Consequences
summary_short: Jason Lei Howden’s gory film centers on a town where residents are inadvertently turned into demons by a teenage band’s music.

headline: Review: ‘Brand: A Second Coming’ Allows a Comedian to Be Serious
summary_short: Russell Brand, the subject of this documentary by Ondi Timoner, champions global revolution and declares himself ready to lead it.

headline: Review: ‘A Christmas Horror Story,’ for the Gory Faithful
summary_short: Three directors combine to make this addition to the scary-holiday-movie genre, which includes William Shatner as a Christmas Eve D.J.

headline: Review: ‘The Walk’ Captures High-Wire Bravado at World Trade Center
summary_short: Robert Zemeckis restages the tightrope journey that Philippe Petit (Joseph Gordon-Levitt) took between the twin towers in 1974.

headline: In ‘99 Homes,’ a Man Buffeted and Then Manipulated in Florida’s Foreclosure Disaster
summary_short: Ramin Bahrani’s tale is on one level a fable about how impersonal economic forces shape individual destinies.

headline: Review: ‘Sicario’ Digs Into the Depths of Drug Cartel Violence
summary_short: Denis Villeneuve’s new movie, which stars Emily Blunt and Josh Brolin, tries to paint a morally complicated picture instead of restaging a morality play.

headline: A Mission for Justice in the Face of Genocide
summary_short: “Watchers of the Sky” examines genocide and the work of the human-rights pioneer Raphael Lemkin and others to combat it.

headline: Review: ‘Olympic Pride, American Prejudice’ Recalls Black Athletes in 1936
summary_short: This documentary, directed by Deborah Riley Draper, brings racial inequality to the forefront in the Olympics held in Berlin during the Third Reich.

headline: Review: ‘TransFatty Lives’ Chronicles a Life With Lou Gehrig’s Disease
summary_short: A young D.J. and video-maker follows his struggles after a life-altering diagnosis.

headline: Review: ‘Iraqi Odyssey’ Shows the Arc of a Family and a Country
summary_short: In this documentary, the director Samir reflects on his family’s history and diaspora, by extension, the story of the family’s homeland.

headline: Review: In ‘Tamasha,’ Finding a Path to Love, Show Business and Adulation
summary_short: A Bollywood melodrama about a boy, a girl, storytelling and make-believe.

headline: Review: In ‘Submerged,’ a Limo Ride Hits Rough Waters
summary_short: Much of the action is underwater in this thriller starring Jonathan Bennett as a limo-driving bodyguard who must rescue a young woman from kidnappers.

headline: Review: In ‘Killing Them Safely,’ a Debate on the Virtues of Tasers
summary_short: This heavily researched documentary by Nick Berardini becomes a dense stew of words and death.

headline: Review: In ‘Karski & the Lords of Humanity,’ a Holocaust Spy
summary_short: This documentary by Slawomir Grunberg focuses on Jan Karski, who reported to the Allies about the Nazi campaign against Polish Jews.

headline: Review: A Whiff of Hidden Toxins in ‘Stink!’
summary_short: A strange odor emanating from the fabric of his daughter’s new pajamas leads a filmmaker to investigate the toxic chemicals allowed in consumer goods.

headline: Review: In ‘The Good Dinosaur,’ a Reptile Tends to His Human Pet
summary_short: Homo sapiens and giant reptiles co-exist in this animated, alternate universe version of Earth history.

headline: Review: In ‘Creed,’ Rocky’s Back, as a Mentor, Not a Fighter
summary_short: No. 7 in a series, “Creed” stars Michael B. Jordan as Sylvester Stallone’s protégé. It’s a rarity, A. O. Scott writes: “a terrific boxing movie.”

headline: Review: ‘Victor Frankenstein’ Recasts a Tale That Keeps On Giving
summary_short: This film, starring James McAvoy and Daniel Radcliffe, recasts a ghoulish story into something of a buddy movie.

headline: Review: ‘The Hunger Games: Mockingjay Part 2,’ Katniss’s Final Battle
summary_short: Jennifer Lawrence returns in the savior role in the closing chapter of this blockbuster series based on Suzanne Collins’s books.

headline: Review: ‘Mediterranea,’ African Migrants’ Perilous Trek to a Hostile Land
summary_short: Risking everything to seek a better life in Europe, two close friends leave West Africa to settle in Italy in Jonas Carpignano’s first feature film.

headline: Review: ‘Criminal Activities,’ a Crime Yarn With John Travolta
summary_short: Mr. Travolta plays a crime boss with a get-rich-quick investment scheme in this movie from Jackie Earle Haley.

headline: Review: ‘Secret in Their Eyes,’ a 13-Year Hunt for a Killer
summary_short: This remake of an Argentine Oscar-winning film centers on the murder of the daughter of an investigator for the Los Angeles District Attorney’s Office.

headline: Review: ‘Legend,’ Starring Tom Hardy as the Gangster Twins Ronnie and Reggie Kray
summary_short: Brian Helgeland’s film immerses viewers in the sights and sounds of swinging ’60s London, showing how the brothers capitalized on their strutting image.

headline: Review: ‘Kingdom of Shadows,’ a Documentary on the Drug War in Mexico
summary_short: Bernardo Ruiz’s documentary takes a front-line look at the grip of Mexican drug cartels from the perspective of three main figures.

headline: Review: In ‘The Night Before,’ a Search for the Holiday Party of the Century
summary_short: Seth Rogen, Anthony Mackie and Joseph Gordon-Levitt star as friends honoring their Christmas Eve tradition of holiday debauchery.

headline: Review: In ‘Censored Voices,’ Soldiers Reflect on the Six-Day War
summary_short: In a film by Mor Loushy, Amos Oz and Avraham Shapira revisit talks they recorded with Israeli soldiers returning from the conflict in 1967.

headline: Review: ‘#Horror’ Finds the Fear in Cyberbullying and Social Media Threats
summary_short: In this feature directorial debut by Tara Subkoff, girls neglected by their parents and obsessed with their cellphones fall prey to perils of the online world.

headline: Review: ‘Democrats,’ Chronicling Politics in Zimbabwe
summary_short: This documentary from Camilla Nielsson looks at recent efforts to put a constitution into place in that country.

headline: Review: ‘Prem Ratan Dhan Payo,’ a Bollywood Tale of a Prince-and-Plebe Double
summary_short: Sooraj R. Barjatya’s film stars Salman Khan as a decent and playful fellow who intervenes in the power battles of a royal family.

headline: Review: In ‘James White,’ Facing Adulthood With Uncertainty
summary_short: The title character, played by Christopher Abbott, grapples with his future while caring for his ailing mother in this Josh Mond film.

headline: Review: ‘The 33’ Recalls a Chilean Mine Disaster and the Men Who Endured It
summary_short: In this stirring and suspenseful story, trapped miners wait underground to be rescued, grappling with fear and bonding as brothers.

display_title: Steve McQueen: The Man & Le Mans
headline: Review: ‘Steve McQueen: The Man & Le Mans,’ a Documentary
summary_short: A look at the making of McQueen’s 1971 movie, “Le Mans,” about that 24-hour sports car race in France.

headline: Review: ‘Song of Lahore’ Chronicles a Pakistani Jazz Ensemble’s American Triumph
summary_short: This documentary, by Sharmeen Obaid-Chinoy and Andy Schocken, shows how the Sachal Jazz Ensemble got to play at Lincoln Center.

headline: Review: ‘Man Up,’ About a Romance With Obstacles
summary_short: The recently divorced Jack (Simon Pegg) mistakes Nancy (Lake Bell) for a blind date in this romantic comedy directed by Ben Palmer.

headline: Review: In ‘Love the Coopers,’ a Dysfunctional Family Sits Down to Christmas Dinner
summary_short: Diane Keaton and John Goodman play a long-married couple who have big news to deliver to the family once it gathers, in Jessie Nelson’s film.

display_title: Ingrid Bergman in Her Own Words
headline: Review: Here’s Looking at ‘Ingrid Bergman — In Her Own Words’
summary_short: This documentary by Stig Bjorkman blends Bergman’s copious documentation of her own life with reminiscences from relatives and colleagues.

headline: Review: In Fellipe Barbosa’s ‘Casa Grande,’ a Teenager Awakens to His Father’s Financial Ruin and More
summary_short: This Brazilian film charts a teenage boy’s journey from self-entitlement to a painful understanding of class privilege.

headline: Review: ‘Madam Phung’s Last Journey’ Follows a Gender-Bending Troupe
summary_short: Nguyen Thi Tham wrote and directed this documentary about transgender performers in Vietnam.

headline: Review: ‘The Peanuts Movie’ Curses the Red Baron in 3 Dimensions
summary_short: The question with this revival of a franchise revered by nostalgic baby boomers is whether it will resonate with today’s 7-year-olds.

headline: Review: ‘Sand Dollars,’ Unrequited Love in the Dominican Republic
summary_short: Geraldine Chaplin falls for a much younger woman while on a Caribbean vacation.

headline: Review: ‘Of Men and War’ Chronicles the Trauma of Combat Veterans
summary_short: This documentary, filmed almost entirely in a California therapy center, follows a dozen war veterans racked with emotional suffering.

headline: Review: In ‘Theeb,’ a Bedouin Boy’s Brutal Coming-of-Age
summary_short: Naji Abu Nowar’s drama, set in 1916, follows a young orphan, alone and unarmed in the Arabic equivalent of the Wild West.

headline: Review: In ‘Spotlight,’ The Boston Globe Digs Up the Catholic Church’s Dirt
summary_short: In this gripping detective story, a small group of reporters exposes the church’s role in covering up the sexual abuse of children by priests.

display_title: What Our Fathers Did: A Nazi Legacy
headline: Review: ‘What Our Fathers Did: A Nazi Legacy’
summary_short: In this documentary, Philippe Sands, a human-rights lawyer who lost members of his family in the Holocaust, retraces the history of two men.

headline: Review: In ‘The Nightingale,’ the Beauties of Rural China
summary_short: Philippe Muyl’s film follows a big-city girl, her grandfather and his pet bird on a visit to the countryside.

headline: Review: In ‘Spectre,’ Daniel Craig Is Back as James Bond, No Surprise
summary_short: There’s nothing unexpected in Spectre, the 24th “official” title in the series, which is presumably as planned.

headline: Review: In ‘Palio,’ Sights and Sounds of This Sienese Horse Race
summary_short: Cosima Spender’s documentary focuses on the 2013 race and the competition between two jockeys.

headline: Review: In ‘Lost in the Sun,’ a Motherless Teenager Teams Up With a Petty Crook
summary_short: Starring Josh Duhamel and Josh Wiggins, this film follows the open-road adventure of a somewhat unlikely pair.

headline: Review: Bryan Cranston in ‘Trumbo,’ as a Screenwriter in a Hollywood Under Siege
summary_short: Directed by Jay Roach, the film tells the personal story of one of the Hollywood 10.

headline: Review: Resettling the Meaning of Home in ‘Brooklyn,’ With Saoirse Ronan
summary_short: This film about a familiar American story, the immigrant who arrives with dreams of the future and pangs over leaving home, explores the question: Where do we come from?

headline: Review: In ‘Among the Believers,’ a Cleric Holds Sway
summary_short: This documentary takes the viewer inside the Islamic schools in Pakistan run by the fiery Abdul Aziz.

headline: Review: In ‘Other People’s Children,’ a Woman’s Pain and Search for Artistic Solace
summary_short: A self-destructive filmmaker walks cluelessly toward her own undoing as she tries to make a documentary about people who live on the streets.

headline: Review: ‘Point Break,’ an X-Games Remake
summary_short: Luke Bracey and Édgar Ramírez follow in the footsteps of Keanu Reeves and Patrick Swayze in the updated version of Kathryn Bigelow’s 1991 classic.

headline: Review: Quentin Tarantino’s ‘The Hateful Eight’ Blends Verbiage and Violence
summary_short: Mr. Tarantino’s western tale of vengeance settles outlaws and bounty hunters around the fire to chat — until it’s time to start killing one another.

headline: Review: Jennifer Lawrence as a Modern-Day Cinderella in ‘Joy’
summary_short: In David O. Russell’s film, Ms. Lawrence plays a would-be entrepreneur surrounded by family members ogreish enough for a fairy tale.

headline: Review: In ‘Concussion,’ a Doctor’s Cri de Coeur Against Football’s Risks
summary_short: Will Smith plays Bennet Omalu, whose findings in an autopsy of a former pro-football player led to an epic clash with the N.F.L.

headline: Review: ‘Daddy’s Home’ Stars Mark Wahlberg and Will Ferrell, Playing Naughty and Nice
summary_short: A contentedly married man’s relationship with his stepchildren comes under siege when the children’s biological father comes back into their lives.

headline: Review: ‘Mr. Six’ Is a Guan Hu Character Study
summary_short: In this film, a former bad guy in Beijing has to figure out how to rescue his kidnapped son.

headline: Review: In ‘45 Years,’ a Dead Flame Threatens a Marriage
summary_short: Charlotte Rampling and Tom Courtenay play a couple whose union is unexpectedly complicated by the discovery of the husband’s long-dead former girlfriend in a glacier.

headline: Review: In ‘He Never Died,’ Mastering Longevity if Not Social Skills
summary_short: Henry Rollins plays Jack, who has spent centuries perfecting the art of being nondescript, in this enjoyably strange horror film.

headline: Review: Inside the Chef René Redzepi’s World in ‘Noma: My Perfect Storm’
summary_short: This documentary from Pierre Deschamps offers a closer look at Mr. Redzepi and his new Nordic cuisine.

headline: Review: ‘Son of Saul’ Revisits Life and Death in Auschwitz
summary_short: In Laszlo Nemes’s debut feature, Geza Rohrig plays a Sonderkommando hoping to bury a boy’s corpse rather than burn it in the ovens.

headline: Review: ‘Mojin: The Lost Legend,’ in Search of a Burial Ground
summary_short: In Wuershan’s film, three Chinese treasure hunters go digging in Mongolia and find a gateway between the living and the dead.

headline: Review: ‘Bajirao Mastani,’ a Bollywood Forbidden Romance
summary_short: A Hindu man falls for a Muslim woman in 18th-century India, in this film from Sanjay Leela Bhansali.

headline: Review: Amy Poehler and Tina Fey Come Home in ‘Sisters’
summary_short: Two 40-something women who never quite grew up, or grew out of their childhood roles, are at the center of “Sisters,” directed by Jason Moore of “Pitch Perfect.”

display_title: Alvin and the Chipmunks: The Road Chip
headline: Review: ‘Alvin and the Chipmunks: The Road Chip’ Features a Trip to Miami
summary_short: In this fourth installment of the series, the Chipmunks travel to Florida when they think their human minder, Dave, is getting too chummy with his girlfriend.

display_title: Star Wars: Episode VII - The Force Awakens
headline: ‘Star Wars: The Force Awakens’ Delivers the Thrills, With a Touch of Humanity
summary_short: J. J. Abrams, the director, turns out to be what this stagnant franchise needs: a superfan and pop culture savant.

headline: Review: ‘The Emperor’s New Clothes,’ a Documentary About Income Inequality
summary_short: This film from Russell Brand and Michael Winterbottom opens Wednesday, Dec. 16.

headline: Review: ‘Sunday Ball’ Visits a Soccer Championship in Rio’s Slums
summary_short: Eryk Rocha’s documentary turns churning legs and arms into a sensory experience that’s bigger on poetry than on clarity.

headline: Review: In ‘The Girl in the Book,’ a Young Editor Is Unsettled by Her Past With a Novelist
summary_short: Marya Cohn’s first feature stars Emily VanCamp as a publishing employee promoting a book that resurrects her painful history with a predatory writer.

headline: Review: In ‘The Big Short,’ Economic Collapse for Fun and Profit
summary_short: Adam McKay’s adaptation of Michael Lewis’s account of fund managers who bet against the real estate bubble finds laughs within the crisis.

headline: Review: ‘Boy and the World,’ a Colorful and Stirring Animated Journey
summary_short: Alê Abreu’s film unleashes the exuberance of a child on the harsh realities of Brazil today, with dark wit and satire.

headline: Review: In ‘The Tainted Veil,’ the Hijab Is Debated
summary_short: This head covering worn by many Muslim women is discussed at length in this documentary.

display_title: In the Heart of the Sea
headline: Review: ‘In the Heart of the Sea,’ It’s Man vs. Leviathan
summary_short: The film, based on Nathaniel Philbrick’s book and directed by Ron Howard, finds a group of men against one very angry whale and the ocean.

headline: Review: In ‘Dixieland,’ an Ex-Convict Is Sorely Tempted
summary_short: Hank Bedford’s atmospheric film, set in Mississippi, focuses on a man who is trying to make a fresh start but is nonetheless lured by the prospect of easy money.

headline: Review: In ‘Body,’ a Mansion Turns Into a House of Horror
summary_short: A holiday romp for three women goes wrong in this new film from Dan Berk and Robert Olsen.

headline: Review: ‘Don Verdean,’ a Sendup of Ambitious Pastors and the Lure of Religious Relics
summary_short: Jared and Jerusha Hess’s film stars Sam Rockwell as an archaeologist who finds himself in a quandary after a pastor asks him to track down Holy Land artifacts.

headline: Review: ‘American Hero,’ a Deadbeat Superhero, Forever Backsliding
summary_short: Stephen Dorff stars as Melvin, an absentee dad who has the power to move objects with his mind, in this movie written and directed by Nick Love.

display_title: Orion: The Man Who Would Be King
headline: Review: ‘Orion’ Tells an Elvis Tale
summary_short: Jeanie Finlay’s documentary tracks the Presley sound-alike singer Jimmy Ellis, whose career took off after Presley’s death.

headline: Review: ‘Dementia,’ Where Misery Is Company
summary_short: The titular illness is not the only disorder in the family of a Vietnam veteran who is recovering from a stroke.

headline: Review: ‘Bikes vs Cars’ Explores the Debate in Cyclist-Friendly Cities
summary_short: From a cabdriver in Copenhagen to an activist in São Paulo, Fredrik Gertten’s documentary presents a wide range of viewpoints.

headline: Review: ‘The Letters,’ a Biopic of Mother Teresa
summary_short: William Riead’s film follows this nun as she decides to work with the impoverished in Kolkata.

headline: Review: Sorrentino’s ‘Youth’: A Euro Buddy Film
summary_short: Michael Caine and Harvey Keitel, playing a composer and a filmmaker, look back on their long friendship from the perspective of an exclusive Alpine retreat.

headline: Review: ‘Macbeth,’ Starring Michael Fassbender, Awash in Gorgeous Carnage
summary_short: Justin Kurzel’s film suggests that there is a timeless quality to slaughter, raising questions about Macbeth’s guilt and freedom of will.

headline: Review: In ‘The World of Kanako,’ the Old Ultraviolence
summary_short: Tetsuya Nakashima’s film about a father trying to rescue his teenage daughter from the Japanese underworld glories in its lurid bloodthirstiness.

headline: Review: In ‘The Wannabe,’ Drugs, Money and Aspirations to Join the Gotti Circle
summary_short: This modest, assured and cautionary gangland character study starring Vincent Piazza and Patricia Arquette isn’t short on mob cred.

headline: Review: In ‘Krampus,’ the Holiday Involves a Demonic Santa
summary_short: A family, stressed over the holidays, unleashes the wrath of Santa’s “shadow,” a demon won comes “to punish.”

headline: Review: Chronicling an Outsider in ‘Almost There’
summary_short: This documentary from Dan Rybicky and Aaron Wickenden follows the story of Peter Anton, an artist in Indiana.

headline: Review: After the Terrors of the Blitz Comes ‘A Royal Night Out’
summary_short: In this fantasy directed by Julian Jarrold, two princesses escape, incognito, to commune with the joyful masses on the day Word War II ended in Europe.

headline: Review: ‘Hitchcock/Truffaut’ Revisits the Master of Suspense
summary_short: This documentary revisits a 1962 conversation between the two directors in a documentary format, with commentary from film luminaries.

display_title: Sound of Redemption: The Frank Morgan Story
headline: Review: ‘Sound of Redemption’ Traces Frank Morgan’s Route From Jazz Musician to Prisoner and Back
summary_short: N.C. Heikin’s documentary is less a thoroughgoing exploration of the saxophonist’s life than a fond tribute.

headline: When the Visitors Don’t Walk So Lightly on the Land
summary_short: “Gringo Trails,” a documentary by Pegi Vail, considers the impact adventure tourists have on the exotic locations they visit.

headline: Your Child Is Choosing a College; Time to Tag Along
summary_short: The romantic comedy “At Middleton” is also a delicate film about two people confronting their flawed marriages.

headline: For One-Night Lotharios, It’s Time to Face the Truth
summary_short: In the sex comedy “That Awkward Moment,” three best buddies make a pact not to be emotionally tangled with women, but then proceed to break the rules.

headline: Is It Love, or Stockholm Syndrome?
summary_short: In “Labor Day,” set in a small town in 1987, an escaped criminal takes shelter with a woman and her son and soon wins them over.

headline: He’s in Love, but No Closer to Figuring It Out
summary_short: The drama “Brightest Star” focuses on romantic relationships, using a young man as the focus.

headline: Thrilling to the Brrroom of a Renegade Cohort
summary_short: The documentary “12 O’Clock Boys” follows a youth through his initiation into a group of dirt bike riders who like to taunt the police.

headline: Everyone Wants a Piece of This Wandering Monster
summary_short: Aaron Eckhart plays a version of Mary Shelley’s monster in the new film “I, Frankenstein,” also starring Bill Nighy.

headline: The Holocaust Lives on in a Fractured Family
summary_short: “Papirosen,” a documentary by the filmmaker Gastón Solnicki, follows generations of his Polish-Argentine family.

headline: How Love Survives Altered Expectations
summary_short: When an Irish husband, father and craftsman suffers a stroke, his family, and an outsider, reflect the changed balance of the household.

headline: In a Teenage Snake Pit, a Chance to Be Trendy
summary_short: Every mean girl needs a gay male best friend; at least that’s what the teenagers in “G.B.F.” believe.

headline: It’s a Guy Thing
summary_short: A photographer who takes what he calls “fetish photos” is the subject of “24 Exposures.”

headline: She’s Having My Baby, Satan Croons
summary_short: “Devil’s Due” centers on a couple who discover they’re expecting a baby after a honeymoon outing that they can’t fully recall. Hmm.

headline: Sea, Sky, Spray and a Love Triangle
summary_short: “Summer in February,” directed by Christopher Menaul, focuses on a love triangle involving the painter A. J. Munnings at an artists’ colony in Edwardian England.

headline: These Criminals Are Throwbacks
summary_short: The animated feature “The Nut Job” centers on a gang of humans trying to rob a bank, and a group of squirrels attempting a heist of a nut store.

headline: Deception and Uncertainty Feed a Murky Justice
summary_short: In “Reasonable Doubt,” a prosecutor thinks he has committed a fatal hit-and-run and then tries to derail the prosecution of a man fingered for the death.

headline: You Have the Right to Remain Funny
summary_short: Kevin Hart plays a man aspiring to be a police officer, and Ice Cube plays a veteran on the force in this buddy cop comedy.

headline: One Good Man to Save the World
summary_short: Paramount reboots an action franchise, casting Chris Pine in a role previously played by Alec Baldwin, Harrison Ford and Ben Affleck.

headline: A Confused Boy Wants to Play, Even When Others Want to Fight
summary_short: In “When I Saw You,” a young Palestinian boy runs away from a refugee camp in 1967 and ends up with a band of volunteer soldiers preparing to fight Israelis.

headline: Wrestlers in Leather: What More Is Required?
summary_short: “The Legend of Hercules,” directed by Renny Harlin, has lots of abs and Kellan Lutz as the title demigod.

headline: Buying Peace of Mind With a Pistol
summary_short: After a violent mugging, a young New York woman moves to Austin, Tex., in search of peace and security in “Loves Her Gun.”

headline: Everyone’s a Drag, Except That Cool New Neighbor
summary_short: “The Truth About Emanuel,” a difficult teenager becomes fascinated with a mysterious woman who moves in next door with her new baby.

headline: Coming-of-Age in Wartime
summary_short: “In Bloom,” Georgia’s entry for the Best Foreign Language Film Oscar, tracks the lives of two girls in Tbilisi in 1992, during the newly independent country’s civil war.

headline: A Korean Who’s More Than He Seems
summary_short: “The Suspect” centers on a former North Korean operative who is on the run after being framed for the murder of his boss.

headline: No Heavy Lifting for These Gym Rats
summary_short: Were you longing for a gross-out comedy about fitness centers? Do you need to see more Fabio on screen? “Dumbbells” is here.

headline: Splitsville, a Land of Diabolical Lawyers
summary_short: The documentary “Divorce Corp.” argues that lawyers and courts collude to make divorces as expensive and drawn-out as possible.

headline: She’s Hard as Nails, He’s Noir and Nasty
summary_short: “Cold Comes the Night” pits a young motel owner against a criminal who takes her and her daughter hostage to recover a fortune in cash.

headline: It’s a Jungle Out There, From Snakes to Mine Monsters
summary_short: “Chander Pahar” centers on a Bengali boy who sets out in search of gold and diamond mines and confronts a cave monster.

headline: The Danish Prince and His Family Drama
summary_short: Bruce Ramsay’s “Hamlet” is set in an upper-class, buttoned-down home in postwar London.

headline: I Remember Mama, the Pot Smuggler
summary_short: A mother with two daughters finds work in Florida as a marijuana smuggler, in this semiautobiographical drama written and directed by Shana Betz.

headline: Recalling a Disaster Without Uttering a Word
summary_short: “The Great Flood” uses music and stark images to tell about the destruction and aftermath of the 1927 Mississippi River flood.

headline: Quick, Get the Camera: Fido’s Levitating
summary_short: “The Marked Ones,” the fifth film in the “Paranormal Activity” franchise, aims for a new market with the same special effects.

headline: A Cold, Appraising Eye, Spying Treasure
summary_short: Geoffrey Rush plays a supercilious auctioneer in Giuseppe Tornatore’s art thriller “The Best Offer.”

headline: Home Fires, Acridly Burning
summary_short: The word “acting” is inadequate for what the cast of “August: Osage County” is doing. It’s more of a thespian cage match.

headline: Soldiers Fighting, but Coping Most of All
summary_short: Mark Wahlberg stars as an American soldier in Afghanistan in a film based on Marcus Luttrell’s memoir.

headline: Disembodied, but, Oh, What a Voice
summary_short: “Her,” directed by Spike Jonze, centers on a lonely soul who is drawn out by the female voice of his computer operating system.

headline: Melancholy Odyssey Through the Folk Scene
summary_short: “Inside Llewyn Davis” is an intoxicating, somewhat surreal ramble through the Greenwich Village folk scene in 1961.

headline: An Old Town With New Problems
summary_short: “It’s Better to Jump” allows Arab residents to express their concerns about the gentrification of their city, part of which is a Unesco World Heritage site.

headline: You May Already Be a Winner. Or Not.
summary_short: “Nebraska,” Alexander Payne’s fourth film set at least partly in his home state, stars Bruce Dern, Will Forte and June Squibb in a comedy that gets under a cantankerous older man’s skin.

headline: Revelers, Pause to Meet Yourselves
summary_short: A bawdy college kegger has a possible extraterrestrial mystery in “+1.”

headline: Poignant in Tooth and Claw
summary_short: “Ernest & Celestine,” about a mouse and a bear, offers the childhood comfort of a miniature world.

headline: The Greatest Story, Retold
summary_short: Adapted from “The Bible,” a History channel mini-series, “Son of God” depicts the last days of Jesus.

headline: Eggs Over Easy, With a Side of Weird
summary_short: The hero of “Odd Thomas,” an adaptation by Stephen Sommers of the Dean Koontz novel, is a short-order cook who sees dead people and finds their murderers.

headline: An Unreliable Hero Aboard a Troubled Flight
summary_short: Liam Neeson stars as an unsettled air marshal trying to prevent murders in the air in “Non-Stop.”

headline: Waiting With Bittersweet Anxiety for Their Moment
summary_short: The director Stephanie Riggs follows the tribulations of three actors who are on call to step in for a star in a stage show.

headline: For a Kurdish Woman, No Way Out
summary_short: In “One Candle, Two Candles ...,” the heroine is pressured to marry a rich older man.

headline: Lava and Lust
summary_short: In Paul W. S. Anderson’s gladiator disaster film “Pompeii,” the lone survivor of a Celtic tribe becomes a slave, but his horse-whisperer talents helps redirect his fate.

headline: Down and Armed in Paris, Teenager in Tow
summary_short: In “3 Days to Kill,” Kevin Costner plays a much-put-upon C.I.A. assassin in Paris with bad guys to dispatch and child-care issues.

headline: Shedding the Cliché of High School Sex
summary_short: “Date and Switch,” directed by Chris Nelson, is a new entry in the high school movie pool.

headline: Demons at Work in Snowy Magic of New York
summary_short: The film adaptation of “Winter’s Tale” partakes of wide-eyed mystical wonder but pitches helplessly into ridiculousness.

headline: Fantasy Girl at Your Service
summary_short: In “Lucky Bastard,” a contest in which the winner is invited to have sex with an actress from a pornographic film has grim consequences.

headline: Once a Lowlife, Always a Lowlife
summary_short: In “Easy Money: Hard to Kill,” the second film of a Swedish franchise, a former glamour boy escapes from prison and tries unsuccessfully to eke an honest existence.

headline: A Couplet Fantasy Denied
summary_short: In “Adult World,” an aspiring 22-year-old poet takes the only job she can find, as an assistant in a pornographic bookstore, but persists in a fantasy about literary renown.

headline: With a Dentist’s Chair and a Chicken Mask, a Girl Can’t Say No
summary_short: “About Last Night,” a raucously entertaining remake, follows the difficulties faced by two couples, one sensitive and well behaved, the other outrageously naughty.

headline: Hellbent on Fusing His Soul With Hers
summary_short: “Endless Love, based on the 1979 novel by Scott Spencer, focuses on an all-consuming relationship between a boy and a privileged girl whose parents are deeply concerned about it.”

headline: Less Redemption, More Tears
summary_short: An ordinary man gets a new life in “RoboCop,” directed by José Padilha.

headline: Bloody Trouble at School
summary_short: “Vampire Academy,” based on Richelle Mead’s young adult series, uses many familiar themes of the bloodsucking genre.

headline: But You Can’t Deny Destiny
summary_short: In “Hasee Toh Phasee,” a wedding is approaching, but the groom has some things on his mind, including his fiancée’s long-estranged sister.

headline: After a Bad Breakup, Anything Goes
summary_short: “Love & Air Sex,” which follows two couples whose relationships have recently dissolved, is set in a city teeming with singles and air sex competitions.

headline: A Jumbled Journey Through a Curious Marketplace
summary_short: A pushcart delivery boy in Paraguay takes a job for a shady butcher, and chaos ensues in this film directed by Juan Carlos Maneglia and Tana Schémbori.

headline: Now They’ll Love Me, a Twin Sister Schemes
summary_short: “The Pretty One” stars Zoe Kazan as a pair of twins, one mousy and insecure, the other vivacious. When the popular twin dies in a car accident, her sister decides to assume her identity.

headline: Toying With Ideas Outside the Manual
summary_short: “The Lego Movie” flirts with flouting its marketing imperative even as it embodies it.

headline: Dreamscapes of a Nightmarish Conflict
summary_short: Jessica Habie’s “Mars at Sunrise” distills the Israeli-Palestinian conflict to a single duel.

headline: A-Team Tracks Nazi Plunder
summary_short: In “The Monuments Men,” George Clooney stars as an art historian who leads a quirky crew in a World War II operation to recover troves of artworks stolen by the Nazis.

headline: Aw, He Seemed So Nice and Sexy
summary_short: “Truth” focuses on a troubled young man who gives into his dark side after falling for someone he met on the Internet.

headline: In Soulful Devotion, Glimmers of Doom
summary_short: The animated film “The Wind Rises,” which Hayao Miyazaki says will be his last, is a poetic yet somber depiction of Jiro Horikoshi as a young warplane designer.

headline: A Miracle Drug or Quackery?
summary_short: Eric Merola’s documentary “Second Opinion: Laetrile at Sloan-Kettering” examines a disputed drug.

display_title: Double Play: James Benning and Richard Linklater
headline: Duet for Directors, in a Conversational Key
summary_short: The film directors Richard Linklater and James Benning chat about their shared interests in the documentary “Double Play.”

headline: Exploring the Blot on a Newspaper’s Record
summary_short: Samantha Grant’s documentary, “A Fragile Trust,” comes a decade after the fraud scandal at The New York Times perpetrated by the reporter Jayson Blair.

headline: A Rock Star and a Roadie, Brothers After All
summary_short: A scruffy documentary of the band the National’s 2010-11 European tour is less about the music than about left-field interviews with bemused band members.

headline: Facing Eviction, He Can’t Resist a Dare
summary_short: “Cheap Thrills” is a dark comedy about two friends who fall into a rough game with a wealthy couple they meet at a bar.

headline: A Boyhood Summer of Darkness
summary_short: Daniel Patrick Carbone’s haunting debut feature offers a dark vision of boyhood adventure in a great outdoors fraught with peril.

headline: Rain, Heavy at Times
summary_short: Russell Crowe stars in “Noah,” Darren Aronofsky’s adaptation of the Old Testament story, which brings blockbuster spectacle and narrative liberties to the story.

headline: Amid Chants of ‘¡Huelga!,’ an Embodiment of Hope
summary_short: Diego Luna’s “Cesar Chavez” reconstructs the emergence of the United Farm Workers organization in the 1960s and focuses on the movement’s leader, who died in 1993.

headline: Gang Wars, Iraq Warfare
summary_short: “Greencard Warriors” follows a family that will do almost anything for papers.

headline: Carnage and Chaos, Heavy on the Gore
summary_short: Arnold Schwarzenegger leads a gang of marauding Drug Enforcement Administration undercover thugs in “Sabotage,” and the bodies and bullets fly.

headline: Pursuing Sex With a Bad Boy
summary_short: “It Felt Like Love” considers the dangers of teenage desire through the experiences of a coltish 14-year-old girl who randomly fixes on a weed-smoking tough guy.

headline: Muppets, a Front for Bigger Schemes
summary_short: “Muppets Most Wanted,” an international caper, includes shots at Russians and the sly skewering of our European allies.

headline: Review: In ‘Divergent,’ Jolted Awake by Fear and Romance
summary_short: In its movie incarnation, Veronica Roth’s dystopian novel “Divergent” has high-stakes action, a gutsy teenage heroine who is an outlier, and romance between warriors.

headline: A Cop With a Secret
summary_short: Cory Monteith plays a street hustler in “McCanick,” the story of a cranky police detective (David Morse) with something to hide.

headline: Welcome Home. Just Avoid the Headgear
summary_short: “Awakened,” a thriller starring Julianne Michelle, follows a woman who has returned to her hometown to investigate her mother’s death.

headline: Returning, in His Own Way, to the Killing Fields
summary_short: In “The Missing Picture,” the director Rithy Panh uses figurines and the usual documentary devices to relay his personal story regarding Cambodia’s killing fields.

display_title: Tyler Perry's The Single Moms Club
headline: A Cranky Bonding Agent for Society’s Oil and Water
summary_short: Thrown together after their children misbehave in school, five very different women form a support group in “Tyler Perry’s The Single Moms Club.”

headline: Writing a New Romance
summary_short: In “Shirin in Love,” a young Iranian-American journalist who feels lukewarm about her fiancé rushes headlong into a relationship with the son of an interview subject.

headline: Preserving Culture in the Amazon
summary_short: “Xingu” tells how three brothers, hoping to protect indigenous people in the Amazon, helped create a sprawling national park in Brazil.

headline: Oil Money, and Where It Flows
summary_short: Rachel Boynton’s documentary “Big Men” is about the 2007 discovery of oil off the coast of Ghana and the perfect storm of avarice that develops around it.

headline: The Killer Online
summary_short: In “The Den,” directed by Zach Donohue, a graduate student researching video-chat culture witnesses a murder online.

headline: Fast Cars, and Racing for Revenge
summary_short: Aaron Paul stars in “Need for Speed,” a B movie based on a video game series that might be best seen at a drive-in.

headline: A Spelling Bee Bully With Decades on His Rivals
summary_short: “Bad Words,” Jason Bateman’s feature-directing debut, is a would-be gonzo comedy with a tough exterior and a marshmallow center.

headline: Where Performance Enhancers Are Legal
summary_short: A rather dull married pharmacist (Sam Rockwell) and a gorgeous, equally married customer (Olivia Wilde) make for an explosive compound in “Better Living Through Chemistry.”

headline: A Pakistani Fiancé Meets the Indian Parents
summary_short: In “Total Siyapaa,” an Indian woman brings her fiancé home to meet her family, a crew that seems more malicious than madcap.

headline: Bittersweet Chocolate on the Pillow
summary_short: On its surface, “The Grand Budapest Hotel” is a caper, but this Wes Anderson film is also concerned with a complicated slice of 20th-century European culture with some very ugly history.

headline: A Dog and His Boy Take a Joy Ride Through History
summary_short: A supersmart dog and his adopted human son set out for time-traveling adventures in “Mr. Peabody & Sherman,” the 3-D, big-screen adaptation of Jay Ward’s animated cartoon.

headline: The Glory of Rome, the Sweetness of Life
summary_short: In “The Great Beauty,” a sybaritic writer, now 65, considers the essence of Rome and his place in it.

display_title: What Is a Man Without a Mustache?
headline: Random Bits of Whimsy in Croatia in 'What Is a Man Without a Mustache?'
summary_short: Quirks of fate give shape to "What Is a Man Without a Mustache?," a pleasant if inconsequential romantic comedy from the Croatian director Hrvoje Hribar.

headline: Review: A Search for Meaning in ‘Garnet’s Gold’
summary_short: This documentary by Ed Perkins chronicles a search for a stash of gold, but also ends up telling a larger story about one man’s life.

headline: Review: In ‘The Hand That Feeds,’ Workers Rise Up at a Hot & Crusty
summary_short: This documentary chronicles labor organizing by low-paid employees at a Manhattan bakery-cafe.

headline: Possessed by Demons, and a Nutty Professor
summary_short: In “The Quiet Ones,” a professor and his aides experiment with a possible cure for a haunted young woman in an isolated house.

headline: A Female Cooperative Based on Revenge
summary_short: In “The Other Woman,” a comedy directed by Nick Cassavetes, Cameron Diaz plays a lawyer who learns that her lover is not only married, but has other girlfriends as well.

headline: Mom, That Fugitive Nazi Is Making Eyes at Me
summary_short: “The German Doctor,” directed by Lucía Puenzo from her own novel, imagines Josef Mengele’s time in South America and his interest in an Argentine family.

headline: Into Africa
summary_short: Sylvia Caminer’s “Tanzania: A Journey Within” documents a trip a young American woman takes with her Tanzanian friend, back to his homeland.

headline: A Rocket Is Aimed at Detroit (Run! Jump!)

display_title: Smiling Through the Apocalypse - Esquire in the 60s

display_title: Night at the Museum: Secret of the Tomb

display_title: Birth Story: Ina May Gaskin and The Farm Midwives

display_title: Walking the Camino: Six Ways to Santiago
