summary_short: In “Shanghai Calling” a haughty Chinese-American corporate lawyer gets his comeuppance when he is sent to China to work on a big deal.

headline: Threatened by Foe and Friend
summary_short: An arms deal gone sour lifts the lid on a rat’s nest of espionage for a North Korean spy who’s been left out in the cold in “The Berlin File.”

headline: Her Date Is a Single Dad; His, a Possible Killer
summary_short: The romantic thriller “Safe Haven” is the eighth film adaptation of a Nicholas Sparks novel.

headline: Ding, Dong! The Witch Is Cute
summary_short: “Beautiful Creatures” has sweet young things and supernatural shenanigans.

display_title: A Good Day to Die Hard
headline: When Action Is the Family Business
summary_short: Bruce Willis takes his fifth turn playing John McClane, this time in Moscow, in the stunt-loaded film “A Good Day to Die Hard.”

headline: Suburban Perfection, With Warts
summary_short: “The Playroom” is a drama about a seemingly ideal family in the 1970s that has several cracks below the surface.

headline: May Cause Greed, Lust or Retirement
summary_short: Steven Soderbergh’s “Side Effects” follows twists and turns involving a fictitious antidepressant (which has its own real Web site).

headline: A Woman Who Unleashes Her Inner Medusa on an Everyman
summary_short: In “Identity Thief” Melissa McCarthy plays Diana, who wreaks havoc on a milquetoast, Sandy Patterson (Jason Bateman), by stealing his credit cards and more.

headline: It’ll Be a Mixed Marriage: Just One of Them Is Alive
summary_short: In “Warm Bodies” zombie meets girl. Zombie loses girl. Zombie — well, you know the rest, though here the familiar balance comes with human tartare.

headline: Taking Back the Night, Slasher Style
summary_short: In “Girls Against Boys” men are pigs, women are sick of it, and revenge-fueled death and dismemberment pass for feminist critique.

headline: Bad, Badder and Baddest
summary_short: Walter Hill’s action film “Bullet to the Head” stars Sylvester Stallone as a contract killer in New Orleans.

headline: In Gangster State of Mind: Aging? Fuhgeddaboutit
summary_short: “Stand Up Guys” features veteran gangsters on a last rampage; you might describe the movie as a bad-boy “Bucket List.”

headline: ‘Coldwater,’ a Brutal Tale of Juvenile Lockup
summary_short: “Coldwater,” Vincent Grashaw’s first feature, is set at a juvenile reform institution in the middle of nowhere.

headline: Racing by Snowmobile for Economic Survival in Michigan
summary_short: The documentary “Northern Light” is a sneakily compelling, endlessly patient observation of three working-class families in the Upper Peninsula of Michigan.

headline: From Rock Album to Stage Musical
summary_short: The documentary “Broadway Idiot” observes the metamorphosis of “American Idiot” from record to stage show, and of Billie Joe Armstrong from rock star to stage actor.

headline: Disco and Villains in 1983 Bollywood
summary_short: “Himmatwala” is a remake of a Bollywood disco film from 30 years ago.

display_title: Tyler Perry's Temptation: Confessions of a Marriage Counselor
headline: Charisma, Wealth, Flattery. How Can She Resist?
summary_short: In “Temptation: Confessions of a Marriage Counselor,” a moralizing film directed by Tyler Perry, a bored wife succumbs easily to the blandishments of a wealthy man.

headline: Old Enough to See the Glass as Half-Full
summary_short: Children in India campaign for a proper water-delivery system in “Revolutionary Optimists.”

headline: Dealing With a Lot, and Nothing at All
summary_short: In “Somebody Up There Likes Me” a young man with little ambition has two constants in his life.

headline: Fighting the Peacenik Alien Within Her
summary_short: In “The Host” Saoirse Ronan seeks refuge from an alien race that has transformed most of the human population into smiling peaceniks.

headline: The Nanny Arrives; Eccentricity Is Squared
summary_short: In “Mental” a hitchhiker helps a man raise his troubled daughters after their mother is committed.

headline: The Joes Fight the Power
summary_short: Noise and heavy weaponry are major players in this follow-up to “G.I. Joe: Rise of the Cobra.”

headline: Is Domestic Bliss Too Much to Ask?
summary_short: Olesya Rulin stars in “Family Weekend,” a comedy about a high school athlete who tries to make her family “normal.”

headline: There’s Something About That Boy
summary_short: “The Croods” is an animated comedy about a Stone Age family, starring the voice of Emma Stone.

headline: Apocalypse Fed
summary_short: “Silver Circle,” directed by Pasha Roberts, is set in a post-apocalyptic world brought on by the Federal Reserve’s monetary policies.

headline: He’s Weary, but Psyched to Save Democracy
summary_short: In the “Die Hard” tradition, the lead character in “Olympus Has Fallen” is a world-weary professional battling evil amid pyrotechnics.

headline: Posthumous Salute to a SEAL Team Leader
summary_short: “Murph: The Protector” is a documentary about Lt. Michael P. Murphy, the SEAL team leader awarded the Medal of Honor posthumously in 2007.

headline: Alone in an Island of Creepy Kids
summary_short: “Come Out and Play” is the Belarussian director Makinov’s debut feature about feral children on an island.

headline: O.K., Class, Let’s Rock to Shakespeare
summary_short: In “Hunky Dory,” a drama teacher persuades her pupils to stage a rock opera based on “The Tempest.”

headline: She’s Not Impressed? Then You’re Not In
summary_short: Tina Fey stars as an admissions officer at Princeton in “Admission,” a comedy directed by Paul Weitz.

headline: Life-Altering Plea for Help
summary_short: In “The Call,” a 911 operator takes a life-altering call from a teenage girl who has just been abducted.

headline: Debauchery and the American Experience (Woo-Hoo!)
summary_short: “Spring Breakers” delves into a deeply American topic: the pursuit of happiness taken to nihilistic extremes.

headline: Lustful Pursuit of Sensory Overload
summary_short: “Vanishing Waves,” a psychedelic science-fiction tale, is a discomfiting blend of visual ecstasy and narrative sterility.

headline: Sleepwalking Magician Pulls a New Self Out of a Hat
summary_short: In “The Incredible Burt Wonderstone,” Steve Carell is a successful Las Vegas magician who faces a challenge from a take-no-prisoners newcomer played by Jim Carrey.

headline: That Man, Before the Curtain, and Before Dorothy, Too
summary_short: “Oz the Great and Powerful,” starring James Franco and Michelle Williams, is Disney’s prequel to the original story.

headline: A Blunt Instrument in the Climate War
summary_short: In “Greedy Lying Bastards,” Craig Scott Rosebraugh sets out to kick global-warming-denying corporate keisters.

headline: Plucked From Obscurity, and Now a Star!
summary_short: A young Filipino gets to live his Steve Perry dream in “Don’t Stop Believin’: Everyman’s Journey.”

headline: Dehumanized Souls Packing Noir Weapons
summary_short: In “Dead Man Down,” a thug with a secret past squares off with a disfigured woman seeking revenge for an attack.

headline: The Devil Wants a Sequel
summary_short: In “The Last Exorcism: Part II,” the victim of the first film in this series is in a house for recovering trauma patients in New Orleans when her demon again comes a-courting.

headline: With Friends Like These . . .
summary_short: “21 & Over,” the directorial debut of the “Hangover” screenwriting team, Jon Lucas and Scott Moore, follows an odd couple through a night of juvenile debauchery.

headline: Finding a Space, and Yourself
summary_short: “Welcome to Pine Hill” is about the different worlds that exist in a modern city (Brooklyn), and even within a single human being.

headline: This London Police Unit Will Do Anything
summary_short: “The Sweeney” follows Jack Regan, the leader of an elite London police unit whose tactics emulate those of the thugs it pursues.

headline: Disgraced Life Conjures Mysterious Forces
summary_short: “The Condemned,” directed by Roberto Busó-García, is billed as a psychological thriller inspired by either a drunken joke or a ghastly medical experiment.

headline: Below the Surface, Demons Personal and Political
summary_short: In “Phantom,” a Soviet submarine captain dispatched on a final cold war mission confronts a handful of K.G.B. radicals intent on deploying the sub’s nuclear missile.

headline: A Mighty Beanstalk Grows a New Twist
summary_short: “Jack the Giant Slayer” sticks with the familiar bedtime story, embellishing it with 3-D and other effects, noisy battles and an occasional wink at the material.

headline: A Family Not Quite on the Up and Up
summary_short: Truth is stranger than fiction in “Genius on Hold,” in which an inventor works with bookies and his son becomes a thief.

headline: A ‘Rigoletto’ Reunion Just Might Save the Day
summary_short: “Quartet” assembles a posse of lovable geezers in a palatial residence for aged artistes and entangles them in the mildest imaginable comic and dramatic situations.

headline: Journey Across a Wide Spectrum
summary_short: “The United States of Autism” follows Richard Everts, the director, whose son is autistic, as he journeys across the country to visit families affected by autism.

headline: About Those Visitors From Other Planets
summary_short: “Sirius,” a documentary by Amardeep Kaleka, seeks to induce government transparency about extraterrestrial life.

headline: Young Love, the Unrequited Type
summary_short: Terence Nance writes, directs and acts in “An Oversimplification of Her Beauty,” his film about the sweet romantic tension between two close friends.

headline: Dangerous Mission in Tight Quarters
summary_short: “The Numbers Station,” a spy drama starring John Cusack and Malin Akerman, unfolds in a concrete bunker.

headline: Coupling, Uncoupling, Dissembling, Recoupling
summary_short: A sex farce that centers on a wedding, with stars including Diane Keaton, Robert De Niro, Katherine Heigl and Susan Sarandon.

headline: Stripped of Clothes, Dignity and Maybe Shame
summary_short: In “Paradise: Love,” a middle-age single mother in Austria treats herself to a birthday trip to a coastal resort in Kenya.

headline: The Thick Have Their Needs, Too
summary_short: Michael Bay’s “Pain & Gain,” a more modest venture than his usual blockbusters, chronicles the true-crime doings of three Miami personal trainers.

headline: Ja, That Manly Raft Trip, Blond Manes a-Whipping
summary_short: “Kon-Tiki” dramatizes Thor Heyerdahl’s celebrated 1947 trip across the Pacific aboard a wooden raft.

headline: After the Apocalypse, Things Go Downhill
summary_short: In “Oblivion,” Tom Cruise is a repairman on a post-apocalyptic Earth who finds himself confronting a stranger-than-usual work order.

headline: When Small Appliances Misbehave
summary_short: The newest episode of the parody franchise “Scary Movie” mines “Paranormal Activity,” “Black Swan” and “Rise of the Planet of the Apes” for a few laughs.

headline: That Rookie at First Is in a New Position
summary_short: “42,” Brian Helgeland’s new film about Jackie Robinson, is blunt, simple and sentimental, using time-tested methods to teach a clear and rousing lesson.

headline: Young Man’s Wobbly Steps to Independence
summary_short: In “The Story of Luke” a high-functioning autistic man faces enormous changes to his sheltered life.

headline: Be Careful What You Wish For
summary_short: An ancient kettle with magical powers tests a broke couple’s bond in Ramaa Mosley’s modern fable about money.

headline: Remembering the Side of the ’60s That Wasn’t All Peace and Love
summary_short: Robert Redford’s “Company You Keep,” which also features Julie Christie and Susan Sarandon, follows 1960s radicals in later life.

headline: A Radical Beatified
summary_short: “Free Angela and All Political Prisoners” is Shola Lynch’s documentary about the scholar and activist Angela Davis and her 1972 murder trial.

headline: Washed-Up Artist Meets His Dark Muse
summary_short: “Eddie: The Sleepwalking Carnival,” a horror comedy from Boris Rodriguez, centers on a once-famous artist whose creative fires are stoked by his houseguest’s very strange habits.

headline: Good Intentions, Paving the Usual
summary_short: “The Place Beyond the Pines,” set in and around Schenectady, N.Y., is a tripartite tale in which the sins of the fathers are visited upon the sons.

headline: A Challenge in the Woods
summary_short: In “Kid-Thing,” a young girl with little social skill faces a situation that tests her judgment.

display_title: Free China: The Courage to Believe
headline: A Repressed Sect’s Ordeal, via Two Victims
summary_short: “Free China: The Courage to Believe,” directed by Michael Perlman, is a work of advocacy, calling attention to the persecution of the Falun Gong sect in China.

headline: Fate of the Earth Rests on a Banjo
summary_short: In “The History of Future Folk,” music-loving space aliens are on a mission to invade Earth.

display_title: La Camioneta: The Journey of One American School Bus
headline: Retired in America, Reborn in Guatemala
summary_short: The documentary “La Camioneta” follows the journey of a decommissioned American school bus as it travels from Virginia to Guatemala.

headline: Suspending Disbelief, as 4 Flee Handcuffs
summary_short: “Now You See Me,” directed by Louis Leterrier, follows the exploits of a criminal group of magicians as they are pursued by a dogged F.B.I. agent.

headline: A Father-Son Outing Goes Terribly Wrong
summary_short: “After Earth,” the Will Smith-Jaden Smith vehicle directed by M. Night Shyamalan, a boy and his dad crash-land on a planet that their ancestors ruined and fled.

headline: Do They Want to Go Faster? Yes, Indeed
summary_short: It’s a flipomania of cars when the boys reunite in “Fast & Furious 6,” starring Vin Diesel, Dwayne Johnson and Michelle Rodriguez.

headline: Tiny Folk in a Big War of Good Versus Evil
summary_short: “Epic,” a 3-D adventure directed by Chris Wedge, is a hymn to nature geared to families.

headline: Yet Another Road Trip, and More Roadkill
summary_short: Four of the unlikeliest on-the verge-of-middle-age buddies ever to join forces in search of adventure come together for the final edition of the “Hangover” trilogy.

headline: Nursing Home or Frat House?
summary_short: In Michelle Schumacher’s “3 Geezers!” old people are living it up in their golden years.

headline: Blood Despite Kinship
summary_short: “Aurangzeb” weaves Bollywood tropes — twins separated as babies, parent-child reunions, crosses and double-crosses — with contemporary outrage at the rules of the game.

headline: Hollywood Does Arabia, From A to B
summary_short: Michael Singh’s documentary “Valentino’s Ghost” looks at the intersection of Western politics in the Middle East and Hollywood’s depiction of Arabs.

headline: Just Us Girls, They Thought. Oops.
summary_short: In “Black Rock,” three young women decide to reconnect on an isolated island in Maine, only to find themselves running for their lives.

headline: Kirk and Spock, in Their Roughhousing Days
summary_short: In “Star Trek Into Darkness,” the U.S.S. Enterprise crew hunts for a terrorist in the latest film in the franchise.

headline: Playing Jazz in High Heels and Skirts
summary_short: “The Girls in the Band” tells the story of women faced with racism and sexist male musicians in the 1930s and ’40s.

headline: From an Unfinished Canvas, a World Springs to Life
summary_short: “The Painting” is an animated film populated by characters living inside an unfinished canvas who go in search of their creator.

headline: Shimmying Off the Literary Mantle
summary_short: In detail and dialogue “The Great Gatsby” largely adheres faithfully to F. Scott Fitzgerald’s novel, but Baz Luhrmann has colored it lavishly with his feel for the era.

headline: These Two Really Need a Vacation, So Beware
summary_short: In the comedy “Sightseers,” a couple of Britons take a sometimes violent vacation.

headline: How Not to Impress Your Girlfriend’s Snobby Family
summary_short: In “Peeples,” directed by Tina Gordon Chism and “presented” by Tyler Perry, an upper-crust black family in Sag Harbor, N.Y., has plenty of secrets to hide.

headline: A Night in Louisiana Can Be Harrowing
summary_short: In “No One Lives,” a gang of hillbillies attacks a stranger, who proves not to be an easy mark.

display_title: He's Way More Famous Than You
headline: After the Breakup, the Revenge Movie
summary_short: In “He’s Way More Famous Than You” a fallen starlet is dumped by her filmmaker boyfriend.

display_title: And Now a Word From Our Sponsor
headline: A Mad Man Someone Should Hire
summary_short: In “And Now a Word From Our Sponsor,” an ad executive is reduced to speaking only in slogans.

headline: Adult Head Games, Focused on a Child
summary_short: “What Maisie Knew,” an adaptation of the Henry James short novel, is about a young girl caught in a custody battle between her mother and father.

headline: Celebrating Conspicuous Consumption
summary_short: In “Scatter My Ashes at Bergdorf’s,” stars dutifully pay tribute to Bergdorf Goodman, the high-end Manhattan department store.

headline: Even Vegan Vampires Can’t Hold Out
summary_short: “Kiss of the Damned,” directed by Xan Cassavetes, introduces a strain of vampires who try to swear off humans and drink only blood substitutes.

headline: Bang, Boom: Terrorism as a Game
summary_short: “Iron Man 3,” with all its explosions so soon after the Boston Marathon bombings, underscores just how thoroughly terrorism and its aftermath have been colonized by the movies.

headline: Agony Eased by a Gentle Art
summary_short: “Free the Mind,” a documentary directed by Phie Ambo, explores how meditation and exercises can be used to alleviate post-traumatic stress.

headline: Plenty of Dust, Bullets and Relationship Drama
summary_short: In “Dead Man’s Burden,” a woman and her husband wring a living from her family’s parched homestead, watched over by the accumulating graves of her unlucky kin.

headline: Sex Stars as People, With Dreams and Worries
summary_short: “Aroused,” a documentary directed by Deborah Anderson, sets out to humanize female pornography stars.

headline: It’s Tough to Keep a Tune, but Easy to Fall in Love
summary_short: Mozart’s comic opera “Così Fan Tutte” inspires a subplot in the movie “1st Night,” directed by Christopher Menaul.

headline: Hiding From Trouble, Found by Innocents
summary_short: In Jeff Nichols’s third feature, two Arkansas boys discover a boat on an overgrown island in the Mississippi River, and also discover the leathery loner who inhabits it.

display_title: Levitated Mass: The Story of Michael Heizer's Monolithic Sculpture
headline: Surreal Journey of a Rock That Would Be Art
summary_short: “Levitated Mass” chronicles the transport of a 340-ton boulder through Southern California to a sculptor’s installation at the Los Angeles County Museum of Art.

headline: The Cultivation of Belief
summary_short: In his documentary “The Gardener,” the Iranian filmmaker Mohsen Makhmalbaf debates the role of religion in holy sites of the Baha’i faith.

headline: A Wedding Turned Nightmare (but Oh, the Video!)
summary_short: In “Breakup at a Wedding,” a bride gets cold feet, but the couple decide to go through with the ceremony anyway.

headline: Catskills Comedy Era Is the Focus of Documentary
summary_short: Jerry Stiller, Jerry Lewis, Jackie Mason and other headliners are featured in “When Comedy Went to School,” a documentary about the Catskills comedy circuit.

headline: When the Fight Came Home
summary_short: Billy Campbell plays a New York farmer who was no fan of slavery but against the Civil War, leading an antislavery firebrand to turn the town against him.

headline: Undying Passion, Despite a Sex Change
summary_short: In “Laurence Anyways,” a couple endure — off and on — after one confides to the other that he wants to become a woman.

headline: Cop Buddies, Packing Extra X Chromosomes
summary_short: “The Heat,” directed by Paul Feig, is a cop-buddy movie, but the buddies are women, Sandra Bullock and Melissa McCarthy.

headline: Wilted Spirits in an Abstemious Family
summary_short: “Petunia,” starring Christine Lahti, David Rasche and Thora Birch, centers on a therapist couple and their not entirely happy brood.

headline: Have a Nice Visit; Come Save Us Again
summary_short: Channing Tatum rescues the president (Jamie Foxx) and the nation in the action-adventure “White House Down.”

headline: A Protopunk Band With Bonds of Steel
summary_short: The music documentary “A Band Called Death” catches up with a groundbreaking punk group that emerged in 1970s Detroit.

headline: These Dead Don’t Walk. They Run.
summary_short: The love-scare affair with zombies is exploited yet again in “World War Z,” with Brad Pitt as the hero trying to save the world as well as his family.

headline: A College Where the Exams Are Terrifying
summary_short: Pixar’s “Monsters University” tells the story of how Mike and Sulley of “Monsters Inc.” met, became friends and learned to be really scary.

headline: Where Being Gay Is a Life-and-Death Struggle
summary_short: The documentary “Call Me Kuchu” chronicles the struggles of the gay rights movement in Uganda, and its prime mover, David Kato, who was bludgeoned to death in January 2011.

headline: Part Man, Part God, All Hunk
summary_short: “Man of Steel” weaves the Superman story into the fabric of 20th-century America and surrounds it with epic-scale cosmic effects.

headline: Elite Assassins Wield Spinning Blades That Slice Off Heads
summary_short: Andrew Lau, best known for the “Infernal Affairs” trilogy, goes back in time and dreams up new ways of killing in “The Guillotines.”

headline: Young Indian Slackers, Biding Their Sweet Time
summary_short: The Hindi comedy “Fukrey,” directed by Mrighdeep Singh Lamba, follows the tribulations of four young Delhi-ites.

headline: Twinkly Totems of Fame, Theirs for the Taking
summary_short: “The Bling Ring” was inspired by the true story of affluent Hollywood teenagers who broke into celebrities’ homes to steal luxury items.

headline: Whoa, the Apocalypse. We’re Still Buds, Right?
summary_short: In “This Is the End,” celebrity buddies find their relationships tested as biblical devastation arrives.

display_title: Évocateur: The Morton Downey Jr. Movie
headline: Fast Rise and Fast Fall of Television’s Tough Guy
summary_short: “Évocateur: The Morton Downey Jr. Movie” chronicles the rise and fall of this 1980s talk-show host.

headline: Four Go Over, but Only Three Come Back
summary_short: In “Wish You Were Here” two Australian couples go to Cambodia for a whirlwind vacation. When one in the group disappears, secrets about the others emerge.

headline: Young Girl Grapples With the Facts of Life
summary_short: In “Tiger Eyes,” the film version of Judy Blume’s young-adult novel, directed by her son, Lawrence Blume, a teenage girl deals with death, dislocation and sexual awakening.

headline: Review: ‘The Purge,’ Starring Ethan Hawke and Lena Headey
summary_short: In “The Purge,” with Ethan Hawke and Lena Headey, an America of the future allows crime with impunity once a year.

headline: A Criminal to Root For
summary_short: In “The Prey,” a bank robber escapes from prison to defend his family and his stash from a serial killer, and leads the police on quite a chase.

headline: Laurel and Hardy in Google’s Toyland
summary_short: In “The Internship,” set in a mock-up of Google’s headquarters, Vince Vaughn and Owen Wilson play analog guys thrust into a digital world.

headline: A Toast to the Stars of Mixology
summary_short: “Hey Bartender” is Douglas Tirola’s documentary ode to high-end mixologists.

headline: So Many Culprits in a Teenage Rampage
summary_short: “Hello Herman,” adapted from John Buffalo Mailer’s 2001 play, depicts a bullied 16-year-old who slaughters dozens of classmates and several adults.

headline: Nine Years Later, Once More
summary_short: “Before Midnight” follows the continuing romance of characters played by Julie Delpy and Ethan Hawke in the third film in a series directed by Richard Linklater.

headline: Two Lonely Souls in Temporary Shelter
summary_short: In “Stranger Things,” a young woman arrives in an English seaside village to clear out her dead mother’s house, and finds an unexpected resident.

headline: Blue-Hued Stepparents Enjoy Some Redemption
summary_short: Smurf essence is the elusive goal in “The Smurfs 2.”

headline: Some Things You Can’t Learn From a Book
summary_short: In “The To Do List,” Aubrey Plaza plays a smart and driven high school graduate who decides that she has been missing something and sets out to lose her virginity.

headline: They’ll Follow Their Pal to the Bitter, Senseless End
summary_short: Rowan Athale’s “Wasteland” takes viewers on a tour of a hopeless youth in the north of England before turning into a crime caper.

headline: Angst-Ridden Artist on a Mysterious Mission
summary_short: “The Time Being,” with Frank Langella as a dying eccentric, doesn’t really go anywhere, but provides pretty pictures along the way.

headline: Those Female Astronauts, Always Being Impregnated by Aliens
summary_short: “Stranded,” about a lunar base invaded by nonhuman visitors, has decent acting but awfully familiar elements.

headline: Claws and Heart Get a Workout in Japan
summary_short: Hugh Jackman’s ageless Wolverine returns to the screen, this time in the Land of the Rising Sun.

headline: The Ninth Circle of Law Enforcement
summary_short: In “R.I.P.D.,” Jeff Bridges and Ryan Reynolds are members of a heavenly police force that hunts dead villains and sends them to hell.

headline: Homeownership Has Its Perils
summary_short: In James Wan’s horror tale “The Conjuring,” Lili Taylor and Ron Livingston are terrorized by the bumps and creaks around them.

display_title: The ROMEOWS (Retired Older Men Eating Out Wednesdays)
headline: Feeding on Memories
summary_short: There’s nothing flashy about the subjects of “The Romeows” — Retired Older Men Eating Out Wednesdays — but what they’ve created matters.

headline: Frolicking in a Musical Metropolis Playground
summary_short: Romance, rivalry and urban fantasy unfold in “The Rooftop,” a musical action film that pays homage to everyone from Busby Berkeley to to the Coen brothers.

headline: They Lost Even Before Getting to Las Vegas
summary_short: Detectives charged with identifying the killer responsible for a clutch of bodies found in a derelict gas station in the Nevada desert seek clues on damaged video.

headline: In ‘RED 2,’ Retired Special Ops Agents Can’t Relax
summary_short: In the action-comedy “RED 2,” retired agents and mercenaries aren’t content to kick back; they load their guns to save the world from nuclear disaster.

headline: Scissors, Shaver and Salvation for a Young Barber
summary_short: The job of custom barber is a Colombian teenager’s ticket to a world beyond his poor family and rough past in “La Playa D.C.”

headline: Snail’s Pace Can Win the Race
summary_short: A snail who thinks he can do great things is supercharged by ambition in “Turbo,” but there is a trail of big commercial interests in the story.

headline: Youth League Tantrums, but Not by the Kids
summary_short: In “Dealin’ With Idiots,” Jeff Garlin lampoons the obsessions of adults with children on a baseball team.

headline: Narrow Space in Society, if Any, for Anonymity
summary_short: “Terms and Conditions May Apply” examines the repercussions of clicking on the “Agree” button on those dense (and typically unread) online user contracts.

headline: A New Year, and a Last Day Alive
summary_short: “Fruitvale Station,” based on the true story of a Bay Area black man shot by a white police officer on a subway platform, examines the subject with a steady, objective eye.

headline: Monsters, Machines and Mind Melding in a Race for the World
summary_short: In “Pacific Rim,” Guillermo del Toro’s new movie, the Jaeger manned robots fight the Kaiju monsters to save the planet.

headline: Political Brutality Sets a Running Champion on His Path
summary_short: This Bollywood biopic trails Milkha Singh from his military training through noteworthy competitions in the 1950s at home and abroad.

headline: Still Kids at Heart (Just Ask Their Wives)
summary_short: “Grown Ups 2” features many of the same former “Saturday Night Live” stars as “Grown Ups,” but they’ve moved to New England from Los Angeles.

headline: Coming of Age With Adults Who Haven’t
summary_short: In “The Way, Way Back,” two surrogate fathers dominate a 14-year-old boy’s days and fight, implicitly, for his young soul.

headline: If Thelma and Louise Were Belly Dancers
summary_short: In Rachid Bouchareb’s “Just Like a Woman,” Sienna Miller and Golshifteh Farahani take a road trip to flee their bad marriages.

headline: Comedic Soul-Searching, Punctuated by Pyrotechnics
summary_short: Kevin Hart’s new stand-up comedy film mines his personal and professional low points, as well as parenthood, for material.

headline: Hero Rides Again, With Big Boots to Fill
summary_short: Gore Verbinski’s reimagining of “The Lone Ranger” tries to give today’s kids their own version of the white-hat western hero with his laconic Indian sidekick.

headline: An Ex-Villain Returns as Mr. Sweets
summary_short: With its frantic, Looney Tunes-style madness, “Despicable Me 2” is consistently diverting and so cute you’ll want to pet it.

headline: Oops, Forgot Where I Hid All the Loot
summary_short: A bank robbery and amnesia are central elements of the Bollywood comedy “Ghanchakkar.”

headline: Turning Up the Voices From the Background
summary_short: The documentary “20 Feet From Stardom” seeks to rewrite the history of pop music by focusing attention on voices at once marginal and vital.

headline: Heady Times in Exotic Iceland
summary_short: Andrea Sisson and Pete Ohs feature Iceland’s natural wonders and Ms. Sisson’s philosophical ruminations in “I Send You This Place.”

headline: Horror at Every Turn of a Dark Cyberjungle
summary_short: “Disconnect,” with Jason Bateman and Hope Davis, offers a montage of overlapping stories about thievery, humiliation and exposed secrets on the Internet.

headline: Macroeconomics and the Little Guy
summary_short: “American Made Movie” pins the decline of the manufacturing sector on forces seemingly beyond anyone’s control and the hopes for reversing it on plucky individuals.

headline: Wandering Souls, United in Rebellion

display_title: Guitar Innovators: John Fahey & Nels Cline

display_title: Walter: Lessons from the World's Oldest People

headline: Taking On Broncos and a Plague

headline: An Old Flame Shows Up, but Who Invited the Witch and Monsters?
summary_short: Keanu Reeves’s presence is not the only Hollywood intrusion into a Japanese legend that is the basis for “47 Ronin.”

display_title: The Secret Life of Walter Mitty
headline: He Can Balance a Checkbook, but Not His Imagination
summary_short: In “The Secret Life of Walter Mitty,” Ben Stiller is an office drone with an active fantasy life.

headline: Old Resentments Come Up Swinging
summary_short: “Grudge Match” teams Sylvester Stallone and Robert De Niro as onetime boxing champions in an unlikely rematch 30 years after their last bout.

headline: Like Simba, Only He’s a Plucky Pachyrhinosaurus
summary_short: In the family-friendly film “Walking With Dinosaurs,” computer-generated creatures face conflicts echoing the “Lion King” story.

headline: A Dream Factory for a Benighted China
summary_short: “Personal Tailor,” a blend of comedy and satire, centers on a fantasy fabrication service that provides wealthy clients with a taste of the lives they have always wanted.

display_title: All the Light in the Sky
headline: An Aging Actress Faces the Mirror
summary_short: “All the Light in the Sky” asks questions about human nature, the march of time and global warming.

headline: Ron Burgundy’s Boob Tube Goes 24 Hours a Day
summary_short: Will Ferrell stars in “Anchorman 2: The Legend Continues,” a sequel now set in the 1980s and the era of cable.

headline: Amid Tortures Of the Flesh, A Naïve Crush
summary_short: “Paradise: Hope,” the third installment in Ulrich Seidl’s grim film trilogy, centers on an adolescent girl who is sent to a summer weight-loss camp.

headline: Special Matriarchal Lessons
summary_short: With “Tyler Perry’s A Madea Christmas,” Mr. Perry serves up his female alter ego in a holiday film.

headline: Guess Who’s Coming to Dinner. No, Don’t.
summary_short: “What’s in a Name?,” directed by Matthieu Delaporte and Alexandre de la Patellière, centers on a fractious dinner party.

headline: Big Hair, Bad Scams, Motormouths
summary_short: “American Hustle,” starring Christian Bale and Amy Adams, may be about a famous federal sting, but it’s also a love story.

headline: Good Heavens, They’re Atheists
summary_short: In the documentary “The Unbelievers,” the prominent secularists Richard Dawkins and Lawrence Krauss travel the world accompanied by a rock soundtrack.

display_title: The Hobbit: The Desolation of Smaug
headline: In the Middle of Middle-earth
summary_short: Part 2 of Peter Jackson’s trilogy based on the one-part “Hobbit,” “The Desolation of Smaug,” has lots of battles, an original character and Orlando Bloom.

headline: An Unbeliever in Disney World
summary_short: In the Disney movie “Saving Mr. Banks,” Walt Disney is — spoiler alert — a nice guy trying to win over the uptight creator of “Mary Poppins,” P. L. Travers.

headline: After Great Loss, a Sexual Feeling Comes
summary_short: As Christmas approaches, a woman manages mourning through experimentation.

headline: Warring Emotions Play Out in a Universe Torn by Conflict
summary_short: “Twice Born” features Penélope Cruz in a drama that uses the 1990s Balkans as a backdrop.

headline: Good Samaritan Ensnared in a Web With No Exit
summary_short: In the Australian thriller “Swerve,” a fatal car accident draws a passer-by into intrigue with a femme fatale and a briefcase full of money.

headline: The Singer’s Bohemia, and His New Legal Practice
summary_short: In “Live at the Foxes Den,” Jackson Rathbone of the “Twilight” movies plays a lawyer who quits his job to sing in a run-down club.

headline: The N.B.A. Prospect, After the Chance Is Gone
summary_short: The documentary “Lenny Cooke” traces the title figure, a basketball star whose supposed destiny never came to pass.

headline: Look at How Exciting My Life Is!
summary_short: In “Night Train to Lisbon,” a stuffy academic undergoes a late midlife crisis, impulsively abandoning his comfortable post as a teacher of classical studies in Switzerland.

headline: The Puzzle of a Past
summary_short: A young man’s trauma is the mystery of “Implanted,” a first feature from Thomas Verrette.

headline: The Trans-Korean Subterfuge of a ‘High School Student’
summary_short: In “Commitment,” a North Korean spy poses as a South Korean teenager.

headline: Fraternal Ties, of Gut and Sinew
summary_short: “Out of the Furnace” looks at the visceral bond between two troubled brothers.

headline: The High Road Through a Struggle Is Never Easy to Navigate
summary_short: “Mandela: Long Walk to Freedom” is a stately film biography of Nelson Mandela, starring Idris Elba.

headline: A Rampage With No Rhyme or Reason
summary_short: The documentary “Long Island Railroad Massacre” returns to the 1993 killings aboard a commuter train and catches up with those affected.

headline: FORCED MARCH (MOVIE)
summary_short: American actor cast in Hungarian film as Holocaust poet-martyr. Bit muddled, less dramatic than contemplative, never very articulate.
